{"title_page": "Steven Grasse", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Steven Grasse\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1964|9|19|}}\n| nationality        = American\n| years_active       = 1989-present\n| known_for          = {{hlist|[[Quaker City Mercantile]]|[[Hendrick's Gin]]|Tamworth Distilling|[[The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Steven Grasse''' (born September 19, 1964) is an American [[advertising]] executive, [[distillery]] owner and the founder of [[Quaker City Mercantile]]. Throughout his career, Grasse has cultivated an [[avant-garde]] image, and he was called the \"punk rock prince of small-batch spirits\" by [[Alex Halberstadt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foodandwine.com/news/steven-grasse-punk-rock-prince-of-small-batch-spirits|title=Steven Grasse: Punk-Rock Prince of Small-Batch Spirits|website=Food & Wine|language=EN|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nSteven Grasse grew up in [[Souderton, Pennsylvania]], as part of a [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mensjournal.com/food-drink/the-admans-whiskey-lab-20140505/|title=Steven Grasse Profile - The Adman's Whiskey Lab|date=2014-05-05|website=Men's Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> As a teenager, he worked for Indian Valley Printing, his father's company, while attending [[Souderton Area High School]]. Grasse was inspired by the work of English music promoter [[Malcolm McLaren]], and decided to study marketing and advertising at [[Syracuse University]]. He went on to intern at several advertising agencies before being hired by [[Saatchi & Saatchi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/philly/entertainment/20081210_Gyro_s_Grasse_says_he_s_no__quot_beast__quot_.html|title=The mad man of Philly ad men|last=Amorosi|first=A. D.|date=|website=Inquirer|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1989\u20132006 ===\nGrasse founded [[Quaker City Mercantile]] (formerly Gyro Worldwide), a [[Philadelphia]]-based advertising agency, in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phillymag.com/news/2010/01/29/legends-the-mad-mans-next-act-0210/|title=Legends: The Mad Man's Next Act - Page 2 of 7|date=2010-01-29|website=Philadelphia Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> In 1999, Grasse partnered with [[William Grant & Sons]] to create [[Hendrick's Gin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.1843magazine.com/design/brand-illusions/why-a-gin-maker-invented-its-own-history|title=Why a gin maker invented its own history|date=2019-09-06|website=1843|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Beginning in 1999, Grasse began producing ''Bikini Bandits'', a series of short films. A feature film based on the franchise was planned to be produced by [[StudioCanal]] but was later cancelled.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lacob|first=Jace|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/08/04/art-in-the-age-ex-ad-man-steven-grasse-s-wonderfully-weird-spirits|title=Art in the Age: Ex-Ad Man Steven Grasse\u2019s Wonderfully Weird Spirits|date=2012-08-04|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en}}</ref>  \n\n=== 2007\u2013present ===\nIn February 2007, Grasse founded the Coalition for British Reparations, and started a petition for the British government to pay US$58 trillion in reparations for damages he alleged the [[British Empire]] had done to the world at large. He described the petition as \"[[performance art]]\", stating that \"It's very serious, but very cheeky\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedp.com/article/2007/02/a_58_trillion_call_for_british_reparations|title=A $58 trillion call for British reparations|last=Heintz|first=Francesca|website=www.thedp.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Grasse authored the controversial book [[The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World|''The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World'']] which was published on April 23, 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Henderson|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3638156/Britains-many-gifts-to-the-world.html|title=Britain's many gifts to the world|date=2007-03-03|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Gyro Worldwide was renamed as Quaker City Mercantile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://phillyadclub.com/goodbye-gyro-worldwide-now-quaker-city-mercantile/|title=Goodbye Gyro Worldwide. . .Now Quaker City Mercantile|date=2009-06-12|website=Philly Ad Club|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> During this time, Grasse also began marketing his own brands,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Morgan|first=Adam|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RZO8BQAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PT211&dq=steven%20grasse&pg=PT211#v=onepage&q=steven%20grasse&f=false|title=A Beautiful Constraint: How To Transform Your Limitations Into Advantages, and Why It's Everyone's Business|last2=Barden|first2=Mark|date=2015-01-07|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-89945-8|language=en}}</ref> and founded Art in the Age of Reproduction, a retail store in [[Philadelphia]]. Grasse cited [[Walter Benjamin]]'s 1935 essay \"[[The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction]]\" with inspiring the idea behind the company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lacob|first=Jace|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/08/04/art-in-the-age-ex-ad-man-steven-grasse-s-wonderfully-weird-spirits|title=Art in the Age: Ex-Ad Man Steven Grasse\u2019s Wonderfully Weird Spirits|date=2012-08-04|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Grasse authored ''Colonial Spirits: A Toast to Our Drunken History'', explored the history of [[History of alcoholic drinks#The Thirteen Colonies|alcohol in Colonial America]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://attadrink.com/colonial-spirits-by-steven-grasse/|title=Colonial Spirits by Steven Grasse|date=2017-04-25|website=attadrink|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The illustrated book included historical recipes and trivia about the history of alcohol in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2017/01/03/507536826/a-survival-guide-to-colonial-cocktails-so-you-dont-die-drinking-them|title=A Survival Guide To Colonial Cocktails (So You Don't Die Drinking Them)|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/philly/food/20160922_Meet_the_Philly_adman_who_tells_you_what_you_want_to_drink.html|title=Martha Washington got tipsy drinking this cocktail. Now you can, too.|last=Melamed|first=Samantha|date=|website=The Inquirer|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Grasse founded Tamworth Distillery, a [[New Hampshire]] based [[Microdistillery|craft distillery]], in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/craft-distilleries-is-wilderness-to-bottle-the-new-farm-to-table|title=Is \u201cWilderness to Bottle\u201d the New Farm To Table?|last=Plummer|first=Todd|website=Vogue|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* ''The Good Reverend's Guide to Infused Spirits''. (2019) with Sonia Kurtz, Michael Alan. [[Skyhorse Publishing]]. {{ISBN|9781510739758|}}\n* ''Colonial Spirits: A Toast to Our Drunken History''. (2016). [[Harry N. Abrams]]. {{ISBN|978-1-4197-2230-1|}}\n* ''[[The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World]]''. (2007). [[Quirk Books]]. {{ISBN|1-59474-173-5|}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{IMDb name|id=1357842|name=Steve Grasse}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:American advertising executives]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Steven Grasse\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1964|9|19|}}\n| nationality        = American\n| years_active       = 1989-present\n| known_for          = {{hlist|[[Quaker City Mercantile]]|[[Hendrick's Gin]]|Tamworth Distilling|[[The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Steven Grasse''' (born September 19, 1964) is an American [[advertising]] executive, [[distillery]] owner and the founder of [[Quaker City Mercantile]]. Throughout his career, Grasse has cultivated an [[avante-garde]] image, and he was called the \"punk rock prince of small-batch spirits\" by [[Alex Halberstadt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foodandwine.com/news/steven-grasse-punk-rock-prince-of-small-batch-spirits|title=Steven Grasse: Punk-Rock Prince of Small-Batch Spirits|website=Food & Wine|language=EN|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nSteven Grasse grew up in [[Souderton, Pennsylvania]], as part of a [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mensjournal.com/food-drink/the-admans-whiskey-lab-20140505/|title=Steven Grasse Profile - The Adman's Whiskey Lab|date=2014-05-05|website=Men's Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> As a teenager, he worked for Indian Valley Printing, his father's company, while attending [[Souderton Area High School]]. Grasse was inspired by the work of English music promoter [[Malcolm McLaren]], and decided to study marketing and advertising at [[Syracuse University]]. He went on to intern at several advertising agencies before being hired by [[Saatchi & Saatchi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/philly/entertainment/20081210_Gyro_s_Grasse_says_he_s_no__quot_beast__quot_.html|title=The mad man of Philly ad men|last=Amorosi|first=A. D.|date=|website=Inquirer|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1989\u20132006 ===\nGrasse founded [[Quaker City Mercantile]] (formerly Gyro Worldwide), a [[Philadelphia]]-based advertising agency, in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phillymag.com/news/2010/01/29/legends-the-mad-mans-next-act-0210/|title=Legends: The Mad Man's Next Act - Page 2 of 7|date=2010-01-29|website=Philadelphia Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> In 1999, Grasse partnered with [[William Grant & Sons]] to create [[Hendrick's Gin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.1843magazine.com/design/brand-illusions/why-a-gin-maker-invented-its-own-history|title=Why a gin maker invented its own history|date=2019-09-06|website=1843|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Beginning in 1999, Grasse began producing ''Bikini Bandits'', a series of short films. A feature film based on the franchise was planned to be produced by [[StudioCanal]] but was later cancelled.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lacob|first=Jace|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/08/04/art-in-the-age-ex-ad-man-steven-grasse-s-wonderfully-weird-spirits|title=Art in the Age: Ex-Ad Man Steven Grasse\u2019s Wonderfully Weird Spirits|date=2012-08-04|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en}}</ref>  \n\n=== 2007\u2013present ===\nIn February 2007, Grasse founded the Coalition for British Reparations, and started a petition for the British government to pay US$58 trillion in reparations for damages he alleged the [[British Empire]] had done to the world at large. He described the petition as \"[[performance art]]\", stating that \"It's very serious, but very cheeky\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedp.com/article/2007/02/a_58_trillion_call_for_british_reparations|title=A $58 trillion call for British reparations|last=Heintz|first=Francesca|website=www.thedp.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Grasse authored the controversial book [[The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World|''The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World'']] which was published on April 23, 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Henderson|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3638156/Britains-many-gifts-to-the-world.html|title=Britain's many gifts to the world|date=2007-03-03|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Gyro Worldwide was renamed as Quaker City Mercantile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://phillyadclub.com/goodbye-gyro-worldwide-now-quaker-city-mercantile/|title=Goodbye Gyro Worldwide. . .Now Quaker City Mercantile|date=2009-06-12|website=Philly Ad Club|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> During this time, Grasse also began marketing his own brands,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Morgan|first=Adam|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RZO8BQAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PT211&dq=steven%20grasse&pg=PT211#v=onepage&q=steven%20grasse&f=false|title=A Beautiful Constraint: How To Transform Your Limitations Into Advantages, and Why It's Everyone's Business|last2=Barden|first2=Mark|date=2015-01-07|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-89945-8|language=en}}</ref> and founded Art in the Age of Reproduction, a retail store in [[Philadelphia]]. Grasse cited [[Walter Benjamin]]'s 1935 essay \"[[The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction]]\" with inspiring the idea behind the company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lacob|first=Jace|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/08/04/art-in-the-age-ex-ad-man-steven-grasse-s-wonderfully-weird-spirits|title=Art in the Age: Ex-Ad Man Steven Grasse\u2019s Wonderfully Weird Spirits|date=2012-08-04|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Grasse authored ''Colonial Spirits: A Toast to Our Drunken History'', explored the history of [[History of alcoholic drinks#The Thirteen Colonies|alcohol in Colonial America]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://attadrink.com/colonial-spirits-by-steven-grasse/|title=Colonial Spirits by Steven Grasse|date=2017-04-25|website=attadrink|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The illustrated book included historical recipes and trivia about the history of alcohol in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2017/01/03/507536826/a-survival-guide-to-colonial-cocktails-so-you-dont-die-drinking-them|title=A Survival Guide To Colonial Cocktails (So You Don't Die Drinking Them)|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/philly/food/20160922_Meet_the_Philly_adman_who_tells_you_what_you_want_to_drink.html|title=Martha Washington got tipsy drinking this cocktail. Now you can, too.|last=Melamed|first=Samantha|date=|website=The Inquirer|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Grasse founded Tamworth Distillery, a [[New Hampshire]] based [[Microdistillery|craft distillery]], in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/craft-distilleries-is-wilderness-to-bottle-the-new-farm-to-table|title=Is \u201cWilderness to Bottle\u201d the New Farm To Table?|last=Plummer|first=Todd|website=Vogue|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* ''The Good Reverend's Guide to Infused Spirits''. (2019) with Sonia Kurtz, Michael Alan. [[Skyhorse Publishing]]. {{ISBN|9781510739758|}}\n* ''Colonial Spirits: A Toast to Our Drunken History''. (2016). [[Harry N. Abrams]]. {{ISBN|978-1-4197-2230-1|}}\n* ''[[The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World]]''. (2007). [[Quirk Books]]. {{ISBN|1-59474-173-5|}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{IMDb name|id=1357842|name=Steve Grasse}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:American advertising executives]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steven_Grasse"}
{"title_page": "Narcoculture in Mexico", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2015}}\n'''Narcoculture in Mexico''' is a subculture that has grown as a result of the strong presence of the various [[drug cartel]]s throughout Mexico. \nIn the same way that other subcultures around the world that are related to crime and [[Drug culture|drug use]] (for example the Scottish [[Ned (Scottish)#Ned culture|ned]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2005/oct/20/penal.crime|title=Scotland's murderous heart|work=the Guardian|access-date=2016-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415203553/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2005/oct/20/penal.crime|archive-date=2017-04-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/3452275.stm|title=Extra police target 'ned culture'|publisher=BBC NEWS|location=UK - Scotland|access-date=2015-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023142725/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/3452275.stm|archive-date=2015-10-23|url-status=live}}</ref> and European [[hooligan]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://munchies.vice.com/articles/what-ive-learned-from-driving-around-drunk-tourists-all-day|title=What I've Learned from Driving Around Drunk Tourists All Day - MUNCHIES|author=Anonymous|work=MUNCHIES: Food by VICE|access-date=2015-10-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018024616/http://munchies.vice.com/articles/what-ive-learned-from-driving-around-drunk-tourists-all-day|archive-date=2015-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=85mxAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Football Hooliganism, Fan Behaviour and Crime|publisher=|isbn=9781137347978|last1=Hopkins|first1=M.|last2=Treadwell|first2=J.|date=2014-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/bundesliga-german-football-hooligans-use-crystal-meth-fuel-violence-1485073|title=Bundesliga: German football hooligans 'use crystal meth to fuel violence'|author=Mark Piggott|work=International Business Times UK|access-date=2015-10-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911221616/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/bundesliga-german-football-hooligans-use-crystal-meth-fuel-violence-1485073|archive-date=2015-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref> or the American street-[[Gangsta rap#Criticisms|gangsta]]s and [[Outlaw motorcycle club#Outlaw motorcycle gangs as criminal enterprises|outlaw bikers]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/4458/20131205/narco-cultura-how-mexicos-mexican-gangsta-rap-glorifies-drug-lords.htm|title='Narco Cultura:' How Mexican 'Gangsta Rap' Glorifies Drug Lords|work=Latin Post|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511233019/http://www.latinpost.com/articles/4458/20131205/narco-cultura-how-mexicos-mexican-gangsta-rap-glorifies-drug-lords.htm|archive-date=11 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Mexican narco culture has developed its own form of dress, music, literature, film, religious beliefs and practices and language (slang) that has helped it become a part of the mainstream fashion in some areas of the country, mainly among lower-class, uneducated youth.<ref name=\"Canalestrellatv 2011\">Canalestrellatv. \"Narcocultura part 1.mov.\" online video clip. Youtube.  Youtube, 15 Nov. 2011. Web 26 May 2013.</ref> Narco culture is dynamic in that there are various regional differences within Mexico and among those who participate in it.\n\n==Origin==\n{{Refimprove section|date=December 2015}}The origins of narco culture, like drug trafficking, had humble beginnings in Mexico. Narco culture emerged from the practice of drug trafficking in the highlands of Badiraguato, Sinaloa. It is in the sierra or countryside where an identity of drug trafficking was created and then consolidated once it crossed into the urban sphere. Narcoculture has been defined as a code of conduct and lifestyle for those that participate in the \"narco world.\"<ref name=\"OvalleMarroquin\" />\n\nMany scholars, like Luis Astorga and Jorge Alan Sanchez Godoy explain that there is no evidence that would suggest that [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] or [[opium]] were consumed in Mexico prior to the arrival of the Spanish and the Chinese {{Citation needed|date=December 2015}}. Although indigenous communities in Mexico consumed hallucinogenic mushrooms and [[Peyote#History|Peyote]] in their religious practices it was not until the arrival of the Spanish that cannabis was introduced to Mexico.\nDrug trafficking in Mexico has been considered by Luis Astorga, to have originated with the Chinese immigration to Sinaloa. It is said {{Citation needed|date=December 2015}} that the Chinese immigrants brought [[poppy seeds]] with them when they arrived in Mexico to work in the railroads and mines.\nSanchez Godoy explains that after cannabis was brought to Mexico, it was used for medical purposes and poppy plants were used for decoration and served as inspiration for several Mexican [[corridos]] or ballads.\n\n== Drug production in Mexico ==\n{{Refimprove section|date=December 2015}}\n\nThe US effectively banned all [[Psychoactive drug]]s when the federal government passed in 1914 the Harrison Act, prohibiting all non-medicinal use of opium, morphine, and cocaine. In 1919 The National Prohibition Act made alcoholic beverages illegal and The Marijuana Tax Act of 1937 outlawed marijuana.<ref name=\"isreview.org\">{{cite web|url=http://isreview.org/issue/90/political-economy-mexicos-drug-war|title=The political economy of Mexico's drug war - International Socialist Review|website=isreview.org|access-date=2016-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218202935/http://isreview.org/issue/90/political-economy-mexicos-drug-war|archive-date=2016-12-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMexico\u2019s proximity to the US made it an easy source and American bootleggers and traffickers rushed to obtain illicit narcotics and alcohol. Exports of Mexican opium, heroin, and marijuana for US consumption steadily increased as a result of Prohibition.<ref name=\"isreview.org\"/>\n\nThe [[black market]] grew quickly, with millions of Americans requiring a huge supply of alcohol, heroin, marijuana and cocaine. The initial shortage caused a boost in drug prices, and these new super-profits attracted black market suppliers to fill the vacuum.<ref name=\"isreview.org\"/>\n\n=== Expulsion of Chinese producers ===\n\nDuring the early 1920s, the Chinese in Sinaloa were victims of segregation, hate crimes, and forceful deportation. In 1927, to cooperate with its northern neighbour Mexican President [[Plutarco Elias Calles]], by federal mandate, ordered the expulsion of the Chinese poppy producers.<ref name=\"SanchezGodoy\" />\n\n=== US morphine demand ===\nOnce the Chinese were expelled from Sinaloa, the production of narcotics was then controlled by the rural Mexican farmers. The narcotics production in Mexico was still small,{{Citation needed|date=December 2015}} but the demand for [[morphine]] in the United States created by the disruption in its morphine supply from Europe during the World Wars led to the temporary legalization of narcotics in Mexico.\n\n===Mexican production and the birth of narcoculture ===\nScholars like Sanchez Godoy and Luis Astorga {{Citation needed|date=December 2015}} state that narcotics were temporarily legalized in Sinaloa in order to supply the United States' demand during the world war. \nThe period when the production of narcotics was temporarily legalized, shaped and created the drug trafficking identity in the region. This is when narcoculture first begins to appear. It is also the period when Mexico entered the large-scale production of narcotics.\n\n== The rise of the Mexican drug cartels and the consolidation of narcoculture ==\n\nThe 1950s in Mexico were marked by the term \"''narcotr\u00e1fico''\" (narco traffic) that began to appear in the media. During the 1940s through 1970s drug trafficking in Mexico was considered to be a \"small family business\" with a relatively simple organization and division of labor.<ref name=\"SanchezGodoy\" /> It is not until after the 1970s with the growth of demand from the United States and alliances with Colombian drug traffickers that cartels in Mexico were formed to control the production and distribution of narcotics. Mexico then became a producer and distributor.\n\nIn previous decades, Mexico served as the route of entrance for the cocaine arriving to the United States from Colombia. With Mexico supplying the United States with heroin and morphine during World War II, it became a producer. The alliance between Mexican cartels and Colombian cartels meant that Mexico was now a distributor and producer. As drug trafficking expanded in Mexico, so did narcoculture. Narcoculture expanded into the urban sector of society and began the process of legitimization and moved away from a subculture into a part of the dominant culture.\n\n=== Coining the term narcoculture ===\nThe term \"narcoculture\" was first coined in the 1970s. Narcoculture defines the way of life and ideas of drug traffickers. Its existence depends on the acceptance of drug traffickers and drug trafficking, becoming a transnational network of production, transportation, and commercialization of illegal drugs.\n\nDrug trafficking has political, economic, ideological, and cultural implications. Drug traffickers interact with the rest of society and as this daily interaction progresses, some of the drug traffickers' mannerisms are adopted by society and this leads to cultural change and legitimization. The drug traffickers' way of life or narcoculture becomes legitimate in the society. Some aspects are adopted by those outside of drug trafficking, and over time people forget that what they have adopted is narcoculture. Narcoculture begins a process of legitimization when it begins to include the popular classes in the urban cities.\n\n=== Rise of the Mexican Mafiosos ===\nNarcoculture in Sinaloa shares many characteristics with Mediterranean culture and mafias in that it is said that the Sinaloa narcoculture is based on honor, bravery, family loyalty, protection, vengeance, generosity, hospitality, nobility, and prestige much like the Mediterranean mafias. Drug traffickers use \"claves\" (codes) to maintain a level of secrecy. Some of these codes, however, have been revealed in ''narcocorridos'' (Mexican ballads about drug trafficking) and are then used by people who listen to this music, even if they are not drug traffickers. This is when narcoculture becomes a part of the mainstream discourse.\n\nPrior to the 1970s, narcoculture and drug trafficking in Sinaloa were almost exclusively rural. The stigma that was placed on narcotics early on meant that people in the cities were reluctant to accept it as a legitimate activity. In the countryside of Sinaloa, people were starving and drug trafficking seemed like the only viable solution. The rural population saw themselves a part of the marginalized society with no real access to education or other methods of social upward mobility. They felt ignored by the government and by society. Drug trafficking then became a source of income and an outlet to rebel against the government that had forgotten them in the countryside.\n\n=== Mafioso Poseurs and modern narcoculture  ===\nNarcoculture is a type of crime-related subculture that emerges in places where traffickers or other mafias have great power, and in consequence great cultural influence.\nBecause of that influence their lives and exploits are often glamorised by the mass media and they are looked up to as role models by some young people.<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor=25064542|title=Review|journal=The Journal of Japanese Studies|volume=31|issue=1|pages=159\u2013163|last1=Nakano|first1=Koichi|year=2005|doi=10.1353/jjs.2005.0020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ccja-acjp.ca/en/cjcr300/cjcr348.html|title=Book Review - Criminal Identities and Consumer Culture: Crime, Exclusion and the New Culture of Narcissism - CCJA|publisher=|access-date=2014-10-17|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141017024417/https://www.ccja-acjp.ca/en/cjcr300/cjcr348.html|archive-date=2014-10-17|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collections.infocollections.org/ukedu/en/d/Ji0005e/5.html|title=The Culture of Violence: 4. The impact of drug trafficking on Colombian culture|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021032506/http://collections.infocollections.org/ukedu/en/d/Ji0005e/5.html|archive-date=21 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSubcultures similar to Mexican narco culture emerged in the United States during Prohibition,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/crimefilms.html|title=Crime and Gangster Films|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217015403/http://www.filmsite.org/crimefilms.html|archive-date=17 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturepicturegalleries/9033812/Top-FBI-agents-in-the-movies.html?image=1|title=Top FBI agents in the movies|work=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023104141/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturepicturegalleries/9033812/Top-FBI-agents-in-the-movies.html?image=1|archive-date=23 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/metro/1642295,cst-nws-dillinger28.article|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715150814/http://www.suntimes.com/news/metro/1642295,cst-nws-dillinger28.article|title=John Dillinger: Hero for the angry masses|archivedate=15 July 2009|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> and in Colombia and Italy in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colombiareports.co/narco-aesthetics-colombias-drug-trade-constructed-female-beauty/|title=How Colombia's drug trade constructed female 'narco-beauty'|work=Colombia News - Colombia Reports|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017234429/http://colombiareports.co/narco-aesthetics-colombias-drug-trade-constructed-female-beauty/|archive-date=17 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.semana.com/enfoque/articulo/maruja-pachon-ex-ministra-educacion/103434-3|title=Maruja Pach\u00f3n, ex ministra de Educaci\u00f3n|date=23 May 2009|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023053646/http://www.semana.com/enfoque/articulo/maruja-pachon-ex-ministra-educacion/103434-3|archive-date=23 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cle.ens-lyon.fr/espagnol/arte-drogas-y-cultura-narco-en-colombia-225357.kjsp?RH=CDL|title=La cl des langues - Espagnol - Arte, drogas y cultura narco en Colombia|author=Christine Bini|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003184946/http://cle.ens-lyon.fr/espagnol/arte-drogas-y-cultura-narco-en-colombia-225357.kjsp?RH=CDL|archive-date=3 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knowital.com/sicily/|title=About Sicily - tourist information, useful tips and sightseeing guide|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205035218/http://www.knowital.com/sicily/|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/01/italian-archbishop-10-year-moratorium-naming-godfathers-mob|title=Italian archbishop calls for 10-year ban on godparents to thwart mafia|work=the Guardian|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014025632/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/01/italian-archbishop-10-year-moratorium-naming-godfathers-mob|archive-date=14 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> These subcultures were characterized by extravagance, ostentation, hedonism, rural roots, honor, prestige, consumerism, power, utilitarianism, religiosity, and violence.<ref name=\"SanchezGodoy\">Sanchez, Godoy Jorge A. \"Procesos de Institucionalizacion de la narcocultura en Sinaloa.\" Frontera Norte 21:41 (2009): 77-103. pdf file.</ref>\n\nThose who take part in narcoculture are not necessarily drug traffickers or part of a criminal organization. Indeed, many of the participants in narcoculture are young people who come from marginalized sectors of society. The admiration that youth have for narcos is  similar to the way other kids look up to rock stars or sports legends. In some cases, the admiration that they feel for the drug traffickers, who they see as heroes, does lead them to get involved in drug trafficking. But in most cases they merely consume the narco culture and imagine that they are part of the narco world, or becoming \"narco-[[poseur]]s\".\n\nNarcoculture has created a fantasy where some people believe that drug trafficking is the only way to escape poverty. This fantasy is supported primarily through music (''[[narcocorridos]]'') and visual media, including television and film. \nSome believe that narcoculture originated in the highlands of Sinaloa, where many of the famous drug lords were born, such as the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel|Beltran Leyva brothers]], [[Ernesto Fonseca Carrillo]] \"Don Neto\", [[Rafael Caro Quintero]], and [[Juan Jose Esparragoza Moreno]] \"El Azul\".\nNarcoculture is rooted in the northern rural areas of Mexico and although it is constantly changing, it continues to foster and strengthen its rural roots over time.<ref name=\"SanchezGodoy\" />\n\n=== Narcoculture lifestyle ===\n\nNarcoculture glorifies the individual and his achievements, wealth, and masculinity.<ref name=\"RockwellNatalia\">Rockwell, Natalia Mendoza. Conversaciones Del Desierto: Cultura, Moral Y Tr\u00e1fico De Drogas. M\u00e9xico, D.F.: Centro De Investigaci\u00f3n Y Docencia Econ\u00f3micas, 2008. Print.</ref><ref name=\"RockwellNatalia\" /> Narcos live luxurious lifestyles and display their wealth by wearing expensive clothing.<ref name=\"suite101\">{{cite web|url=http://suite101.net/article/los-narcotraficantes-mexicanos-de-criminales-a-idolos-mediaticos-a45143|title=Los narcotraficantes mexicanos, de criminales a \u00eddolos medi\u00e1ticos|author=Israel P\u00e9rez Valencia|work=Suite101 (Spain)|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226211117/http://suite101.net/article/los-narcotraficantes-mexicanos-de-criminales-a-idolos-mediaticos-a45143|archive-date=26 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> There are regional differences in the styles of dress; for example the northern cities closest to the border are influenced by American styles of dress and brands. The clothing is gender-conscious, where men and women wear distinct fashion items pertaining to their gender. In most Mexican cities, there are men wearing ''[[piteado]]'' belts, cowboy boots made of exotic animal skin, silk shirts and cowboy hats or baseball caps; thus, some narcos have cast aside the cowboy or Northern style to wear expensive designer clothes.\n\nCertain clothing items, such as Ralph Lauren Polo shirts or Ed Hardy style clothing, were worn by several infamous drug traffickers at the moment of their capture, becoming highly fashionable items among the masses, prompting the creation of imitation styles sold on the black market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217060036/http://www.lacronica.com/EdicionDigital/Ediciones/20110613/PDFS/General_20.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=17 December 2014|website=archive.org|access-date=5 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528015605/http://web.archive.org/web/20141217060036/http://www.lacronica.com/EdicionDigital/Ediciones/20110613/PDFS/General_20.pdf|archive-date=28 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStyles vary in many border towns, but it is very common to see drug traffickers wearing luxury brand labels such as Burberry or Gucci hats, shirts, belts and shoes. Women associated with drug cartels often dress very ostentatiously and wear lots of jewelry, and it is common to see them wear such brands as Bebe, Guess, Burberry, Gucci and Coach.\n\nBesides wearing expensive brands, the drug lords run their own bars, which are visited mostly by men. The narco parties are get-togethers and parties where narcos drink and socialize.<ref>Guillermoprieto, Alma. \"[http://clas.berkeley.edu/Publications/Review/Spring2009/pdf/BRLAS-Spring2009-Guillermoprieto.pdf The Narcovirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823031251/http://www.clas.berkeley.edu/Publications/Review/Spring2009/pdf/BRLAS-Spring2009-Guillermoprieto.pdf |date=2011-08-23 }}.\" U.S.-Mexico Futures Forum.  Spring 2009. Web. 4 Nov. 2012.</ref>  Although many businesses have closed down because of the tremendous amount of violence sweeping the nation, the narcobars, restaurants, and nightclubs have remained open, and have thrived.\n\nThe projection of a glamorous image of the drug cartels by the mass media in Mexico has served to thwart the federal government's efforts of legitimizing the war against drugs and organized crime.<ref name=\"suite101\" />\n\n=== Narco music ===\n\n==== Narco ''corridos'' ====\n\nIn Sinaloa, narcoculture enjoys a place of privilege. In other parts of Mexico the acceptance of narcoculture has been a slow process. Narco ''corridos'', however, have helped narcoculture become more acceptable in places where interactions with drug traffickers do not take place on a daily basis.<ref name=\"OvalleMarroquin\">Ovalle Marroquin, Lilian P. \"Las Fronteras de la 'narcocultura.' \" 2007. Digital file.</ref>\n\nThe Mexican ''corrido'', a song narrating stories real or imagined about historical characters, became popular during the Mexican Revolution of 1910. The ''corrido'' became popular because it narrated news and events to a largely illiterate population. The ''corrido'' also created popular heroes and celebrated their lives and adventures. [[Pancho Villa]], revolutionary leader, was one of the figures celebrated through this corridos.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\">Galdamez Martinez,  Efren, Garcia Abarca, Sarai, Gonzalez Flores Mariela, Perez Camacho, Humberto, and Trejo Salazar,  Elisa. \"Los narcocorridos como forma de expression en Mexico:  Los del Norte.\" Slideshare.net.  n.d.  Web. 22 May 2013.</ref>\n\nAlthough these ''corridos''  mention kidnappings, assassination, executions, battles and disasters, they differ from the current ''narco-corridos'' in that the original ''corridos'' attempted to tell a story and give a moral message (like the fall and redemption, the sin and punishment, or life and death of a person ).\n\nThe first ''narco-corridos'' began to appear in the 1970s. Most scholars agree that the [[Tigres del Norte]] were the pioneers of this genre, first appearing in the southern United States, then becoming  popular in Sinaloa, Sonora, Tijuana and Michoac\u00e1n.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" />\n\n''Narcocorridos'' glorify and romanticize narco trafficking, and in a more recent trend of hyper-violent lyrics ( called ''[[Narcocorrido#Movimiento alterado|Movimiento alterado]]'', Spanish for the ''cocaine-[[alertness]] movement''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milenio.com/region/Movimiento-alterado-narco-sale-closet_0_276572792.html|title=Movimiento alterado: cuando el narco 'sale del cl\u00f3set'|author=Milenio Digital|work=Milenio|access-date=2015-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424133814/http://www.milenio.com/region/Movimiento-alterado-narco-sale-closet_0_276572792.html|archive-date=2015-04-24|url-status=live}}</ref> they started to express the pride of modern narcos have in murdering, torturing and dismembering their rivals. The traditional ''corridos'' spoke about the benevolent bandit who committed crimes for a good cause (in a robin-hood style).  Joaquin \"El Chapo\" Guzman, Ismael \"El Mayo\" Zambada, and Rafael Caro Quintero among others, have been elevated to popular heroes in a similar way as the traditional corrido elevated the so-called benevolent bandits [[Heraclio Bernal]] and Jesus Malverde during the Mexican Revolution.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" /> The ''corridos'' about these characters praised the bravery of these bandits and identified them as defenders of the poor against an unjust government.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" />\n\nIn addition to narrating the stories of well-known drug lords, ''narcocorridos'' demonstrate the evolution of drug trafficking in Mexico. The ''narcocorridos'' display a yearning for the countryside while expressing a desire for the modernity that the city has to offer. The austerity and simplicity of the countryside is reflected through images of horses, the ranch, agriculture, poverty, and the sombrero. The modernity of the city and material desires are expressed through images of mansions, luxury cars, cell phones,  and designer clothing.<ref name=\"GaxiolaGraciela\">Gaxiola, Graciela. \" 'Chinola kid,' narrativa desde la frontera.\" El Debate 21 May 2013. Online.</ref> Despite the poverty that exists in rural areas, the narco corridos idealize it as a place where there is no judgment or obstacles that would impede drug trafficking.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" />\n\n==== Narco Hip-Hop ====\n\nA music scene, similar to the early underground [[gangsta-rap]] scene of the mid to late 1990s, has emerged in northeastern Mexico ([[Nuevo Leon]], [[Tamaulipas]] and [[Coahuila]]), where the musical phenomenon of hip-hop is being co-opted by the influence of organized crime and the [[Mexican Drug War|drug war]] in the region. With lyrics similar to those of a [[narcocorrido]] (drug ballad), has appeared the [[Latin hip hop#Narco-Rap|Mexican Narco-rap]].\n\nHowever, unlike the corridos, which relate to rural regions of the Mexican Pacific (and which are generally linked to the [[Sinaloa cartel]]) the narco-rap emerged in the urban area of Tamaulipas, in the border with [[Texas]], a turf currently under armed dispute between [[the Zetas]] and the [[Gulf Cartel]].\n\nDerived from the constant presence of \"halcones\" (\"hawks\", cartel spies) and cartel-convoys circulating the streets of the region, young people have been involved in the local narcoculture, and narco-raps express the reality of life on the streets, of those cities under the drug cartels rule.\n\nThere are several notable cases, among them is a highly popular song called {{YouTube|Pfrp8_JkABo|''The Song of Metro 3''}} that praises the life and exploits of drug lord [[Samuel Flores Borrego]] (alias Metro 3) for his \"ferocity and loyalty.\" <ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=d9VvdwvVpxwC&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=samuel+flores+borrego&source=bl&ots=QI_7ZVyNCK&sig=TMP3VIN-0FH9xkF_HK4Dyx2P-y8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TZ0gULvpI4bA2gWz2YCoCw&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=samuel%20flores%20borrego&f=false To Die in Mexico: Dispatches from Inside the Drug War</ref>\n\nSome of the main exponents of the genre are [[Cartel De Santa]],  [[Samuel Flores Borrego#Narco-Rap legacy|Cano y Blunt]], DemenT and Big Los.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/es_mx/read/en-tamaulipas-los-narcos-disparan-a-ritmo-de-rap-0000156-v5n4|title=En Tamaulipas los narcos disparan a ritmo de rap|work=VICE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/06/23/hfr-el-narco-rap-la-banda-sonora-del-horror-en-reynosa|title=El narco-rap, la banda sonora del horror en Reynosa|date=23 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131031413/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/06/23/hfr-el-narco-rap-la-banda-sonora-del-horror-en-reynosa|archivedate=31 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://diario.mx/El_Paso/2013-06-16_0ee2cdd6/se-suman-los-raperos-norteamericanos-a-la-ola-narco/|title=Se suman los raperos norteamericanos a la 'ola narco'|author=Luis Chaparro<br>El Diario de El Paso|date=16 June 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevoheraldo.com/el_valle/noticias_locales/mcallen-reynosa-la-maldosa/article_b3e9d5da-e8e4-11e2-b83d-0019bb30f31a.html|title=McALLEN: 'Reynosa la Maldosa'|work=El Nuevo Heraldo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2013/06/us-rappers-dedicate-their-songs-to.html|title=Borderland Beat: US Rappers Dedicate Their Songs to Mexican Drug Lords|author=Chivis|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/read/mexicos-narco-rappers-are-here-to-stay-cano-blunt-interview-reynosa|title=Mexico's Narco Rappers Are Here to Stay|work=VICE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nuestraaparenterendicion.com/index.php/biblioteca/cronicas-y-reportajes/item/962-voy-a-morir-porque-creen-que-soy-un-zeta|title=Voy a morir porque creen que soy un Zeta|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThis trend of narco-Mexico-related hip-hop has also an [[United States|American]] counterpart, artists such as the rapper [[Uncle Murda]], [[Skrillex]], [[YG (rapper)|YG]], [[Gucci Mane]], [[2 Chainz]] and [[The Game (rapper)|Jayceon \"The Game\" Taylor]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/12/world/americas/mexico-el-chapo-profile/|title=The legend of 'El Chapo': Hiding in plain sight?|first1=Catherine E.|last1=Shoichet|first2=Don|last2=Melvin|first3=Mariano|last3=Castillo|website=CNN|access-date=2018-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913135832/http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/12/world/americas/mexico-el-chapo-profile/|archive-date=2017-09-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/es_mx/blog/the-game-acaba-de-lanzar-una-cancin-dedicada-al-chapo|title=The Game y Skrillex acaban de lanzar una canci\u00f3n dedicada al Chapo|date=23 September 2015|website=vice.com|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085426/http://noisey.vice.com/es_mx/blog/the-game-acaba-de-lanzar-una-cancin-dedicada-al-chapo|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espectaculos.televisa.com/musica/noticias/865919/chapo-joaquin-guzman-loera-tambien-tiene-hip-hop-corridos/|title=Televisa Espect\u00e1culos secci\u00f3n de M\u00fasica|website=Espect\u00e1culos Producci\u00f3n|access-date=2018-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054527/http://espectaculos.televisa.com/musica/noticias/865919/chapo-joaquin-guzman-loera-tambien-tiene-hip-hop-corridos/|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref>have made songs dedicated Drug traffickers such as \"El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n\".\n\n=== Narco juniors ===\n\n\"Narco juniors\" are a new form of narcocultural expression. Narco juniors are the children of the older drug traffickers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.debate.com.mx/mexico/Ellos-son-los-narcojuniors-mas-poderosos-de-Mexico-20151227-0089.html|title=Ellos son los 'narcojuniors' m\u00e1s poderosos de M\u00e9xico|website=debate.com.mx|access-date=2018-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222104808/https://www.debate.com.mx/mexico/Ellos-son-los-narcojuniors-mas-poderosos-de-Mexico-20151227-0089.html|archive-date=2018-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/411526/los-narcojuniors-sinaloenses-poderosos-y-exhibicionistas|title=Los narcojuniors sinaloenses, poderosos y exhibicionistas - Proceso|date=25 July 2015|website=proceso.com.mx|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222051405/http://www.proceso.com.mx/411526/los-narcojuniors-sinaloenses-poderosos-y-exhibicionistas|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> or the children of rich entrepreneurs that get involved in drug trade \"for fun\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/177006/la-mama-de-hodoyan-recuerda-como-se-conocieron-y-convivieron-los-narcojuniors-del-cartel-de-tijuana|title=La mam\u00e1 de Hodoy\u00e1n recuerda c\u00f3mo se conocieron y convivieron los \"narcojuniors\" del C\u00e1rtel de Tijuana - Proceso|date=6 December 1997|website=proceso.com.mx|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222051410/http://www.proceso.com.mx/177006/la-mama-de-hodoyan-recuerda-como-se-conocieron-y-convivieron-los-narcojuniors-del-cartel-de-tijuana|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/2013/01/08/nacional/878467|title=Todo empez\u00f3 en Tijuana|date=22 February 2014|website=excelsior.com.mx|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211120741/http://www.excelsior.com.mx/2013/01/08/nacional/878467|archive-date=11 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> that have come to reconstitute the meaning of narcoculture and drug trafficking. Unlike their fathers or grandfathers, the narco juniors have for the most part been raised in urban wealth. The older narco traffickers were raised in rural poverty, placed a high value on family and felt connected to their people and culture. They felt a responsibility to give back to their community. The narco juniors share a cynical pride in being drug traffickers. The narco juniors place more value on spending money, parties, and luxury.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" /> The marginalized people who were helped by the older traffickers, have now become the victims of the narco juniors' aggression.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" />\n\n=== Narco religion ===\n\nNarco-superstition and religion is a major aspect of narcoculture. It is a form of [[superstition]], depicted through drug traffickers' devotion to St. [[St. Jude|Jude Thaddaeus]] (patron of lost causes and desperate situations) and [[Jesus Malverde]]. Jesus Malverde was said to be a bandit that stole from the rich to give to the poor. He lived his life running from the authorities. His image was appropriated as the patron saint of drug traffickers, the poor, and the marginalized. An altar with his name was erected in the place where it is said that he was hanged by the government.\n\nAnother aspect of narco religion is the involvement of drug traffickers with their local churches. This occurs primarily through narco limosnas (narco-donations) that drug traffickers give to the church.{{fact|date=January 2019}} Drug traffickers have also used the church to launder money. Nora Perez-Rayon Elizundia gives an example of a bishop in Aguascalientes that admitted to taking donations from a drug trafficker because he said that the money could  be \"purified\" when used for good causes.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn other parts of Mexico some drug traffickers and their hitmen pray for protection to the [[Santa Muerte|Holy Death]], a personification of death, and in some cases they practice [[Santer\u00eda]] or [[devil worship]]ing. These type of activities are not mainstream narco-behaviors, but do occur in some remote areas.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\n=== Narco propaganda ===\nNarco propaganda includes narco mantas, banners that appear in public places, such as highway overpasses and bridges. This is a way for narcos to communicate directly to the populace. These banners are also used to threaten leaders or other members of rival cartels.\nVariations of these banners include the narco poster, a message left next to a dead body, and the narco-pinta, graffiti sprayed or hand-painted on a whitewashed brick or adobe wall next to a commercial building or house.<ref name=\"Campbell, Howard\">Campbell, Howard. \"Narco-Propaganda in the Mexican 'Drug War' An Anthropological Perspective.\" (2014): Sage Journals. Web. 24 Oct. 2014. http://lap.sagepub.com/content/early/2012/04/30/0094582X12443519 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416111705/http://lap.sagepub.com/content/early/2012/04/30/0094582X12443519 |date=2016-04-16 }}</ref>\n\n=== Narco western ===\nModern literature, not only novels or poetry but also newspapers, magazines and internet publishings, are means that  tend to narrate 'real stories', or  at least what is believed to be real about  certain people involved with the narco movement. Sometimes they exaggerate  the legacy of these people, and of  the crimes they have committed, in order to intimidate their enemies or the population in general.<ref name=\"Boothroyd, Dave\">Boothroyd, Dave. Culture on Drugs: Narco-Cultural Studies of High Modernity. New York, NY, USA: Manchester University Press, 2006.</ref>\n\nThe narco western is a new literary genre that was started by Hilario Pe\u00f1a's ''Chinola Kid'' published in October 2012.  In a recent interview Hilario states that the narco western is the modern version of a western.<ref name=\"GaxiolaGraciela\" /> Instead of a horse, his character drives a truck and instead of fighting Apaches, his character must defeat criminals and the federal police in the state of Sinaloa.\n\n=== Narco cinema===\nSee: [[Mexploitation#Mexican narcocinema]]\n\nNarco cinema in Mexico started as a combination of ''[[telenovela]]s'' (soap operas) and Mexican cinema during the 1960s, where the 'golden age' of cinema collapsed due to the interest of the population in television.<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\">Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos '[http://hemisphericinstitute.org/hemi/en/e-misferica-82/gutierrez Narco and Cinema: The War Over Public Debate in Mexico] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141119025246/http://hemisphericinstitute.org/hemi/en/e-misferica-82/gutierrez |date=2014-11-19 }}', In E-MISFERICA 8.2 #Narcomachine, 2011.</ref> During the 1970s, narco cinema consisted of movies released mostly for home entertainment or 'video home', creating a B-film market that focused on very controversial topics, that with use of violence would try to create a national reality or identity. These films were mostly made with a low budget, usually under 140,000 Mexican pesos (US$10,000), telling stories about police, drug dealers and prostitutes. These films are rarely discussed in mainstream media because of their low budgets, and connection with   pop culture and low brow entertainment.<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\" />\n\nNarco cinema today controls the Mexican film market, being influential along the border between the United States and Mexico. The films deal with the identity of the narco, consisting of a struggle of an anti-hero being immersed in a border culture, articulating narratives of life, death, love, loss, hope, greed, desire, humor and violence, alongside addiction, repetition and compulsion.<ref name=\"Benavides, O. Hugo.\">Benavides, O. Hugo. Drugs, Thugs, and Divas: Telenovelas and Narco Dramas in Latin America. Austin, TX, USA: University of Texas Press, 2008.</ref>\n\nNarco cinema develops anti-norms and expresses feelings discouraged in culturally accepted institutions.<ref name=\"Benavides, O. Hugo.\" /> In this genre violence is at its most extreme, weapons and thug-like behavior taking center stage. The use of stereotyped characters and predictable plots alienates those looking for subtexts, complex story lines, and sophisticated writing, but for the poor rural people, these films are in demand because they tell the story of their lives and the lives around them.<ref name=\"Benavides, O. Hugo.\" />\n\nNarco violence is also used by mainstream films, taking inspiration from real life events that marked the country, or in other cases fictionalized events,<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\" /> example: [[Breaking Bad]].\n\nSome examples of mainstream narco cinema include ''[[Miss Bala (2011 film)|Miss Bala]]'', ''[[El Infierno]]'' and ''[[Heli (film)|Heli]]''.\n\n''Miss Bala'', a 2011 film directed by Gerardo Naranjo, that premiered in Cannes and got attention from critics, became a box office success in Mexico. Based on real life events, it tells the story of a young woman dreaming of becoming a beauty pageant queen. Narcos manipulate her to work for them, in exchange for her victory.<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\" />\n\n''El Infierno'' is a film directed by Luis Estrada. Compared to ''Miss Bala'', this film is more fictionalized and makes use of dark humor, developing empathy for the anti-hero, glorifying the drug bosses.<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\" />\n\n''Heli'', by Mexican director Amat Escalante, is one of the most representative films of narco cinema. The director said he tried not to focus the movie around explicit violence, which is expected of drug related movies. Yet one scene from the movie was considered the most brutal in Mexican cinema, showing traffickers burning the genitals of two young men in front of a group of children. Escalante refers to this as exposition, in that it shows how Mexico's youth is being ruined by these kind of people, at times leaving them without anything to look forward to in the future. The film focuses on love, family and hope, people wanting to believe they can succeed. This hope is conveyed through the eyes of Estela, a girl who falls in love with an older boy who involves her and her family in the drug world. Overall, Heli tries to eliminate the stereotypical figure of the Mexican cowboy or ''ranchero'', where the male figure is depicted by wearing boots and a hat. Instead the film shows atrocities committed by traffickers without offering any real solutions.<ref name=\"Molina, Javier.\">Molina, Javier. \"Mexican Cinema Brings Narco-terror to the Screen.\" ''El Pa\u00eds'', 6 August 2013. Web. 25 October 2014 http://elpais.com/m/elpais/2013/08/06/inenglish/1375805458_247638.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211002031/http://elpais.com/m/elpais/2013/08/06/inenglish/1375805458_247638.html |date=2014-12-11 }}</ref>\n\n===Social media===\nCartels have been making use of the Internet over the years going from the outdated [[MySpace]], to [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gorman|first1=Ryan|title=Status: In a Mexican drug cartel . . . Pouting gangsters take to Facebook to show off their bling, molls and heavy firepower|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2487477/The-pouting-killers-Facebook-Mexicos-evil-drug-gang-soldiers-social-media-publicize-bling-cash-heavy-firepower.html|website=dailymail.co.uk|accessdate=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203122359/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2487477/The-pouting-killers-Facebook-Mexicos-evil-drug-gang-soldiers-social-media-publicize-bling-cash-heavy-firepower.html|archive-date=3 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Stroud|first1=Matt|title=Facebook becomes the new front in Mexico's drug war|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/4/1/5569878/the-dark-side-of-the-facebook-revolution|publisher=The Verge|accessdate=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131002928/http://www.theverge.com/2014/4/1/5569878/the-dark-side-of-the-facebook-revolution|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cox|first1=Joseph|title=Mexico's Drug Cartels Love Social Media|url=https://www.vice.com/read/mexicos-drug-cartels-are-using-the-internet-to-get-up-to-mischief|publisher=Vice|accessdate=26 January 2016|date=4 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126001507/http://www.vice.com/read/mexicos-drug-cartels-are-using-the-internet-to-get-up-to-mischief|archive-date=26 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Narcos at (Instagram) war! From guns and girls to big cats and big piles of cash, El Chapo's sons spark social media battles between Mexican cartel members showing off their sickening wealth|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3226232/Narcos-Instagram-war-guns-girls-big-cats-big-piles-cash-El-Chapo-s-sons-spark-social-media-battles-Mexican-cartel-members-showing-sickening-wealth.html|website=dailymail.co.uk|accessdate=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131153453/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3226232/Narcos-Instagram-war-guns-girls-big-cats-big-piles-cash-El-Chapo-s-sons-spark-social-media-battles-Mexican-cartel-members-showing-sickening-wealth.html|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico's Cartel Brats Brag About Themselves on Social Media|url=http://www.vocativ.com/underworld/drugs/mexicos-cartel-brats-brag-social-media/|website=vocativ.com|accessdate=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131054023/http://www.vocativ.com/underworld/drugs/mexicos-cartel-brats-brag-social-media/|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Here they post videos that announce themselves as a new emerging power to be feared. One of the most visited websites to follow information about events related to narco violence is ''[[El Blog del Narco]]'', which defines itself at neutral. Their only objective is to publish stories in a journalistic way. What draws the most attention are the confessional/torture videos posted, which contain lots of graphic violence, providing torture to the prisoners before being executed in front of the camera.<ref name=\"Campbell, Howard\" />\nTwitter is used to post threats to one another, and sometimes, with the use of special technology, Narcos can track other rivals in order to kill them. This can be detrimental as well, because sometimes police finds them in the same way.<ref name=\"Campbell, Howard\" /> Instagram, can be used to show off their lifestyles, which includes new cars, expensive watches, designer clothes, fine liquor, exotic pets and massive weaponry.\n\nNotable examples are [[Jos\u00e9 Rodrigo Ar\u00e9chiga Gamboa|El Chino \u00c1ntrax]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adnpolitico.com/gobierno/2014/01/04/lujo-y-viajes-en-supuestas-redes-sociales-de-chino-antrax|title=Lujo y armas, en supuestas redes sociales de 'Chino \u00c1ntrax'|publisher=|access-date=2015-10-08|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6MPka5ZuK?url=http://www.adnpolitico.com/gobierno/2014/01/04/lujo-y-viajes-en-supuestas-redes-sociales-de-chino-antrax|archive-date=2014-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/world_news/Americas/article1359366.ece?CMP=OTH-gnws-standard-2014_01_04|title=Facebook posturing helps nail Mexico's young drug barons - The Sunday Times|publisher=|access-date=2015-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201115928/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/world_news/Americas/article1359366.ece?CMP=OTH-gnws-standard-2014_01_04|archive-date=2016-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/chino-antrax-exhibicionismo-caro-los-costos-del-ego|title=RIODOCE|access-date=2015-10-08|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6MQt7xnsj?url=http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/chino-antrax-exhibicionismo-caro-los-costos-del-ego|archive-date=2014-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Claudia Ochoa Felix]], supposed leaders of [[Los \u00c1ntrax]], an enforcer gang of the Sinaloa cartel. Both captured the attention of news outlets and blogs with photos on Twitter and Instagram that showed how they enjoy the sort of spoils that Mexicans relate with the lives of successful drug traffickers.<ref name=\"Ochoa Felix, Claudia\">Ochoa Felix, Claudia. The Press Ruined My Life. Sinaloa, Mex. Press Conference. 12 June \t2014. Web. 17 Nov. 2014. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KASuJrYXv0c#t {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006105150/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KASuJrYXv0c#t |date=2014-10-06 }}</ref> Claudia posts pictures on social media, as which she poses with expensive accessories like watches, purses, designer clothes, champagne bottles, cars and planes. Also  frequently poses with big guns.  In a press release, she mentions how her life has changed after those pictures have circulated around the world, and she fears for her family's safety. She claims that all those pictures of her were modified, because she is not the one appearing in them. She also claims that she has no association whatsoever with any of the drug cartels operating in Mexico.<ref name=\"Ochoa Felix, Claudia\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Mexican drug war]]\n* [[Crime in Mexico]]\n* [[Jihobbyist]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Mexico topics}}\n\n[[Category:Illegal drug trade]]\n[[Category:Mexican culture]]\n[[Category:Drugs in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican Drug War]]\n[[Category:Illegal drug trade in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Drug culture]]\n[[Category:Subcultures]]\n[[Category:Criminal subcultures]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2015}}\n'''Narcoculture in Mexico''' is a subculture that has grown as a result of the strong presence of the various [[drug cartel]]s throughout Mexico. \nIn the same way that other subcultures around the world that are related to crime and [[Drug culture|drug use]] (for example the Scottish [[Ned (Scottish)#Ned culture|ned]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2005/oct/20/penal.crime|title=Scotland's murderous heart|work=the Guardian|access-date=2016-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415203553/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2005/oct/20/penal.crime|archive-date=2017-04-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/3452275.stm|title=Extra police target 'ned culture'|publisher=BBC NEWS|location=UK - Scotland|access-date=2015-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023142725/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/3452275.stm|archive-date=2015-10-23|url-status=live}}</ref> and European [[hooligan]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://munchies.vice.com/articles/what-ive-learned-from-driving-around-drunk-tourists-all-day|title=What I've Learned from Driving Around Drunk Tourists All Day - MUNCHIES|author=Anonymous|work=MUNCHIES: Food by VICE|access-date=2015-10-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018024616/http://munchies.vice.com/articles/what-ive-learned-from-driving-around-drunk-tourists-all-day|archive-date=2015-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=85mxAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Football Hooliganism, Fan Behaviour and Crime|publisher=|isbn=9781137347978|last1=Hopkins|first1=M.|last2=Treadwell|first2=J.|date=2014-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/bundesliga-german-football-hooligans-use-crystal-meth-fuel-violence-1485073|title=Bundesliga: German football hooligans 'use crystal meth to fuel violence'|author=Mark Piggott|work=International Business Times UK|access-date=2015-10-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911221616/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/bundesliga-german-football-hooligans-use-crystal-meth-fuel-violence-1485073|archive-date=2015-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref> or the American street-[[Gangsta rap#Criticisms|gangsta]]s and [[Outlaw motorcycle club#Outlaw motorcycle gangs as criminal enterprises|outlaw bikers]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/4458/20131205/narco-cultura-how-mexicos-mexican-gangsta-rap-glorifies-drug-lords.htm|title='Narco Cultura:' How Mexican 'Gangsta Rap' Glorifies Drug Lords|work=Latin Post|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511233019/http://www.latinpost.com/articles/4458/20131205/narco-cultura-how-mexicos-mexican-gangsta-rap-glorifies-drug-lords.htm|archive-date=11 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Mexican narco culture has developed its own form of dress, music, literature, film, religious beliefs and practices and language (slang) that has helped it become a part of the mainstream fashion in some areas of the country, mainly among lower-class, uneducated youth.<ref name=\"Canalestrellatv 2011\">Canalestrellatv. \"Narcocultura part 1.mov.\" online video clip. Youtube.  Youtube, 15 Nov. 2011. Web 26 May 2013.</ref> Narco culture is dynamic in that there are various regional differences within Mexico and among those who participate in it.\n\n==Origin==\n{{Refimprove section|date=December 2015}}The origins of narco culture, like drug trafficking, had humble beginnings in Mexico. Narco culture emerged from the practice of drug trafficking in the highlands of Badiraguato, Sinaloa. It is in the sierra or countryside where an identity of drug trafficking was created and then consolidated once it crossed into the urban sphere. Narcoculture has been defined as a code of conduct and lifestyle for those that participate in the \"narco world.\"<ref name=\"OvalleMarroquin\" />\n\nMany scholars, like Luis Astorga and Jorge Alan Sanchez Godoy explain that there is no evidence that would suggest that [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] or [[opium]] were consumed in Mexico prior to the arrival of the Spanish and the Chinese {{Citation needed|date=December 2015}}. Although indigenous communities in Mexico consumed hallucinogenic mushrooms and [[Peyote#History|Peyote]] in their religious practices it was not until the arrival of the Spanish that cannabis was introduced to Mexico.\nDrug trafficking in Mexico has been considered by Luis Astorga, to have originated with the Chinese immigration to Sinaloa. It is said {{Citation needed|date=December 2015}} that the Chinese immigrants brought [[poppy seeds]] with them when they arrived in Mexico to work in the railroads and mines.\nSanchez Godoy explains that after cannabis was brought to Mexico, it was used for medical purposes and poppy plants were used for decoration and served as inspiration for several Mexican [[corridos]] or ballads.\n\n== Drug production in Mexico ==\n{{Refimprove section|date=December 2015}}\n\nThe US effectively banned all [[Psychoactive drug]]s when the federal government passed in 1914 the Harrison Act, prohibiting all non-medicinal use of opium, morphine, and cocaine. In 1919 The National Prohibition Act made alcoholic beverages illegal and The Marijuana Tax Act of 1937 outlawed marijuana.<ref name=\"isreview.org\">{{cite web|url=http://isreview.org/issue/90/political-economy-mexicos-drug-war|title=The political economy of Mexico's drug war - International Socialist Review|website=isreview.org|access-date=2016-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218202935/http://isreview.org/issue/90/political-economy-mexicos-drug-war|archive-date=2016-12-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMexico\u2019s proximity to the US made it an easy source and American bootleggers and traffickers rushed to obtain illicit narcotics and alcohol. Exports of Mexican opium, heroin, and marijuana for US consumption steadily increased as a result of Prohibition.<ref name=\"isreview.org\"/>\n\nThe [[black market]] grew quickly, with millions of Americans requiring a huge supply of alcohol, heroin, marijuana and cocaine. The initial shortage caused a boost in drug prices, and these new super-profits attracted black market suppliers to fill the vacuum.<ref name=\"isreview.org\"/>\n\n=== Expulsion of Chinese producers ===\n\nDuring the early 1920s, the Chinese in Sinaloa were victims of segregation, hate crimes, and forceful deportation. In 1927, to cooperate with its northern neighbour Mexican President [[Plutarco Elias Calles]], by federal mandate, ordered the expulsion of the Chinese poppy producers.<ref name=\"SanchezGodoy\" />\n\n=== US morphine demand ===\nOnce the Chinese were expelled from Sinaloa, the production of narcotics was then controlled by the rural Mexican farmers. The narcotics production in Mexico was still small,{{Citation needed|date=December 2015}} but the demand for [[morphine]] in the United States created by the disruption in its morphine supply from Europe during the World Wars led to the temporary legalization of narcotics in Mexico.\n\n===Mexican production and the birth of narcoculture ===\nScholars like Sanchez Godoy and Luis Astorga {{Citation needed|date=December 2015}} state that narcotics were temporarily legalized in Sinaloa in order to supply the United States' demand during the world war. \nThe period when the production of narcotics was temporarily legalized, shaped and created the drug trafficking identity in the region. This is when narcoculture first begins to appear. It is also the period when Mexico entered the large-scale production of narcotics.\n\n== The rise of the Mexican drug cartels and the consolidation of narcoculture ==\n\nThe 1950s in Mexico were marked by the term \"''narcotr\u00e1fico''\" (narco traffic) that began to appear in the media. During the 1940s through 1970s drug trafficking in Mexico was considered to be a \"small family business\" with a relatively simple organization and division of labor.<ref name=\"SanchezGodoy\" /> It is not until after the 1970s with the growth of demand from the United States and alliances with Colombian drug traffickers that cartels in Mexico were formed to control the production and distribution of narcotics. Mexico then became a producer and distributor.\n\nIn previous decades, Mexico served as the route of entrance for the cocaine arriving to the United States from Colombia. With Mexico supplying the United States with heroin and morphine during World War II, it became a producer. The alliance between Mexican cartels and Colombian cartels meant that Mexico was now a distributor and producer. As drug trafficking expanded in Mexico, so did narcoculture. Narcoculture expanded into the urban sector of society and began the process of legitimization and moved away from a subculture into a part of the dominant culture.\n\n=== Coining the term narcoculture ===\nThe term \"narcoculture\" was first coined in the 1970s. Narcoculture defines the way of life and ideas of drug traffickers. Its existence depends on the acceptance of drug traffickers and drug trafficking, becoming a transnational network of production, transportation, and commercialization of illegal drugs.\n\nDrug trafficking has political, economic, ideological, and cultural implications. Drug traffickers interact with the rest of society and as this daily interaction progresses, some of the drug traffickers' mannerisms are adopted by society and this leads to cultural change and legitimization. The drug traffickers' way of life or narcoculture becomes legitimate in the society. Some aspects are adopted by those outside of drug trafficking, and over time people forget that what they have adopted is narcoculture. Narcoculture begins a process of legitimization when it begins to include the popular classes in the urban cities.\n\n=== Rise of the Mexican Mafiosos ===\nNarcoculture in Sinaloa shares many characteristics with Mediterranean culture and mafias in that it is said that the Sinaloa narcoculture is based on honor, bravery, family loyalty, protection, vengeance, generosity, hospitality, nobility, and prestige much like the Mediterranean mafias. Drug traffickers use \"claves\" (codes) to maintain a level of secrecy. Some of these codes, however, have been revealed in ''narcocorridos'' (Mexican ballads about drug trafficking) and are then used by people who listen to this music, even if they are not drug traffickers. This is when narcoculture becomes a part of the mainstream discourse.\n\nPrior to the 1970s, narcoculture and drug trafficking in Sinaloa were almost exclusively rural. The stigma that was placed on narcotics early on meant that people in the cities were reluctant to accept it as a legitimate activity. In the countryside of Sinaloa, people were starving and drug trafficking seemed like the only viable solution. The rural population saw themselves a part of the marginalized society with no real access to education or other methods of social upward mobility. They felt ignored by the government and by society. Drug trafficking then became a source of income and an outlet to rebel against the government that had forgotten them in the countryside.\n\n=== Mafioso Poseurs and modern narcoculture  ===\nNarcoculture is a type of crime-related subculture that emerges in places where traffickers or other mafias have great power, and in consequence great cultural influence.\nBecause of that influence their lives and exploits are often glamorised by the mass media and they are looked up to as role models by some young people.<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor=25064542|title=Review|journal=The Journal of Japanese Studies|volume=31|issue=1|pages=159\u2013163|last1=Nakano|first1=Koichi|year=2005|doi=10.1353/jjs.2005.0020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ccja-acjp.ca/en/cjcr300/cjcr348.html|title=Book Review - Criminal Identities and Consumer Culture: Crime, Exclusion and the New Culture of Narcissism - CCJA|publisher=|access-date=2014-10-17|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141017024417/https://www.ccja-acjp.ca/en/cjcr300/cjcr348.html|archive-date=2014-10-17|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collections.infocollections.org/ukedu/en/d/Ji0005e/5.html|title=The Culture of Violence: 4. The impact of drug trafficking on Colombian culture|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021032506/http://collections.infocollections.org/ukedu/en/d/Ji0005e/5.html|archive-date=21 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSubcultures similar to Mexican narco culture emerged in the United States during Prohibition,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/crimefilms.html|title=Crime and Gangster Films|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217015403/http://www.filmsite.org/crimefilms.html|archive-date=17 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturepicturegalleries/9033812/Top-FBI-agents-in-the-movies.html?image=1|title=Top FBI agents in the movies|work=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023104141/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturepicturegalleries/9033812/Top-FBI-agents-in-the-movies.html?image=1|archive-date=23 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/metro/1642295,cst-nws-dillinger28.article|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715150814/http://www.suntimes.com/news/metro/1642295,cst-nws-dillinger28.article|title=John Dillinger: Hero for the angry masses|archivedate=15 July 2009|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> and in Colombia and Italy in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colombiareports.co/narco-aesthetics-colombias-drug-trade-constructed-female-beauty/|title=How Colombia's drug trade constructed female 'narco-beauty'|work=Colombia News - Colombia Reports|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017234429/http://colombiareports.co/narco-aesthetics-colombias-drug-trade-constructed-female-beauty/|archive-date=17 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.semana.com/enfoque/articulo/maruja-pachon-ex-ministra-educacion/103434-3|title=Maruja Pach\u00f3n, ex ministra de Educaci\u00f3n|date=23 May 2009|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023053646/http://www.semana.com/enfoque/articulo/maruja-pachon-ex-ministra-educacion/103434-3|archive-date=23 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cle.ens-lyon.fr/espagnol/arte-drogas-y-cultura-narco-en-colombia-225357.kjsp?RH=CDL|title=La cl des langues - Espagnol - Arte, drogas y cultura narco en Colombia|author=Christine Bini|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003184946/http://cle.ens-lyon.fr/espagnol/arte-drogas-y-cultura-narco-en-colombia-225357.kjsp?RH=CDL|archive-date=3 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knowital.com/sicily/|title=About Sicily - tourist information, useful tips and sightseeing guide|publisher=|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205035218/http://www.knowital.com/sicily/|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/01/italian-archbishop-10-year-moratorium-naming-godfathers-mob|title=Italian archbishop calls for 10-year ban on godparents to thwart mafia|work=the Guardian|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014025632/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/01/italian-archbishop-10-year-moratorium-naming-godfathers-mob|archive-date=14 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> These subcultures were characterized by extravagance, ostentation, hedonism, rural roots, honor, prestige, consumerism, power, utilitarianism, religiosity, and violence.<ref name=\"SanchezGodoy\">Sanchez, Godoy Jorge A. \"Procesos de Institucionalizacion de la narcocultura en Sinaloa.\" Frontera Norte 21:41 (2009): 77-103. pdf file.</ref>\n\nThose who take part in narcoculture are not necessarily drug traffickers or part of a criminal organization. Indeed, many of the participants in narcoculture are young people who come from marginalized sectors of society. The admiration that youth have for narcos is  similar to the way other kids look up to rock stars or sports legends. In some cases, the admiration that they feel for the drug traffickers, who they see as heroes, does lead them to get involved in drug trafficking. But in most cases they merely consume the narco culture and imagine that they are part of the narco world, or becoming \"narco-[[poseur]]s\".\n\nNarcoculture has created a fantasy where some people believe that drug trafficking is the only way to escape poverty. This fantasy is supported primarily through music (''[[narcocorridos]]'') and visual media, including television and film. \nSome believe that narcoculture originated in the highlands of Sinaloa, where many of the famous drug lords were born, such as the [[Beltr\u00e1n-Leyva Cartel|Beltran Leyva brothers]], [[Ernesto Fonseca Carrillo]] \"Don Neto\", [[Rafael Caro Quintero]], and [[Juan Jose Esparragoza Moreno]] \"El Azul\".\nNarcoculture is rooted in the northern rural areas of Mexico and although it is constantly changing, it continues to foster and strengthen its rural roots over time.<ref name=\"SanchezGodoy\" />\n\n=== Narcoculture lifestyle ===\n\nNarcoculture glorifies the individual and his achievements, wealth, and masculinity.<ref name=\"RockwellNatalia\">Rockwell, Natalia Mendoza. Conversaciones Del Desierto: Cultura, Moral Y Tr\u00e1fico De Drogas. M\u00e9xico, D.F.: Centro De Investigaci\u00f3n Y Docencia Econ\u00f3micas, 2008. Print.</ref><ref name=\"RockwellNatalia\" /> Narcos live luxurious lifestyles and display their wealth by wearing expensive clothing.<ref name=\"suite101\">{{cite web|url=http://suite101.net/article/los-narcotraficantes-mexicanos-de-criminales-a-idolos-mediaticos-a45143|title=Los narcotraficantes mexicanos, de criminales a \u00eddolos medi\u00e1ticos|author=Israel P\u00e9rez Valencia|work=Suite101 (Spain)|accessdate=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226211117/http://suite101.net/article/los-narcotraficantes-mexicanos-de-criminales-a-idolos-mediaticos-a45143|archive-date=26 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> There are regional differences in the styles of dress; for example the northern cities closest to the border are influenced by American styles of dress and brands. The clothing is gender-conscious, where men and women wear distinct fashion items pertaining to their gender. In most Mexican cities, there are men wearing ''[[piteado]]'' belts, cowboy boots made of exotic animal skin, silk shirts and cowboy hats or baseball caps; thus, some narcos have cast aside the cowboy or Northern style to wear expensive designer clothes.\n\nCertain clothing items, such as Ralph Lauren Polo shirts or Ed Hardy style clothing, were worn by several infamous drug traffickers at the moment of their capture, becoming highly fashionable items among the masses, prompting the creation of imitation styles sold on the black market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217060036/http://www.lacronica.com/EdicionDigital/Ediciones/20110613/PDFS/General_20.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=17 December 2014|website=archive.org|access-date=5 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528015605/http://web.archive.org/web/20141217060036/http://www.lacronica.com/EdicionDigital/Ediciones/20110613/PDFS/General_20.pdf|archive-date=28 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStyles vary in many border towns, but it is very common to see drug traffickers wearing luxury brand labels such as Burberry or Gucci hats, shirts, belts and shoes. Women associated with drug cartels often dress very ostentatiously and wear lots of jewelry, and it is common to see them wear such brands as Bebe, Guess, Burberry, Gucci and Coach.\n\nBesides wearing expensive brands, the drug lords run their own bars, which are visited mostly by men. The narco parties are get-togethers and parties where narcos drink and socialize.<ref>Guillermoprieto, Alma. \"[http://clas.berkeley.edu/Publications/Review/Spring2009/pdf/BRLAS-Spring2009-Guillermoprieto.pdf The Narcovirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823031251/http://www.clas.berkeley.edu/Publications/Review/Spring2009/pdf/BRLAS-Spring2009-Guillermoprieto.pdf |date=2011-08-23 }}.\" U.S.-Mexico Futures Forum.  Spring 2009. Web. 4 Nov. 2012.</ref>  Although many businesses have closed down because of the tremendous amount of violence sweeping the nation, the narcobars, restaurants, and nightclubs have remained open, and have thrived.\n\nThe projection of a glamorous image of the drug cartels by the mass media in Mexico has served to thwart the federal government's efforts of legitimizing the war against drugs and organized crime.<ref name=\"suite101\" />\n\n=== Narco music ===\n\n==== Narco ''corridos'' ====\n\nIn Sinaloa, narcoculture enjoys a place of privilege. In other parts of Mexico the acceptance of narcoculture has been a slow process. Narco ''corridos'', however, have helped narcoculture become more acceptable in places where interactions with drug traffickers do not take place on a daily basis.<ref name=\"OvalleMarroquin\">Ovalle Marroquin, Lilian P. \"Las Fronteras de la 'narcocultura.' \" 2007. Digital file.</ref>\n\nThe Mexican ''corrido'', a song narrating stories real or imagined about historical characters, became popular during the Mexican Revolution of 1910. The ''corrido'' became popular because it narrated news and events to a largely illiterate population. The ''corrido'' also created popular heroes and celebrated their lives and adventures. [[Pancho Villa]], revolutionary leader, was one of the figures celebrated through this corridos.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\">Galdamez Martinez,  Efren, Garcia Abarca, Sarai, Gonzalez Flores Mariela, Perez Camacho, Humberto, and Trejo Salazar,  Elisa. \"Los narcocorridos como forma de expression en Mexico:  Los del Norte.\" Slideshare.net.  n.d.  Web. 22 May 2013.</ref>\n\nAlthough these ''corridos''  mention kidnappings, assassination, executions, battles and disasters, they differ from the current ''narco-corridos'' in that the original ''corridos'' attempted to tell a story and give a moral message (like the fall and redemption, the sin and punishment, or life and death of a person ).\n\nThe first ''narco-corridos'' began to appear in the 1970s. Most scholars agree that the [[Tigres del Norte]] were the pioneers of this genre, first appearing in the southern United States, then becoming  popular in Sinaloa, Sonora, Tijuana and Michoac\u00e1n.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" />\n\n''Narcocorridos'' glorify and romanticize narco trafficking, and in a more recent trend of hyper-violent lyrics ( called ''[[Narcocorrido#Movimiento alterado|Movimiento alterado]]'', Spanish for the ''cocaine-[[alertness]] movement''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milenio.com/region/Movimiento-alterado-narco-sale-closet_0_276572792.html|title=Movimiento alterado: cuando el narco 'sale del cl\u00f3set'|author=Milenio Digital|work=Milenio|access-date=2015-05-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424133814/http://www.milenio.com/region/Movimiento-alterado-narco-sale-closet_0_276572792.html|archive-date=2015-04-24|url-status=live}}</ref> they started to express the pride of modern narcos have in murdering, torturing and dismembering their rivals. The traditional ''corridos'' spoke about the benevolent bandit who committed crimes for a good cause (in a robin-hood style).  Joaquin \"El Chapo\" Guzman, Ismael \"El Mayo\" Zambada, and Rafael Caro Quintero among others, have been elevated to popular heroes in a similar way as the traditional corrido elevated the so-called benevolent bandits [[Heraclio Bernal]] and Jesus Malverde during the Mexican Revolution.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" /> The ''corridos'' about these characters praised the bravery of these bandits and identified them as defenders of the poor against an unjust government.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" />\n\nIn addition to narrating the stories of well-known drug lords, ''narcocorridos'' demonstrate the evolution of drug trafficking in Mexico. The ''narcocorridos'' display a yearning for the countryside while expressing a desire for the modernity that the city has to offer. The austerity and simplicity of the countryside is reflected through images of horses, the ranch, agriculture, poverty, and the sombrero. The modernity of the city and material desires are expressed through images of mansions, luxury cars, cell phones,  and designer clothing.<ref name=\"GaxiolaGraciela\">Gaxiola, Graciela. \" 'Chinola kid,' narrativa desde la frontera.\" El Debate 21 May 2013. Online.</ref> Despite the poverty that exists in rural areas, the narco corridos idealize it as a place where there is no judgment or obstacles that would impede drug trafficking.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" />\n\n==== Narco Hip-Hop ====\n\nA music scene, similar to the early underground [[gangsta-rap]] scene of the Mid to Late 90's, has emerged in northeastern Mexico ([[Nuevo Leon]], [[Tamaulipas]] and [[Coahuila]]), where the musical phenomenon of hip-hop is being co-opted by the influence of organized crime and the [[Mexican Drug War|drug war]] in the region. With lyrics similar to those of a [[narcocorrido]] (drug ballad), has appeared the [[Latin hip hop#Narco-Rap|Mexican Narco-rap]].\n\nHowever, unlike the corridos, which relate to rural regions of the Mexican Pacific (and which are generally linked to the [[Sinaloa cartel]]) the narco-rap emerged in the urban area of Tamaulipas, in the border with [[Texas]], a turf currently under armed dispute between [[the Zetas]] and the [[Gulf Cartel]].\n\nDerived from the constant presence of \"halcones\" (\"hawks\", cartel spies) and cartel-convoys circulating the streets of the region, young people have been involved in the local narcoculture, and narco-raps express the reality of life on the streets, of those cities under the drug cartels rule.\n\nThere are several notable cases, among them is a highly popular song called {{YouTube|Pfrp8_JkABo|''The Song of Metro 3''}} that praises the life and exploits of drug lord [[Samuel Flores Borrego]] (alias Metro 3) for his \"ferocity and loyalty.\" <ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=d9VvdwvVpxwC&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=samuel+flores+borrego&source=bl&ots=QI_7ZVyNCK&sig=TMP3VIN-0FH9xkF_HK4Dyx2P-y8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TZ0gULvpI4bA2gWz2YCoCw&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=samuel%20flores%20borrego&f=false To Die in Mexico: Dispatches from Inside the Drug War</ref>\n\nSome of the main exponents of the genre are [[Cartel De Santa]],  [[Samuel Flores Borrego#Narco-Rap legacy|Cano y Blunt]], DemenT and Big Los.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/es_mx/read/en-tamaulipas-los-narcos-disparan-a-ritmo-de-rap-0000156-v5n4|title=En Tamaulipas los narcos disparan a ritmo de rap|work=VICE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/06/23/hfr-el-narco-rap-la-banda-sonora-del-horror-en-reynosa|title=El narco-rap, la banda sonora del horror en Reynosa|date=23 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131031413/http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2010/06/23/hfr-el-narco-rap-la-banda-sonora-del-horror-en-reynosa|archivedate=31 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://diario.mx/El_Paso/2013-06-16_0ee2cdd6/se-suman-los-raperos-norteamericanos-a-la-ola-narco/|title=Se suman los raperos norteamericanos a la 'ola narco'|author=Luis Chaparro<br>El Diario de El Paso|date=16 June 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevoheraldo.com/el_valle/noticias_locales/mcallen-reynosa-la-maldosa/article_b3e9d5da-e8e4-11e2-b83d-0019bb30f31a.html|title=McALLEN: 'Reynosa la Maldosa'|work=El Nuevo Heraldo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2013/06/us-rappers-dedicate-their-songs-to.html|title=Borderland Beat: US Rappers Dedicate Their Songs to Mexican Drug Lords|author=Chivis|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/read/mexicos-narco-rappers-are-here-to-stay-cano-blunt-interview-reynosa|title=Mexico's Narco Rappers Are Here to Stay|work=VICE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nuestraaparenterendicion.com/index.php/biblioteca/cronicas-y-reportajes/item/962-voy-a-morir-porque-creen-que-soy-un-zeta|title=Voy a morir porque creen que soy un Zeta|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThis trend of narco-Mexico-related hip-hop has also an [[United States|American]] counterpart, artists such as the rapper [[Uncle Murda]], [[Skrillex]], [[YG (rapper)|YG]], [[Gucci Mane]], [[2 Chainz]] and [[The Game (rapper)|Jayceon \"The Game\" Taylor]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/12/world/americas/mexico-el-chapo-profile/|title=The legend of 'El Chapo': Hiding in plain sight?|first1=Catherine E.|last1=Shoichet|first2=Don|last2=Melvin|first3=Mariano|last3=Castillo|website=CNN|access-date=2018-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913135832/http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/12/world/americas/mexico-el-chapo-profile/|archive-date=2017-09-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/es_mx/blog/the-game-acaba-de-lanzar-una-cancin-dedicada-al-chapo|title=The Game y Skrillex acaban de lanzar una canci\u00f3n dedicada al Chapo|date=23 September 2015|website=vice.com|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085426/http://noisey.vice.com/es_mx/blog/the-game-acaba-de-lanzar-una-cancin-dedicada-al-chapo|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espectaculos.televisa.com/musica/noticias/865919/chapo-joaquin-guzman-loera-tambien-tiene-hip-hop-corridos/|title=Televisa Espect\u00e1culos secci\u00f3n de M\u00fasica|website=Espect\u00e1culos Producci\u00f3n|access-date=2018-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054527/http://espectaculos.televisa.com/musica/noticias/865919/chapo-joaquin-guzman-loera-tambien-tiene-hip-hop-corridos/|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref>have made songs dedicated Drug traffickers such as \"El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n\".\n\n=== Narco juniors ===\n\n\"Narco juniors\" are a new form of narcocultural expression. Narco juniors are the children of the older drug traffickers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.debate.com.mx/mexico/Ellos-son-los-narcojuniors-mas-poderosos-de-Mexico-20151227-0089.html|title=Ellos son los 'narcojuniors' m\u00e1s poderosos de M\u00e9xico|website=debate.com.mx|access-date=2018-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222104808/https://www.debate.com.mx/mexico/Ellos-son-los-narcojuniors-mas-poderosos-de-Mexico-20151227-0089.html|archive-date=2018-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/411526/los-narcojuniors-sinaloenses-poderosos-y-exhibicionistas|title=Los narcojuniors sinaloenses, poderosos y exhibicionistas - Proceso|date=25 July 2015|website=proceso.com.mx|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222051405/http://www.proceso.com.mx/411526/los-narcojuniors-sinaloenses-poderosos-y-exhibicionistas|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> or the children of rich entrepreneurs that get involved in drug trade \"for fun\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/177006/la-mama-de-hodoyan-recuerda-como-se-conocieron-y-convivieron-los-narcojuniors-del-cartel-de-tijuana|title=La mam\u00e1 de Hodoy\u00e1n recuerda c\u00f3mo se conocieron y convivieron los \"narcojuniors\" del C\u00e1rtel de Tijuana - Proceso|date=6 December 1997|website=proceso.com.mx|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222051410/http://www.proceso.com.mx/177006/la-mama-de-hodoyan-recuerda-como-se-conocieron-y-convivieron-los-narcojuniors-del-cartel-de-tijuana|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/2013/01/08/nacional/878467|title=Todo empez\u00f3 en Tijuana|date=22 February 2014|website=excelsior.com.mx|access-date=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211120741/http://www.excelsior.com.mx/2013/01/08/nacional/878467|archive-date=11 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> that have come to reconstitute the meaning of narcoculture and drug trafficking. Unlike their fathers or grandfathers, the narco juniors have for the most part been raised in urban wealth. The older narco traffickers were raised in rural poverty, placed a high value on family and felt connected to their people and culture. They felt a responsibility to give back to their community. The narco juniors share a cynical pride in being drug traffickers. The narco juniors place more value on spending money, parties, and luxury.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" /> The marginalized people who were helped by the older traffickers, have now become the victims of the narco juniors' aggression.<ref name=\"GaldamezMartinez\" />\n\n=== Narco religion ===\n\nNarco-superstition and religion is a major aspect of narcoculture. It is a form of [[superstition]], depicted through drug traffickers' devotion to St. [[St. Jude|Jude Thaddaeus]] (patron of lost causes and desperate situations) and [[Jesus Malverde]]. Jesus Malverde was said to be a bandit that stole from the rich to give to the poor. He lived his life running from the authorities. His image was appropriated as the patron saint of drug traffickers, the poor, and the marginalized. An altar with his name was erected in the place where it is said that he was hanged by the government.\n\nAnother aspect of narco religion is the involvement of drug traffickers with their local churches. This occurs primarily through narco limosnas (narco-donations) that drug traffickers give to the church.{{fact|date=January 2019}} Drug traffickers have also used the church to launder money. Nora Perez-Rayon Elizundia gives an example of a bishop in Aguascalientes that admitted to taking donations from a drug trafficker because he said that the money could  be \"purified\" when used for good causes.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn other parts of Mexico some drug traffickers and their hitmen pray for protection to the [[Santa Muerte|Holy Death]], a personification of death, and in some cases they practice [[Santer\u00eda]] or [[devil worship]]ing. These type of activities are not mainstream narco-behaviors, but do occur in some remote areas.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\n=== Narco propaganda ===\nNarco propaganda includes narco mantas, banners that appear in public places, such as highway overpasses and bridges. This is a way for narcos to communicate directly to the populace. These banners are also used to threaten leaders or other members of rival cartels.\nVariations of these banners include the narco poster, a message left next to a dead body, and the narco-pinta, graffiti sprayed or hand-painted on a whitewashed brick or adobe wall next to a commercial building or house.<ref name=\"Campbell, Howard\">Campbell, Howard. \"Narco-Propaganda in the Mexican 'Drug War' An Anthropological Perspective.\" (2014): Sage Journals. Web. 24 Oct. 2014. http://lap.sagepub.com/content/early/2012/04/30/0094582X12443519 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416111705/http://lap.sagepub.com/content/early/2012/04/30/0094582X12443519 |date=2016-04-16 }}</ref>\n\n=== Narco western ===\nModern literature, not only novels or poetry but also newspapers, magazines and internet publishings, are means that  tend to narrate 'real stories', or  at least what is believed to be real about  certain people involved with the narco movement. Sometimes they exaggerate  the legacy of these people, and of  the crimes they have committed, in order to intimidate their enemies or the population in general.<ref name=\"Boothroyd, Dave\">Boothroyd, Dave. Culture on Drugs: Narco-Cultural Studies of High Modernity. New York, NY, USA: Manchester University Press, 2006.</ref>\n\nThe narco western is a new literary genre that was started by Hilario Pe\u00f1a's ''Chinola Kid'' published in October 2012.  In a recent interview Hilario states that the narco western is the modern version of a western.<ref name=\"GaxiolaGraciela\" /> Instead of a horse, his character drives a truck and instead of fighting Apaches, his character must defeat criminals and the federal police in the state of Sinaloa.\n\n=== Narco cinema===\nSee: [[Mexploitation#Mexican narcocinema]]\n\nNarco cinema in Mexico started as a combination of ''[[telenovela]]s'' (soap operas) and Mexican cinema during the 1960s, where the 'golden age' of cinema collapsed due to the interest of the population in television.<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\">Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos '[http://hemisphericinstitute.org/hemi/en/e-misferica-82/gutierrez Narco and Cinema: The War Over Public Debate in Mexico] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141119025246/http://hemisphericinstitute.org/hemi/en/e-misferica-82/gutierrez |date=2014-11-19 }}', In E-MISFERICA 8.2 #Narcomachine, 2011.</ref> During the 1970s, narco cinema consisted of movies released mostly for home entertainment or 'video home', creating a B-film market that focused on very controversial topics, that with use of violence would try to create a national reality or identity. These films were mostly made with a low budget, usually under 140,000 Mexican pesos (US$10,000), telling stories about police, drug dealers and prostitutes. These films are rarely discussed in mainstream media because of their low budgets, and connection with   pop culture and low brow entertainment.<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\" />\n\nNarco cinema today controls the Mexican film market, being influential along the border between the United States and Mexico. The films deal with the identity of the narco, consisting of a struggle of an anti-hero being immersed in a border culture, articulating narratives of life, death, love, loss, hope, greed, desire, humor and violence, alongside addiction, repetition and compulsion.<ref name=\"Benavides, O. Hugo.\">Benavides, O. Hugo. Drugs, Thugs, and Divas: Telenovelas and Narco Dramas in Latin America. Austin, TX, USA: University of Texas Press, 2008.</ref>\n\nNarco cinema develops anti-norms and expresses feelings discouraged in culturally accepted institutions.<ref name=\"Benavides, O. Hugo.\" /> In this genre violence is at its most extreme, weapons and thug-like behavior taking center stage. The use of stereotyped characters and predictable plots alienates those looking for subtexts, complex story lines, and sophisticated writing, but for the poor rural people, these films are in demand because they tell the story of their lives and the lives around them.<ref name=\"Benavides, O. Hugo.\" />\n\nNarco violence is also used by mainstream films, taking inspiration from real life events that marked the country, or in other cases fictionalized events,<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\" /> example: [[Breaking Bad]].\n\nSome examples of mainstream narco cinema include ''[[Miss Bala (2011 film)|Miss Bala]]'', ''[[El Infierno]]'' and ''[[Heli (film)|Heli]]''.\n\n''Miss Bala'', a 2011 film directed by Gerardo Naranjo, that premiered in Cannes and got attention from critics, became a box office success in Mexico. Based on real life events, it tells the story of a young woman dreaming of becoming a beauty pageant queen. Narcos manipulate her to work for them, in exchange for her victory.<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\" />\n\n''El Infierno'' is a film directed by Luis Estrada. Compared to ''Miss Bala'', this film is more fictionalized and makes use of dark humor, developing empathy for the anti-hero, glorifying the drug bosses.<ref name=\" Guti\u00e9rrez, Carlos\" />\n\n''Heli'', by Mexican director Amat Escalante, is one of the most representative films of narco cinema. The director said he tried not to focus the movie around explicit violence, which is expected of drug related movies. Yet one scene from the movie was considered the most brutal in Mexican cinema, showing traffickers burning the genitals of two young men in front of a group of children. Escalante refers to this as exposition, in that it shows how Mexico's youth is being ruined by these kind of people, at times leaving them without anything to look forward to in the future. The film focuses on love, family and hope, people wanting to believe they can succeed. This hope is conveyed through the eyes of Estela, a girl who falls in love with an older boy who involves her and her family in the drug world. Overall, Heli tries to eliminate the stereotypical figure of the Mexican cowboy or ''ranchero'', where the male figure is depicted by wearing boots and a hat. Instead the film shows atrocities committed by traffickers without offering any real solutions.<ref name=\"Molina, Javier.\">Molina, Javier. \"Mexican Cinema Brings Narco-terror to the Screen.\" ''El Pa\u00eds'', 6 August 2013. Web. 25 October 2014 http://elpais.com/m/elpais/2013/08/06/inenglish/1375805458_247638.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211002031/http://elpais.com/m/elpais/2013/08/06/inenglish/1375805458_247638.html |date=2014-12-11 }}</ref>\n\n===Social media===\nCartels have been making use of the Internet over the years going from the outdated [[MySpace]], to [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gorman|first1=Ryan|title=Status: In a Mexican drug cartel . . . Pouting gangsters take to Facebook to show off their bling, molls and heavy firepower|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2487477/The-pouting-killers-Facebook-Mexicos-evil-drug-gang-soldiers-social-media-publicize-bling-cash-heavy-firepower.html|website=dailymail.co.uk|accessdate=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203122359/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2487477/The-pouting-killers-Facebook-Mexicos-evil-drug-gang-soldiers-social-media-publicize-bling-cash-heavy-firepower.html|archive-date=3 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Stroud|first1=Matt|title=Facebook becomes the new front in Mexico's drug war|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/4/1/5569878/the-dark-side-of-the-facebook-revolution|publisher=The Verge|accessdate=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131002928/http://www.theverge.com/2014/4/1/5569878/the-dark-side-of-the-facebook-revolution|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cox|first1=Joseph|title=Mexico's Drug Cartels Love Social Media|url=https://www.vice.com/read/mexicos-drug-cartels-are-using-the-internet-to-get-up-to-mischief|publisher=Vice|accessdate=26 January 2016|date=4 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126001507/http://www.vice.com/read/mexicos-drug-cartels-are-using-the-internet-to-get-up-to-mischief|archive-date=26 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Narcos at (Instagram) war! From guns and girls to big cats and big piles of cash, El Chapo's sons spark social media battles between Mexican cartel members showing off their sickening wealth|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3226232/Narcos-Instagram-war-guns-girls-big-cats-big-piles-cash-El-Chapo-s-sons-spark-social-media-battles-Mexican-cartel-members-showing-sickening-wealth.html|website=dailymail.co.uk|accessdate=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131153453/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3226232/Narcos-Instagram-war-guns-girls-big-cats-big-piles-cash-El-Chapo-s-sons-spark-social-media-battles-Mexican-cartel-members-showing-sickening-wealth.html|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico's Cartel Brats Brag About Themselves on Social Media|url=http://www.vocativ.com/underworld/drugs/mexicos-cartel-brats-brag-social-media/|website=vocativ.com|accessdate=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131054023/http://www.vocativ.com/underworld/drugs/mexicos-cartel-brats-brag-social-media/|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Here they post videos that announce themselves as a new emerging power to be feared. One of the most visited websites to follow information about events related to narco violence is ''[[El Blog del Narco]]'', which defines itself at neutral. Their only objective is to publish stories in a journalistic way. What draws the most attention are the confessional/torture videos posted, which contain lots of graphic violence, providing torture to the prisoners before being executed in front of the camera.<ref name=\"Campbell, Howard\" />\nTwitter is used to post threats to one another, and sometimes, with the use of special technology, Narcos can track other rivals in order to kill them. This can be detrimental as well, because sometimes police finds them in the same way.<ref name=\"Campbell, Howard\" /> Instagram, can be used to show off their lifestyles, which includes new cars, expensive watches, designer clothes, fine liquor, exotic pets and massive weaponry.\n\nNotable examples are [[Jos\u00e9 Rodrigo Ar\u00e9chiga Gamboa|El Chino \u00c1ntrax]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adnpolitico.com/gobierno/2014/01/04/lujo-y-viajes-en-supuestas-redes-sociales-de-chino-antrax|title=Lujo y armas, en supuestas redes sociales de 'Chino \u00c1ntrax'|publisher=|access-date=2015-10-08|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6MPka5ZuK?url=http://www.adnpolitico.com/gobierno/2014/01/04/lujo-y-viajes-en-supuestas-redes-sociales-de-chino-antrax|archive-date=2014-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/world_news/Americas/article1359366.ece?CMP=OTH-gnws-standard-2014_01_04|title=Facebook posturing helps nail Mexico's young drug barons - The Sunday Times|publisher=|access-date=2015-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201115928/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/world_news/Americas/article1359366.ece?CMP=OTH-gnws-standard-2014_01_04|archive-date=2016-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/chino-antrax-exhibicionismo-caro-los-costos-del-ego|title=RIODOCE|access-date=2015-10-08|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6MQt7xnsj?url=http://riodoce.mx/narcotrafico-2/chino-antrax-exhibicionismo-caro-los-costos-del-ego|archive-date=2014-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Claudia Ochoa Felix]], supposed leaders of [[Los \u00c1ntrax]], an enforcer gang of the Sinaloa cartel. Both captured the attention of news outlets and blogs with photos on Twitter and Instagram that showed how they enjoy the sort of spoils that Mexicans relate with the lives of successful drug traffickers.<ref name=\"Ochoa Felix, Claudia\">Ochoa Felix, Claudia. The Press Ruined My Life. Sinaloa, Mex. Press Conference. 12 June \t2014. Web. 17 Nov. 2014. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KASuJrYXv0c#t {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006105150/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KASuJrYXv0c#t |date=2014-10-06 }}</ref> Claudia posts pictures on social media, as which she poses with expensive accessories like watches, purses, designer clothes, champagne bottles, cars and planes. Also  frequently poses with big guns.  In a press release, she mentions how her life has changed after those pictures have circulated around the world, and she fears for her family's safety. She claims that all those pictures of her were modified, because she is not the one appearing in them. She also claims that she has no association whatsoever with any of the drug cartels operating in Mexico.<ref name=\"Ochoa Felix, Claudia\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Mexican drug war]]\n* [[Crime in Mexico]]\n* [[Jihobbyist]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Mexico topics}}\n\n[[Category:Illegal drug trade]]\n[[Category:Mexican culture]]\n[[Category:Drugs in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican Drug War]]\n[[Category:Illegal drug trade in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Drug culture]]\n[[Category:Subcultures]]\n[[Category:Criminal subcultures]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narcoculture_in_Mexico"}
{"title_page": "Liz Sheridan", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Liz Sheridan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Ann Sheridan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1929|4|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rye, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Dale Wales<br/>|1985|2003|end=d.}}\n| yearsactive   = 1976\u20132010\n| children       = 1\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Ann Sheridan''' (born April 10, 1929) is an American actress. She was born and raised in [[Rye, New York]], the daughter of concert singer Elizabeth Poole-Jones and classical pianist, Frank Sheridan. While best known for her role as Jerry's mother in ''[[Seinfeld]]'', her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/60/Liz-Sheridan.html|title=Liz Sheridan Biography (1929-)|author=|date=|work=filmreference.com|accessdate=16 March 2016}} While best known for her role in Seinfeld, her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheridan began her professional life in New York City as a nightclub dancer, moving on to stage work. She was cast in Broadway productions throughout the 1970s, both in musicals and plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/liz-sheridan-80515|title=Liz Sheridan|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sheridan co-starred with [[Meryl Streep]] and [[Christopher Lloyd]] in the 1977's musical, ''[[Happy End (musical)|Happy End]]'', before moving to Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/happy-end-4000#OpeningNightCast|title=Happy End|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Working in Hollywood, she came to prominence in supporting roles in over a dozen feature films and 60 [[prime time]] network television movies, mini-series, and series including ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Archie Bunker's Place]]'', ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', ''[[Newhart]]'', ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Who's the Boss?|Who's the Boss]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues|Hill St. Blues,]]'' ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'', ''[[Family Ties]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. Her first major role was playing nosy neighbor Raquel Ochmonek on the NBC TV series ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'', from 1986 to 1990. Following that she secured her most renowned and long-lived role, as [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|Jerry Seinfeld]]'s mother, Helen, in the long-running and highly rated series, ''Seinfeld''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-20-best-tv-sitcoms-of-all-time-2013-6#1-seinfeld-20|title=The 20 Best TV Sitcoms Of All Time|last=Driscoll|first=Molly|date=June 8, 2013|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She appeared in all nine seasons, from 1990 to 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/filmoseries#tt0098904|title=Filmography by TV series for Liz Sheridan (I)|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, she lived and worked in the Caribbean, \"singing and playing the piano in almost every bar and saloon in the West Indies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the 1960s, she performed in one of Julius Monk's annual cabaret reviews at Plaza 9, located in the [[Plaza Hotel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quora.com/Was-there-a-club-in-New-York-City-in-the-1970s-called-Plaza-9-all-that-Jazz|title=Was there a club in New York City in the 1970s called \"Plaza 9 & all that Jazz?\"|last=Rose|first=David S.|date=2018|website=Quora|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, with [[Andy Griffith]] and [[Doris Roberts]], Sheridan co-starred in the feature film, ''[[Play the Game (2009 film)|Play the Game]]'', a romantic comedy about a lonely, [[Widow|widowed]] [[grandfather]] who, after a 60-year hiatus, learns dating tricks from his serial romancer of a grandson. The film stirred up controversy due to its octogenarian sex scene between Sheridan and Griffith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/play-the-game-2009|title=Andy Griffith and Seinfeld's mom: I would really rather not know|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=August 26, 2009|website=Roger Ebert|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Saslow|first=Rachel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/17/AR2009081702067.html|title=Media Scan: A Movie About Aging, a DVD for Exercise, a Book About Dieting|date=18 August 2009|work=Washington Post|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile working as a dancer in New York City nightclubs, Sheridan met the then-unknown [[James Dean]]. She details a romantic relationship with Dean. She wrote a book, ''Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: A Love Story'', chronicling their time together. In it, she describes them as each other's first romantic love. Dean pursued work on the stage in New York, then film roles Hollywood. Without sure footing or a serious plan, Sheridan was not interested in following him around on both coasts, thus bringing about the end of their relationship.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Spoto|first=Donald|title=Rebel: The Life and Legend of James Dean|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1996|isbn=978-0060176563|location=New York, New York|pages=95-122}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|title=An Affair to Remember|last=Lipton|first=Michael A.|date=June 24, 1996|website=People magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|archive-date=June 24, 1996|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 1953, Sheridan departed New York for the Virgin Islands.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=298}}</ref> She lived for years in the Caribbean, settling in St. Thomas and later Puerto Rico. She earned a living as a dancer, dance instructor, and also by singing and playing piano. She, with a neighbor who had a dance troupe, won a dance contest she choreographed for the first Carnival in St. Thomas. She also won a six hundred dollar purse finishing first in a horse race, atop her mare, General\u00e9. After a brief engagement to a man, Justus Villa (aka Pancho), she realized realized she didn't want to be married to him, broke it off and returned, for a time, to New York City. There she met up again with Dean, at a party. Afterwards, in a cab, he told her, \"Nothing's lost between us. It never will be. You're a part of me and I'm a part of you. I take you with me wherever I go.\" That was the last time she saw him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainmen|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=306-319}}</ref>  Back in the Caribbean, she met jazz musician<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-2227934/william-dale-wales-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=William Dale Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=My Heritage|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kelley|first=Robin|title=Thelonious Monk: The Life and Times of an American Original|publisher=Free Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0684831909|location=New York, NY|pages=pp. 227, 229}}</ref> William \"Dale\" Wales (1917\u20132003) in Puerto Rico. They shared a life from 1960 until his death; they wed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first= |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Biography: Spouse|publisher=imdb.com|date= |accessdate=2016-06-12}}</ref> Their daughter is a photographer living in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]]. \n\nLiz Sheridan and actress Elizabeth Montgomery were best friends: \"Lizzie and Dizzie.\" Montgomery only took on the nickname \"Lizzie\" following her performance in the Emmy Award winning TV movie, ''[[The Legend of Lizzie Borden]]''; Dizzie, more commonly Dizzy, was a shortened version of \"Dizabeth,\" which is how her sister managed to pronounce her name when young.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 6, 358, 366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio|title=Liz Sheridan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They each adored horses and together they frequented the Santa Anita race track.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=The Essential Elizabeth Montgomery: A Guide to Her Magical Performances|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2013|isbn=978-1589798243|location=Lanham, MD|pages=17-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 291, 293}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0792210}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheridan, Liz}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American dancers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Dancers from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Liz Sheridan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Ann Sheridan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1929|4|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rye, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Dale Wales<br/>|1985|2003|end=d.}}\n| yearsactive   = 1976\u20132010\n| children       = 1\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Ann Sheridan''' (born April 10, 1929) is an American actress. She was born and raised in [[Rye, New York]], the daughter of concert singer Elizabeth Poole-Jones and classical pianist, Frank Sheridan. While best known for her role as Jerry's mother in ''[[Seinfeld]]'', her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/60/Liz-Sheridan.html|title=Liz Sheridan Biography (1929-)|author=|date=|work=filmreference.com|accessdate=16 March 2016}} While best known for her role in Seinfeld, her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheridan began her professional life in New York City as a nightclub dancer, moving on to stage work. She was cast in Broadway productions throughout the 1970s, both in musicals and plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/liz-sheridan-80515|title=Liz Sheridan|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sheridan co-starred with [[Meryl Streep]] and [[Christopher Lloyd]] in the 1977's musical, ''[[Happy End (musical)|Happy End]]'', before moving to Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/happy-end-4000#OpeningNightCast|title=Happy End|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Working in Hollywood, she came to prominence in supporting roles in over a dozen feature films and 60 [[prime time]] network television movies, mini-series, and series including ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Archie Bunker's Place]]'', ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', ''[[Newhart]]'', ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Who's the Boss?|Who's the Boss]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues|Hill St. Blues,]]'' ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'', ''[[Family Ties]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. Her first major role was playing nosy neighbor Raquel Ochmonek on the NBC TV series ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'', from 1986 to 1990. Following that she secured her most renowned and long-lived role, as [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|Jerry Seinfeld]]'s mother, Helen, in the long-running and highly rated series, ''Seinfeld''. She appeared in all nine seasons, from 1990 to 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/filmoseries#tt0098904|title=Filmography by TV series for Liz Sheridan (I)|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, she lived and worked in the Caribbean, \"singing and playing the piano in almost every bar and saloon in the West Indies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the 1960s, she performed in one of Julius Monk's annual cabaret reviews at Plaza 9, located in the [[Plaza Hotel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quora.com/Was-there-a-club-in-New-York-City-in-the-1970s-called-Plaza-9-all-that-Jazz|title=Was there a club in New York City in the 1970s called \"Plaza 9 & all that Jazz?\"|last=Rose|first=David S.|date=2018|website=Quora|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, with [[Andy Griffith]] and [[Doris Roberts]], Sheridan co-starred in the feature film, ''[[Play the Game (2009 film)|Play the Game]]'', a romantic comedy about a lonely, [[Widow|widowed]] [[grandfather]] who, after a 60-year hiatus, learns dating tricks from his serial romancer of a grandson. The film stirred up controversy due to its octogenarian sex scene between Sheridan and Griffith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/play-the-game-2009|title=Andy Griffith and Seinfeld's mom: I would really rather not know|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=August 26, 2009|website=Roger Ebert|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Saslow|first=Rachel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/17/AR2009081702067.html|title=Media Scan: A Movie About Aging, a DVD for Exercise, a Book About Dieting|date=18 August 2009|work=Washington Post|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile working as a dancer in New York City nightclubs, Sheridan met the then-unknown [[James Dean]]. She details a romantic relationship with Dean. She wrote a book, ''Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: A Love Story'', chronicling their time together. In it, she describes them as each other's first romantic love. Dean pursued work on the stage in New York, then film roles Hollywood. Without sure footing or a serious plan, Sheridan was not interested in following him around on both coasts, thus bringing about the end of their relationship.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Spoto|first=Donald|title=Rebel: The Life and Legend of James Dean|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1996|isbn=978-0060176563|location=New York, New York|pages=95-122}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|title=An Affair to Remember|last=Lipton|first=Michael A.|date=June 24, 1996|website=People magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|archive-date=June 24, 1996|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 1953, Sheridan departed New York for the Virgin Islands.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=298}}</ref> She lived for years in the Caribbean, settling in St. Thomas and later Puerto Rico. She earned a living as a dancer, dance instructor, and also by singing and playing piano. She, with a neighbor who had a dance troupe, won a dance contest she choreographed for the first Carnival in St. Thomas. She also won a six hundred dollar purse finishing first in a horse race, atop her mare, General\u00e9. After a brief engagement to a man, Justus Villa (aka Pancho), she realized realized she didn't want to be married to him, broke it off and returned, for a time, to New York City. There she met up again with Dean, at a party. Afterwards, in a cab, he told her, \"Nothing's lost between us. It never will be. You're a part of me and I'm a part of you. I take you with me wherever I go.\" That was the last time she saw him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainmen|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=306-319}}</ref>  Back in the Caribbean, she met jazz musician<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-2227934/william-dale-wales-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=William Dale Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=My Heritage|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kelley|first=Robin|title=Thelonious Monk: The Life and Times of an American Original|publisher=Free Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0684831909|location=New York, NY|pages=pp. 227, 229}}</ref> William \"Dale\" Wales (1917\u20132003) in Puerto Rico. They shared a life from 1960 until his death; they wed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first= |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Biography: Spouse|publisher=imdb.com|date= |accessdate=2016-06-12}}</ref> Their daughter is a photographer living in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]]. \n\nLiz Sheridan and actress Elizabeth Montgomery were best friends: \"Lizzie and Dizzie.\" Montgomery only took on the nickname \"Lizzie\" following her performance in the Emmy Award winning TV movie, ''[[The Legend of Lizzie Borden]]''; Dizzie, more commonly Dizzy, was a shortened version of \"Dizabeth,\" which is how her sister managed to pronounce her name when young.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 6, 358, 366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio|title=Liz Sheridan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They each adored horses and together they frequented the Santa Anita race track.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=The Essential Elizabeth Montgomery: A Guide to Her Magical Performances|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2013|isbn=978-1589798243|location=Lanham, MD|pages=17-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 291, 293}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0792210}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheridan, Liz}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American dancers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Dancers from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "PaulThePony", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Added citation to support statement about Seinfeld being highly rated.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liz_Sheridan"}
{"title_page": "Richard K. Lublin", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=March 2018}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Richard K. Lublin\n| image       =Lublin flight home from 69th Primetime Emmy Awards.jpg\n| caption=Richard Lublin, returning from the 69th Primetime Emmy Awards, held in Los Angeles, CA\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1939|10|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Hartford, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| residence = [[Avon, Connecticut]] and [[Naples, Florida]]\n| nationality = United States of America\n| alma mater = [[Duke University]], [[Cornell Law School]]\n| occupation  = Actor, Philanthropist, Lawyer (retired), Educator\n| spouse = Jane Lublin (d. 2016)\n}}\n'''Richard K. Lublin''' (born October 15, 1939) is an [[United States|American]] actor, philanthropist, lawyer and educator.\n\n==Early life==\nRichard K. Lublin was born in [[Hartford, Connecticut]]. He received his B.A. from [[Duke University]] in 1961, and graduated from [[Cornell Law School]] with his [[Juris Doctor]] degree in 1964.\n\n==Acting==\nRichard Lublin entered his part-time acting career in 1995 after retiring from 32 years of active law practice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://view.publitas.com/p222-6222/vl-_0817_layout/page/10-11 |title=Valley Life: From Law to \u2032Law and Order\u2032 }}</ref>  His legal and acting careers merged in 1998 when he first landed roles as an attorney in ''[[The Practice]]'' and ''[[Ally McBeal]]''. In the late 1990s, he played featured roles as a judge on ''[[Law & Order]]''. Richard also had supporting roles on highly popular television shows like ''Chicago Hope, Frasier, Rescue Me, Married with Children'' and the HBO series, ''Luck''.\n\nIn his first movie role, Richard was cast in the Sidney Lumet film ''Before the Devil Knows You\u2019re Dead'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/969469/Richard-K-Lublin |title=The New York Times: Movies & TV: Richard K. Lublin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3024977/ |title=IMDb (Internet Movie Database) }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/richard_k_lublin/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes: Flixster: }}</ref> which movie critic [[Roger Ebert]] reviewed as \u201ca superb crime melodrama.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/before-the-devil-knows-youre-dead-2007 |title=Movie Critic Roger Ebert review: }}</ref> In the film, Lublin plays \u201cMourner #4\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/352063/Before-the-Devil-Knows-You-re-Dead/cast |title=The New York Times: Movies: Before the Devil Knows You're Dead: Acting Credits: }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.imdb.com/title/tt0292963/fullcredits/cast |title=Before the Devil Knows your Dead: Full Credits: Cast (IMDb) }}</ref> and has dialog scenes with noted actors [[Albert Finney]], [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]], and [[Ethan Hawke]].\n\nIn 2017, Richard is performing in a new feature film ''The Land of Steady Habits'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6485928/combined |title=IMDb (Internet Movie Database) }}</ref> written and directed by [[Nicole Holofcener]]. Set in Connecticut, the film focuses on the journey of Anders Hill, played by [[Ben Mendelsohn]], a man in his mid-fifties who has just retired. Richard Lublin plays the role of Hill\u2019s friendly neighbor, and has dialogue with the leading actor in several scenes, as Anders laments about the changes he\u2019s experiencing along his journey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capecod.com/entertainment/former-hyannisport-resident-to-appear-in-new-feature-film/ |title=CapeCod.com: Entertainment: Former Hyannisport Resident to Appear in New Feature Film: }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Lublin\u00a0presided over the festivities and handed out awards during the closing night presentation at the\u00a0[https://artisnaples.org/naples-international-film-festival/2018/ International Film Festival in Naples, Florida] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://artisnaples.org/naples-international-film-festival/2018/ |title=2018 Naples International Film Festival }}</ref>  where Steve Martin and Martin Short performed. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/avon-resident-richard-lublin-presents-naples-film-festival/ |title=AvonPatch: Avon Resident, Richard Lublin Presents at Naples Film Festival}}</ref> Richard Lublin is a member of the Screen Actors Guild and American Federation of Television and Radio Artists ([[SAG-AFTRA]]).\n\n[[File:Richard Lublin receives Honorary Degree, Doctor of Fine Arts, from the University of Connecticut.jpg|thumb|Richard Lublin receives Honorary Degree, Doctor of Fine Arts, from the University of Connecticut]]In May 2019, Richard Lublin was honored for his unconventional bridging of two disparate careers in Law and the Arts. He received an Honorary Degree, Doctor of Fine Arts, honoris causa, from the University of Connecticut, School of Fine Arts during their commencement ceremony, where Richard was also the commencement speaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/mansfield/uconn-announces-2019-commencement-speakers/ |title=Mansfield-StorrsPatch: UConn Announces 2019 Commencement Speakers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://today.uconn.edu/2019/04/commencement-2019-speakers-hd-recipients/ |title=UConn Today: 2019 Commencement Speakers and Honorary Degree Recipients}}</ref>\n\nWhen the honorary doctorate was conferred, he was introduced with these remarks: \u201cToday, we are privileged to honor you, Richard Lublin, as a representative of what can be achieved with drive, fortitude, and imagination. As an accomplished attorney and actor, your life\u2019s work teaches us that with passion, there are no barriers to achievement.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/richard-lublin-receives-honorary-doctor-fine-arts/ |title=AvonPatch: Richard Lublin receives an Honorary Doctor of Fine Arts}}</ref>\n\n==Acting Roles==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Genre\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6485928/combined The Land of Steady Habits]'' || Friendly Neighbor || Film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[http://www.hollywood.com/news/tv/7009792/hbo-announces-new-series-luck-with-dustin-hoffman-dennis-farina-and-nick-nolte Luck]''  || Race Track Official || Television - HBO\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Rescue Me (U.S. TV series)|Rescue Me]]'' || New York Fire Chief || Television\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Before the Devil Knows You're Dead]]'' || Mourner #4 || Film\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Frasier]]'' || Coffee shop customer || Television\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Law & Order]]'' || Judge || Television\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' || Attorney || Television\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Chicago Hope]]'' || Cardiologist || Television\n|-\n| 1998 || ''Chicago Hope''|| Trauma Surgeon || Television\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[The Practice (TV Series)|The Practice]]'' || Attorney || Television\n|-\n| 1997 || ''Chicago Hope'' || ER Doctor Vincent Pellitier || Television\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Unhappily Ever After]]'' || Focus of joke || Television\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Married... with Children]]'' || Mall walker || Television\n|-\n|}\n\n==Early career==\nAfter graduating from Cornell Law School, Richard Lublin was admitted to the [[Ohio State Bar Association]] in 1964 and the [[Connecticut Bar Association]] in 1965. He was admitted to practice before Connecticut\u2019s U.S. District Court in 1969, the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Florida in 1975 and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit in 1975. Lublin was a founding partner of a prominent Connecticut law firm, which had offices in East Hartford and Avon, Conn. He retired from active law practice in 1995.\n\nRichard Lublin returned to his undergraduate alma mater, Duke University, as a guest lecturer in law from 1990-1995. He was a member of Duke University\u2019s Advisory Board of Trustees from 1988 \u20131994.\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 1993, Lublin established the Richard K. Lublin Teaching Award as one of [http://trinity.duke.edu/faculty/awards-recognition four endowed teaching awards] presented annually within Duke University\u2019s [[Trinity College of Arts & Sciences]]. The Lublin Award recognizes undergraduate teaching excellence across all educational and research programs in the humanities, social sciences and natural sciences at Duke University. According to ''Duke Today'', winners of the Lublin Scholarship and other teaching awards \u201cuse different approaches in different fields, but students and faculty colleagues said all share a passion for teaching, interest in innovative methods and give priority to developing their students\u2019 capacity to think.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.duke.edu/2011/05/teaching2011 |title=Duke Today: A Talent for Teaching:}}</ref> In October 2013, Lublin issued a national plea for other philanthropists to endow additional teaching awards at colleges and universities across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/PhilanthropyWorldMagazine/20131004005617/en |title=Philanthropy World: Richard K. Lublin Encourages Endowment of Additional Teaching Awards Nationwide:}}</ref> In 2019, Dr. Deborah Reisinger, Duke University\u2019s Trinity College of Arts & Sciences Associate Professor of the Practice of Romance Studies, became the 33rd recipient of the Richard Lublin Teaching Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/philanthropist-praises-recipient-richard-lublin-teaching-award |title=AvonPatch: Philanthropist Praises Recipient of Richard Lublin Teaching Award: Urges More Endowed Teaching Scholarships:}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nOther [http://www.richard-lublin.com/richard-lublin-duke-award.php educational scholarships] established by Lublin include: a student scholarship fund at Duke that awards a stipend to a graduating senior going on to law school, and a college scholarship award to a graduating high school senior in his hometown of Avon, Conn.\n\nMuch of Lublin\u2019s philanthropic activity has been devoted to cancer and medical research. He and his late wife Jane made significant contributions to support cancer treatment and research at the [http://cancer.uchc.edu/ Carole and Ray Neag Comprehensive Cancer Center] at [[UConn Health]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://campaignforuconn2010report.org/stories/cancer-survivors-pledge-1-million-to-fight-disease |title=2010 UCONN Foundation Report: Cancer Survivors Pledge $1 Million: }}</ref> According to a 2010 UConn Foundation report, the couple\u2019s gift \u201cwill support the work of leading clinician-scientists including [http://cancer.uchc.edu/physicians/bios/hegde.html Upendra Hegde, M.D.\"], an associate director of medical oncology in the melanoma program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2009/12/miracle-worker-physician-inspires-gift/ |title=Miracle Worker Physician Inspires Gift: }}</ref> Since 2010, the Lublins were title sponsors for UConn Health\u2019s annual \u201cWhite Coat Gala.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://courantblogs.com/java/uconn-holds-3rd-annual-white-coat-gala/ |title=Hartford Courant: UConn Holds 3rd Annual White Coat Gala}}</ref> In 2017, Richard Lublin was the Founding Title Sponsor, in memory of Jane.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eiseverywhere.com/ehome/214073/ |title=UCONN Health: 8th Annual White Coat Gala}}</ref> The Lublins also annually sponsored the UConn Cancer Research Golf Tournament, which has raised millions of dollars for cancer research since it began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2013/08/golf-tourney-boosts-cancer-research-at-health-center/ |title=UConn Today: Golf Tourney Boosts Cancer Research at Health Center}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Philanthropy-Lublin receives UCONN Medal of Honor.jpg|thumb|Carole Neag presents the Medal of Honor to Richard Lublin as the University of Connecticut President Susan Herbst looks on.]] In recognition of their extraordinary philanthropic activity, the University of Connecticut bestowed one of its highest awards - the Carole and Ray Neag Medal of Honor - to Richard and Jane Lublin at its annual White Coat Gala held on April 12, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://courantblogs.com/java/tag/richard-lublin/ |title=Hartford Courant: White Coat Gala on a Husky Blue High}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2014/04/gala-draws-support-for-uconn-health/ |title=UConn Today: Gala Draws Support for UConn Health}}</ref> After accepting the Medal of Honor, Richard Lublin said, \"The act of giving, multiplied many times, can advance research to new levels in our efforts to eliminate cancer. We've seen what can happen when a great deal of money is given to battle a disease. The AIDS virus was once a death sentence, but adequate funding has allowed pharmaceutical companies and the medical profession to develop a treatment that allows patients to go on with their lives. More progress needs to be made with the hundreds of types of cancer.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://avon.patch.com/groups/announcements/p/avon-residents-richard-and-jane-lublin-receive-uconns-neag-medal-of-honor-for-waging-war-on-cancer?ncid=newsltuspatc00000010/ |title=AvonPatch: Avon Residents Richard and Jane Lublin Receive UConn's Neag Medal of Honor for Waging War on Cancer}}</ref> In February 2015, Richard Lublin was formally appointed as an inaugural member of the Dean\u2019s Advisory Board at the UConn School of Medicine. His role on the Board is to assist the Dean in identifying and advancing the primary needs of the school for issues such as scholarship, research and faculty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naplesnews.com/ugc/news-ugc/richard-lublin-naples-resident-was-appointed-to-the-deans-advisory-board-at-the-uconn-school-of-medicine_179739 |title=Naples Daily News: Richard Lublin appointed to the Dean's Advisory Board at the UConn School of Medicine}}</ref> In 2015, Lublin was also elected to the CT and Western MA Board of the American Heart Association to help guide the organization's mission and fundraising efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naplesnews.com/ugc/news-ugc/richard-lublin-naples-resident-elected-to-the-ct-and-western-ma-board-of-the-american-heart-association_180318 |title=Naples Daily News: Richard Lublin, Naples resident elected to the CT and Western MA Board of the American Heart Association}}</ref> Richard Lublin continued his active involvement in the fight against cancer as chairman of the 2018 American Cancer Society's (ACS) Naples, FL Annual Bucket List Gala. This prestigious fundraiser has raised more than $5.5 million since its inception in 2011. Funds raised help the ACS fund its mission to save and celebrate lives, and to lead the fight for a world without cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acsbucketlistbash.com/meet-our-chair |title=ACS Bucket List Bash: American Cancer Society Announces Event Chair for 2018 Bucket List Bash}}</ref> For the 2018 event, Lublin hired the legendary Diana Ross to attract donors. The successful fundraiser drew 500 attendees and raised more than one million dollars for the American Cancer Society. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/avon-resident-richard-lublin-chairs-american-cancer-society-event |title=Avon Resident Richard Lublin Chairs American Cancer Society Event}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/community/avon/hc-ugc-article-avon-resident-richard-lublin-chairs-successfu-2018-04-19-story.html |title=Avon Resident Richard Lublin Chairs Successful American Cancer Society Fundraiser: Gala features Diana Ross performance - raises over one million}}</ref> In 2018, Richard Lublin was elected as a member of the prestigious [https://www.cancer.org/involved/donate/leadership-giving/laureate-society.html Laureate Society] for making important strides in cancer care and cancer research. Members from the society review and evaluate grant requests for medical research annually to help determine the best investments. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/richard-lublin-elected-prestigious-laureate-society/ |title=AvonPatch: Richard Lublin Elected to the Prestigious Laureate Society}}</ref>\n \nIn 1992, the Lublins established the Jane and Richard Lublin Research and Endowment Fund at the Lahey Clinic in Burlington, Mass. They later awarded the Lahey Clinic leadership gifts for research in prostate and bladder cancer, urology, and effective pain management for cancer and trauma patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lahey.org/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&ItemID=1857 |title=2004 Lahey Clinic Benefactor journal: }}</ref> In 2014, the Lahey Clinic recognized the Lublins for their \"22 years of philanthropic support of cancer research and pain management initiatives at the Lahey Hospital & Medical Center.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naplesnews.com/ugc/news-ugc/philanthropists-richard-and-jane-lublin-receive-certificate-of-appreciation-from-lahey-hospital-medical-center_132293 |title=Naples Daily News: Philanthropists Richard and Jane Lublin Receive Certificate of Appreciation from Lahey Hospital & Medical Center}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, they helped establish a research fund for cardiovascular surgery at Hartford Hospital in honor of Dr. Hiroyoshi Takata.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2012-09-26/community/hcrs-65789hc-avon-20120924_1_heart-surgery-first-successful-heart-transplant-delicate-surgery |title=Hartford Courant: Gift Pays Tribute to Hartford Hospital Cardiovascular Surgeon }}</ref> Later that year, ''UConn Today'' reported that the Lublins made \u201cthe first philanthropic gift in support of Bioscience Connecticut initiatives at the UConn Health Center.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2012/11/uconn-health-center-receives-gift-supporting-bioscience-connecticut/ |title=UConn Today: UConn Health Center Receives Gift Supporting Bioscience Connecticut: }}</ref> According to the ''Hartford Business Journal'', [http://biosciencect.uchc.edu/ Bioscience Connecticut] is \u201cthe state\u2019s $864 million attempt to reverse a two-decade-long jobs drought by creating a vibrant bioscience sector.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20120109/PRINTEDITION/301099995/thomas-callahan-moving-quickly-to-shape-bioscience-ct/ |title=Hartford Business Journal: Thomas Callahan: Moving Quickly to Shape Bioscience CT: }}</ref> In recognition of the Lublins\u2019 generosity, UConn Health named the new waiting room in the Carole and Ray Neag Comprehensive Cancer Center in their honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2012/11/uconn-health-center-receives-gift-supporting-bioscience-connecticut/ |title=UConn Today: UConn Health Center Receives Gift Supporting Bioscience Connecticut: }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20130114/PRINTEDITION/301119961/bioscience-connecticut-receives-first-donation/ |title=Hartford Business Journal: Nonprofit Notebook: Bioscience Connecticut Receives First Donation: }}</ref>  In 1997 the Lublins honored the memory of Jane\u2019s father, who died from cancer, by donating the cost of constructing the waiting room at the [http://www.capecodhealth.org/hospitals-facilities/davenport-mugar-cancer-center/ Davenport-Mugar Cancer Center] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capecodhealth.org/hospitals-facilities/davenport-mugar-cancer-center/ |title=Cape Cod Health: Davenport Mugar Cancer Center: }}</ref> at Cape Cod Hospital in Hyannis, Mass. A plaque displayed in the waiting room reads: \u201cGiven in memory of W. Victor Jensen by Richard and Jane Lublin.\u201d\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\nOfficial website: https://www.richard-lublin.com/\n\nDuke University Teaching Awards: http://trinity.duke.edu/faculty/awards-recognition\n\nUConn Health - Carole and Ray Neag Comprehensive Cancer Center: http://cancer.uchc.edu/\n\nUConn Health - Bioscience Connecticut: http://biosciencect.uchc.edu/\n\nUConn Health \u2013 Physician Profile Upendra Hegde, M.D.: http://cancer.uchc.edu/physicians/bios/hegde.html\n\nAmerican Cancer Society - Laureate Society: https://www.cancer.org/involved/donate/leadership-giving/laureate-society.html\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lublin, Richard K.}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:People from Avon, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Hartford, Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=March 2018}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Richard K. Lublin\n| image       =Lublin flight home from 69th Primetime Emmy Awards.jpg\n| caption=Richard Lublin, returning from the 69th Primetime Emmy Awards, held in Los Angeles, CA\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1939|10|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Hartford, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| residence = [[Avon, Connecticut]] and [[Naples, Florida]]\n| nationality = United States of America\n| alma mater = [[Duke University]], [[Cornell Law School]]\n| occupation  = Actor, Philanthropist, Lawyer (retired), Educator\n| spouse = Jane Lublin (d. 2016)\n}}\n'''Richard K. Lublin''' (born October 15, 1939) is an [[United States|American]] actor, philanthropist, lawyer and educator.\n\n==Early life==\nRichard K. Lublin was born in [[Hartford, Connecticut]]. He received his B.A. from [[Duke University]] in 1961, and graduated from [[Cornell Law School]] with his [[Juris Doctor]] degree in 1964.\n\n==Acting==\nRichard Lublin entered his part-time acting career in 1995 after retiring from 32 years of active law practice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://view.publitas.com/p222-6222/vl-_0817_layout/page/10-11 |title=Valley Life: From Law to \u2032Law and Order\u2032 }}</ref>  His legal and acting careers merged in 1998 when he first landed roles as an attorney in ''[[The Practice]]'' and ''[[Ally McBeal]]''. In the late 90's, he played featured roles as a judge on ''[[Law & Order]]''. Richard also had supporting roles on highly popular television shows like ''Chicago Hope, Frasier, Rescue Me, Married with Children'' and the HBO series, ''Luck''.\n\nIn his first movie role, Richard was cast in the Sidney Lumet film ''Before the Devil Knows You\u2019re Dead'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/969469/Richard-K-Lublin |title=The New York Times: Movies & TV: Richard K. Lublin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3024977/ |title=IMDb (Internet Movie Database) }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/richard_k_lublin/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes: Flixster: }}</ref> which movie critic [[Roger Ebert]] reviewed as \u201ca superb crime melodrama.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/before-the-devil-knows-youre-dead-2007 |title=Movie Critic Roger Ebert review: }}</ref> In the film, Lublin plays \u201cMourner #4\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/352063/Before-the-Devil-Knows-You-re-Dead/cast |title=The New York Times: Movies: Before the Devil Knows You're Dead: Acting Credits: }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.imdb.com/title/tt0292963/fullcredits/cast |title=Before the Devil Knows your Dead: Full Credits: Cast (IMDb) }}</ref> and has dialog scenes with noted actors [[Albert Finney]], [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]], and [[Ethan Hawke]].\n\nIn 2017, Richard is performing in a new feature film ''The Land of Steady Habits'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6485928/combined |title=IMDb (Internet Movie Database) }}</ref> written and directed by [[Nicole Holofcener]]. Set in Connecticut, the film focuses on the journey of Anders Hill, played by [[Ben Mendelsohn]], a man in his mid-fifties who has just retired. Richard Lublin plays the role of Hill\u2019s friendly neighbor, and has dialogue with the leading actor in several scenes, as Anders laments about the changes he\u2019s experiencing along his journey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capecod.com/entertainment/former-hyannisport-resident-to-appear-in-new-feature-film/ |title=CapeCod.com: Entertainment: Former Hyannisport Resident to Appear in New Feature Film: }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Lublin\u00a0presided over the festivities and handed out awards during the closing night presentation at the\u00a0[https://artisnaples.org/naples-international-film-festival/2018/ International Film Festival in Naples, Florida] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://artisnaples.org/naples-international-film-festival/2018/ |title=2018 Naples International Film Festival }}</ref>  where Steve Martin and Martin Short performed. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/avon-resident-richard-lublin-presents-naples-film-festival/ |title=AvonPatch: Avon Resident, Richard Lublin Presents at Naples Film Festival}}</ref> Richard Lublin is a member of the Screen Actors Guild and American Federation of Television and Radio Artists ([[SAG-AFTRA]]).\n\n[[File:Richard Lublin receives Honorary Degree, Doctor of Fine Arts, from the University of Connecticut.jpg|thumb|Richard Lublin receives Honorary Degree, Doctor of Fine Arts, from the University of Connecticut]]In May 2019, Richard Lublin was honored for his unconventional bridging of two disparate careers in Law and the Arts. He received an Honorary Degree, Doctor of Fine Arts, honoris causa, from the University of Connecticut, School of Fine Arts during their commencement ceremony, where Richard was also the commencement speaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/mansfield/uconn-announces-2019-commencement-speakers/ |title=Mansfield-StorrsPatch: UConn Announces 2019 Commencement Speakers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://today.uconn.edu/2019/04/commencement-2019-speakers-hd-recipients/ |title=UConn Today: 2019 Commencement Speakers and Honorary Degree Recipients}}</ref>\n\nWhen the honorary doctorate was conferred, he was introduced with these remarks: \u201cToday, we are privileged to honor you, Richard Lublin, as a representative of what can be achieved with drive, fortitude, and imagination. As an accomplished attorney and actor, your life\u2019s work teaches us that with passion, there are no barriers to achievement.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/richard-lublin-receives-honorary-doctor-fine-arts/ |title=AvonPatch: Richard Lublin receives an Honorary Doctor of Fine Arts}}</ref>\n\n==Acting Roles==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Genre\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6485928/combined The Land of Steady Habits]'' || Friendly Neighbor || Film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[http://www.hollywood.com/news/tv/7009792/hbo-announces-new-series-luck-with-dustin-hoffman-dennis-farina-and-nick-nolte Luck]''  || Race Track Official || Television - HBO\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Rescue Me (U.S. TV series)|Rescue Me]]'' || New York Fire Chief || Television\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Before the Devil Knows You're Dead]]'' || Mourner #4 || Film\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Frasier]]'' || Coffee shop customer || Television\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Law & Order]]'' || Judge || Television\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' || Attorney || Television\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Chicago Hope]]'' || Cardiologist || Television\n|-\n| 1998 || ''Chicago Hope''|| Trauma Surgeon || Television\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[The Practice (TV Series)|The Practice]]'' || Attorney || Television\n|-\n| 1997 || ''Chicago Hope'' || ER Doctor Vincent Pellitier || Television\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Unhappily Ever After]]'' || Focus of joke || Television\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Married... with Children]]'' || Mall walker || Television\n|-\n|}\n\n==Early career==\nAfter graduating from Cornell Law School, Richard Lublin was admitted to the [[Ohio State Bar Association]] in 1964 and the [[Connecticut Bar Association]] in 1965. He was admitted to practice before Connecticut\u2019s U.S. District Court in 1969, the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Florida in 1975 and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit in 1975. Lublin was a founding partner of a prominent Connecticut law firm, which had offices in East Hartford and Avon, Conn. He retired from active law practice in 1995.\n\nRichard Lublin returned to his undergraduate alma mater, Duke University, as a guest lecturer in law from 1990-1995. He was a member of Duke University\u2019s Advisory Board of Trustees from 1988 \u20131994.\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 1993, Lublin established the Richard K. Lublin Teaching Award as one of [http://trinity.duke.edu/faculty/awards-recognition four endowed teaching awards] presented annually within Duke University\u2019s [[Trinity College of Arts & Sciences]]. The Lublin Award recognizes undergraduate teaching excellence across all educational and research programs in the humanities, social sciences and natural sciences at Duke University. According to ''Duke Today'', winners of the Lublin Scholarship and other teaching awards \u201cuse different approaches in different fields, but students and faculty colleagues said all share a passion for teaching, interest in innovative methods and give priority to developing their students\u2019 capacity to think.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.duke.edu/2011/05/teaching2011 |title=Duke Today: A Talent for Teaching:}}</ref> In October 2013, Lublin issued a national plea for other philanthropists to endow additional teaching awards at colleges and universities across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/PhilanthropyWorldMagazine/20131004005617/en |title=Philanthropy World: Richard K. Lublin Encourages Endowment of Additional Teaching Awards Nationwide:}}</ref> In 2019, Dr. Deborah Reisinger, Duke University\u2019s Trinity College of Arts & Sciences Associate Professor of the Practice of Romance Studies, became the 33rd recipient of the Richard Lublin Teaching Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/philanthropist-praises-recipient-richard-lublin-teaching-award |title=AvonPatch: Philanthropist Praises Recipient of Richard Lublin Teaching Award: Urges More Endowed Teaching Scholarships:}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nOther [http://www.richard-lublin.com/richard-lublin-duke-award.php educational scholarships] established by Lublin include: a student scholarship fund at Duke that awards a stipend to a graduating senior going on to law school, and a college scholarship award to a graduating high school senior in his hometown of Avon, Conn.\n\nMuch of Lublin\u2019s philanthropic activity has been devoted to cancer and medical research. He and his late wife Jane made significant contributions to support cancer treatment and research at the [http://cancer.uchc.edu/ Carole and Ray Neag Comprehensive Cancer Center] at [[UConn Health]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://campaignforuconn2010report.org/stories/cancer-survivors-pledge-1-million-to-fight-disease |title=2010 UCONN Foundation Report: Cancer Survivors Pledge $1 Million: }}</ref> According to a 2010 UConn Foundation report, the couple\u2019s gift \u201cwill support the work of leading clinician-scientists including [http://cancer.uchc.edu/physicians/bios/hegde.html Upendra Hegde, M.D.\"], an associate director of medical oncology in the melanoma program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2009/12/miracle-worker-physician-inspires-gift/ |title=Miracle Worker Physician Inspires Gift: }}</ref> Since 2010, the Lublins were title sponsors for UConn Health\u2019s annual \u201cWhite Coat Gala.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://courantblogs.com/java/uconn-holds-3rd-annual-white-coat-gala/ |title=Hartford Courant: UConn Holds 3rd Annual White Coat Gala}}</ref> In 2017, Richard Lublin was the Founding Title Sponsor, in memory of Jane.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eiseverywhere.com/ehome/214073/ |title=UCONN Health: 8th Annual White Coat Gala}}</ref> The Lublins also annually sponsored the UConn Cancer Research Golf Tournament, which has raised millions of dollars for cancer research since it began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2013/08/golf-tourney-boosts-cancer-research-at-health-center/ |title=UConn Today: Golf Tourney Boosts Cancer Research at Health Center}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Philanthropy-Lublin receives UCONN Medal of Honor.jpg|thumb|Carole Neag presents the Medal of Honor to Richard Lublin as the University of Connecticut President Susan Herbst looks on.]] In recognition of their extraordinary philanthropic activity, the University of Connecticut bestowed one of its highest awards - the Carole and Ray Neag Medal of Honor - to Richard and Jane Lublin at its annual White Coat Gala held on April 12, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://courantblogs.com/java/tag/richard-lublin/ |title=Hartford Courant: White Coat Gala on a Husky Blue High}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2014/04/gala-draws-support-for-uconn-health/ |title=UConn Today: Gala Draws Support for UConn Health}}</ref> After accepting the Medal of Honor, Richard Lublin said, \"The act of giving, multiplied many times, can advance research to new levels in our efforts to eliminate cancer. We've seen what can happen when a great deal of money is given to battle a disease. The AIDS virus was once a death sentence, but adequate funding has allowed pharmaceutical companies and the medical profession to develop a treatment that allows patients to go on with their lives. More progress needs to be made with the hundreds of types of cancer.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://avon.patch.com/groups/announcements/p/avon-residents-richard-and-jane-lublin-receive-uconns-neag-medal-of-honor-for-waging-war-on-cancer?ncid=newsltuspatc00000010/ |title=AvonPatch: Avon Residents Richard and Jane Lublin Receive UConn's Neag Medal of Honor for Waging War on Cancer}}</ref> In February 2015, Richard Lublin was formally appointed as an inaugural member of the Dean\u2019s Advisory Board at the UConn School of Medicine. His role on the Board is to assist the Dean in identifying and advancing the primary needs of the school for issues such as scholarship, research and faculty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naplesnews.com/ugc/news-ugc/richard-lublin-naples-resident-was-appointed-to-the-deans-advisory-board-at-the-uconn-school-of-medicine_179739 |title=Naples Daily News: Richard Lublin appointed to the Dean's Advisory Board at the UConn School of Medicine}}</ref> In 2015, Lublin was also elected to the CT and Western MA Board of the American Heart Association to help guide the organization's mission and fundraising efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naplesnews.com/ugc/news-ugc/richard-lublin-naples-resident-elected-to-the-ct-and-western-ma-board-of-the-american-heart-association_180318 |title=Naples Daily News: Richard Lublin, Naples resident elected to the CT and Western MA Board of the American Heart Association}}</ref> Richard Lublin continued his active involvement in the fight against cancer as chairman of the 2018 American Cancer Society's (ACS) Naples, FL Annual Bucket List Gala. This prestigious fundraiser has raised more than $5.5 million since its inception in 2011. Funds raised help the ACS fund its mission to save and celebrate lives, and to lead the fight for a world without cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acsbucketlistbash.com/meet-our-chair |title=ACS Bucket List Bash: American Cancer Society Announces Event Chair for 2018 Bucket List Bash}}</ref> For the 2018 event, Lublin hired the legendary Diana Ross to attract donors. The successful fundraiser drew 500 attendees and raised more than one million dollars for the American Cancer Society. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/avon-resident-richard-lublin-chairs-american-cancer-society-event |title=Avon Resident Richard Lublin Chairs American Cancer Society Event}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/community/avon/hc-ugc-article-avon-resident-richard-lublin-chairs-successfu-2018-04-19-story.html |title=Avon Resident Richard Lublin Chairs Successful American Cancer Society Fundraiser: Gala features Diana Ross performance - raises over one million}}</ref> In 2018, Richard Lublin was elected as a member of the prestigious [https://www.cancer.org/involved/donate/leadership-giving/laureate-society.html Laureate Society] for making important strides in cancer care and cancer research. Members from the society review and evaluate grant requests for medical research annually to help determine the best investments. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/richard-lublin-elected-prestigious-laureate-society/ |title=AvonPatch: Richard Lublin Elected to the Prestigious Laureate Society}}</ref>\n \nIn 1992, the Lublins established the Jane and Richard Lublin Research and Endowment Fund at the Lahey Clinic in Burlington, Mass. They later awarded the Lahey Clinic leadership gifts for research in prostate and bladder cancer, urology, and effective pain management for cancer and trauma patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lahey.org/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&ItemID=1857 |title=2004 Lahey Clinic Benefactor journal: }}</ref> In 2014, the Lahey Clinic recognized the Lublins for their \"22 years of philanthropic support of cancer research and pain management initiatives at the Lahey Hospital & Medical Center.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naplesnews.com/ugc/news-ugc/philanthropists-richard-and-jane-lublin-receive-certificate-of-appreciation-from-lahey-hospital-medical-center_132293 |title=Naples Daily News: Philanthropists Richard and Jane Lublin Receive Certificate of Appreciation from Lahey Hospital & Medical Center}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, they helped establish a research fund for cardiovascular surgery at Hartford Hospital in honor of Dr. Hiroyoshi Takata.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2012-09-26/community/hcrs-65789hc-avon-20120924_1_heart-surgery-first-successful-heart-transplant-delicate-surgery |title=Hartford Courant: Gift Pays Tribute to Hartford Hospital Cardiovascular Surgeon }}</ref> Later that year, ''UConn Today'' reported that the Lublins made \u201cthe first philanthropic gift in support of Bioscience Connecticut initiatives at the UConn Health Center.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2012/11/uconn-health-center-receives-gift-supporting-bioscience-connecticut/ |title=UConn Today: UConn Health Center Receives Gift Supporting Bioscience Connecticut: }}</ref> According to the ''Hartford Business Journal'', [http://biosciencect.uchc.edu/ Bioscience Connecticut] is \u201cthe state\u2019s $864 million attempt to reverse a two-decade-long jobs drought by creating a vibrant bioscience sector.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20120109/PRINTEDITION/301099995/thomas-callahan-moving-quickly-to-shape-bioscience-ct/ |title=Hartford Business Journal: Thomas Callahan: Moving Quickly to Shape Bioscience CT: }}</ref> In recognition of the Lublins\u2019 generosity, UConn Health named the new waiting room in the Carole and Ray Neag Comprehensive Cancer Center in their honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://today.uconn.edu/blog/2012/11/uconn-health-center-receives-gift-supporting-bioscience-connecticut/ |title=UConn Today: UConn Health Center Receives Gift Supporting Bioscience Connecticut: }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20130114/PRINTEDITION/301119961/bioscience-connecticut-receives-first-donation/ |title=Hartford Business Journal: Nonprofit Notebook: Bioscience Connecticut Receives First Donation: }}</ref>  In 1997 the Lublins honored the memory of Jane\u2019s father, who died from cancer, by donating the cost of constructing the waiting room at the [http://www.capecodhealth.org/hospitals-facilities/davenport-mugar-cancer-center/ Davenport-Mugar Cancer Center] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capecodhealth.org/hospitals-facilities/davenport-mugar-cancer-center/ |title=Cape Cod Health: Davenport Mugar Cancer Center: }}</ref> at Cape Cod Hospital in Hyannis, Mass. A plaque displayed in the waiting room reads: \u201cGiven in memory of W. Victor Jensen by Richard and Jane Lublin.\u201d\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\nOfficial website: https://www.richard-lublin.com/\n\nDuke University Teaching Awards: http://trinity.duke.edu/faculty/awards-recognition\n\nUConn Health - Carole and Ray Neag Comprehensive Cancer Center: http://cancer.uchc.edu/\n\nUConn Health - Bioscience Connecticut: http://biosciencect.uchc.edu/\n\nUConn Health \u2013 Physician Profile Upendra Hegde, M.D.: http://cancer.uchc.edu/physicians/bios/hegde.html\n\nAmerican Cancer Society - Laureate Society: https://www.cancer.org/involved/donate/leadership-giving/laureate-society.html\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lublin, Richard K.}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:People from Avon, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Hartford, Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_K._Lublin"}
{"title_page": "Perry Milou", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Perry Milou\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       =\n| birth_name     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1967|10|4}}\n| birth_place    = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = [[Art]], [[Painting]], [[Pop art]]\n| training      = [[University of Arizona]] [[Tucson, Arizona]]\n| movement      = [[Pop art]], [[Contemporary art]]\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n}}\n\n'''Perry Milou''' (born October 4, 1967) is an American contemporary [[pop artist]] known for his representational works of popular culture subjects including iconic celebrities, notable sports players, political figures and landmarks.\nCollectors and critics have noted his bold and rich palettes throughout his career.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\">{{cite book |last1=Glantz |first1=Joseph |title=Philadelphia Originals |date=2009 |publisher=Schiffer Publishing |location=Atglen, PA |isbn=978-0-7643-3338-5 }}</ref> His list of commission patrons and collectors includes names such as [[Sylvester Stallone]], [[Julius Erving]], the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]], the [[Philadelphia Eagles]]<ref name=\"Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia\">{{cite book |last1=Nickels |first1=Thom |title=Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia |date=2014 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |location=Charleston, SC |isbn=978-1-4671-0141-7 }}</ref> and [[Ed Rendell]].\nHe lives and works in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n\n[[File:VanGohing to Philly, Philadelphia skyline painting by Perry Milou.jpg|thumb|Vangoghing to Philly by Perry Milou]]\n\n== Work ==\nMilou first gained recognition in Philadelphia, with paintings of local sports heroes and landmarks which he created outdoors in a high traffic area of the city where people could see him and his work.<ref name=\"First Look Perry Milou Gallery\">{{cite news |last1=Amorosi |first1=A.D. |title=First Look Perry Milou Gallery |publisher=Philadelphia City Paper |date=June 2\u201312, 2003}}</ref>\nMilou takes an original approach while drawing influence from masters <ref name=\"Hip To Be Square\">{{cite book |last1=Waltzer |first1=James |title=Hip To Be Square |date=March 2004 |publisher=Where Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Philadelphia }}</ref>\u2013 pop stylings of [[Peter Max]] and [[Andy Warhol]], skills of [[Edgar Degas]] and brushstrokes of [[Vincent Van Gogh]].<ref name=\"Patriotic Art Becomes \u2018Melting Pot\u2019\">{{cite journal |last1=Jancsurak |first1=Joe |title=Patriotic Art Becomes 'Melting Pot' |journal=Art Business News |date=July 2005 |volume=32| issue = 7 }}</ref> He's described his art as a \"fine-pop\u201d<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\">{{cite web |last1=Melamed |first1=Samantha |title=The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/pope/20150827_His_papal_paintings_have_become_big__big_business.html |website=philly.com |publisher=Inquirer, Philly news, philly.com |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref> and \u201cin your face with vibrant colors\u201d,<ref name=\"Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia\" /> and said \u201cmy art peters between commercial and [[fine art]].\u201d Others have coined his style as \u201cpop-[[Impressionist art|impressionist]]\u201c.<ref name=\"First Look Perry Milou Gallery\" />\nIn the late 2000s he developed a technique which he called \u201crain,\u201d dripping oil paint vertically down the canvas,<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> creating the sensation of looking through a rain streaked window. An example of this technique is ''The Dreary Dean'', which depicts the tragic moodiness of [[James Dean]] in portrait.<ref name=\"Hot Tips Art Scene\">{{cite book | last1=Zeleniak |first1=James | last2=Brown | first2=Gerard |title=Hot Tips Art Scene |date=July 2003 |publisher=Where Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Philadelphia }}</ref> Other works combined [[Swarovski]] crystals with this painting technique, like his ''Vegas Icons Playing Cards'' series.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />\nHis portfolio's long list of recognizable figures includes names such as [[Liz Taylor]], [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Frida Kahlo]], [[Geronimo]], characters from television's [[The Sopranos]],<ref name=\"Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia\" /> [[Frank Sinatra]], [[George W. Bush]],<ref name=\"Patriotic Art Becomes \u2018Melting Pot\u2019\" /> Rocky Balboa,<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> the [[Dalai Lama]], [[Nelson Mandela]], [[Sophia Loren]], [[Jackie Kennedy]], [[Robin Williams]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Barbra Streisand]], Sylvester Stallone, [[Elvis Presley]], [[Lady Gaga]], [[Chazz Palminteri]], [[Cole Hamels]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], and [[Albert Einstein]].<ref name=\"The Delaware Velley Italian-American Herold\">{{cite news |last1=Zippi |first1=Barbara Ann |title=Italian Culture, Inside the colorful world of the man who painted the pope |volume=2 |issue=9 |publisher=The Delaware Velley Italian-American Herold |date=September 2015}}</ref> In 2007 his Marilyn Monroe series was featured in the ''Marylin in Art'' book published by Cantor Publishing Group.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> In January 2017, Milou presented [[Joe Biden]] his portrait of the former US Vice President upon his return home to Delaware after the [[inauguration]].<ref name=\"Carson Wentz meets Philly artist who painted his portrait\">{{cite news |last1=Koller |first1=Brock |title=Carson Wentz meets Philly artist who painted his portrait |url=http://6abc.com/sports/wentz-meets-philly-artist-who-painted-his-portrait/2090454/ |accessdate=2 June 2018 |agency=6ABC News |publisher=6ABC News |date=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\u201cI am constantly looking at the sky; it is the closest thing to watching God paint in the present moment.\u201d<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />\n\n=== ''Vegas Icons Playing Cards'' Series ===\nIn the 2000s, Milou created a series of 16 \u201cplaying cards\u201d,<ref name=\"The Art Of The Entrepreneur\">{{cite book |last1=Delahauterive |first1=Huey |title=The Art Of The Entrepreneur |date=2008 |publisher=Symposium Magazine, Troy Publishing Inc. }}</ref> multi-media oil paintings embellished with Swarovski Crystals and [[decoupage]].<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />  Each painting featured a pop icon which he paired with a suited insignia and corresponding quote, using different painting techniques to represent the characteristics of each character. This series includes [[Bono]] as the two of clubs, Elvis Presley the king of spades, and Marilyn Monroe queen of diamonds.<ref name=\"The Art Of The Entrepreneur\" />\n\n=== ''Lover Lips'' Series ===\nContinuing to work in series, Milou developed a collection of large scale oil paintings in his \"rain\" style thematically centered on lips. This series includes subjects from classic actresses such as [[Sophia Loren]] and [[Brigitte Bardot]] to modern one's like [[Angelina Jolie]] and [[Jessica Alba]].<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />\n\n=== ''Pucker Up Project'' ===\nIn 2008, after moving to Miami, Milou was one of many artists to open his gallery doors for [[Art Basel Miami|Art Basel]]. During this time he created The ''Pucker Up Project'',<ref name=\"Main Event, Art Basel Preview\">{{cite book |last1=Martin |first1=Richard |title=Main Event, Art Basel Preview |date=November 2008 |publisher=Miami Magazine, Modern Luxury Media |location=Miami }}</ref> a series of three 8x8ft paintings. Each canvas included 1,024 painted square sections that combined created the image on each canvas, an effect like [[pointillism]] Anticipating large crowds, he linked this interactive project to charity and charged $100 to kiss a square.<ref name=\"The Art Of The Entrepreneur\" /> Proceeds went to benefit the Sylvester Comprehensive Cancer Center.<ref name=\"Main Event, Art Basel Preview\" />\n\n[[File:Prayer for Peace, Pope Francis painting by Perry Milou.jpg|thumb|A Prayer for Peace by Perry Milou]]\n\n=== ''A Prayer for Peace'' ===\nIn 2015 Milou's painting ''A Prayer For Peace'' became the official licensed portrait by The [[World Meeting of Families]] for the Papal visit to Philadelphia. Inspired by [[Pope Francis]], Milou created a series of paintings he coined ''The Faces of Francis''.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" /> The first licensed painting ''A Prayer for Peace'' portrayed Francis in profile blowing a kiss<ref name=\"Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis\">{{cite news |first1=Cherri | last1=Gregg | first2=Jan | last2=Carabeo |title=Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis |url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2015/08/19/artist-world-meeting-of-families-portrait-pope-francis/ |accessdate=2 June 2018 |agency=CBS Philly |publisher=CBS Philly |date=August 19, 2015}}</ref> with the earth as the background, painted in Milou's \u201crain\u201d technique.<ref name=\"Brush With Fate\">{{cite book |last1=Amorosi |first1=A.D. |title=Brush With Fate |date=Fall 2015 |publisher=Philadelphia Style Magazine, Niche Media Holdings |location=New York, New York }}</ref> The second ''Holy Day'' depicts Francis outside the Philadelphia Museum of Art. ''A Prayer for Peace'' is priced at $1,000,000 with a majority of the proceeds designated to charity.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis\" />\nThe organization negotiated a percentage-based licensing deal with Milou, which led to a line of official merchandise - posters, mugs, paperweights, tote bags \u2013 developed through retailer [[Aramark]]. This deal led to more partnerships for the event, including 15 more Pope centered products and prints of the paintings with text like \u201cIrish Blessings\u201d, \u201cAmore\u201d and \"Feliz Natal\".<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" />\nMilou believes this honor came from a higher power and [[Miracle|divine intervention]] made everything fall into place, sharing \u201cdivine coincidences\u201d about his life - being born on October 4, St. Francis Day,<ref name=\"Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis\" /> his grandfather's name Francis DeFrancesco, mother Angel, wife Angela, father in law Angelo, nanny Angelica, daughter Francesca and his son due to be born the week Pope Francis arrived in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"The Delaware Velley Italian-American Herold\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/08/28/perry-milou-pope-painting-getty-images/|title=Welcome {{!}} Philadelphia Magazine|website=www.phillymag.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2015/08/19/artist-world-meeting-of-families-portrait-pope-francis/|title=Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting Of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis|date=2015-08-19|access-date=2018-06-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports icons ===\nMilou began including sports players in paintings in the early 2000s, especially when a local team was on a championship run.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" /> An early example being ''The Franchise'' created in 2001, a 7x4.5&nbsp;ft oil painting featuring [[76ers]] [[Allen Iverson]], [[Wilt Chamberlain]], [[Charles Barkley]], and [[Julius Erving]]. \u201cI attempted to depict the four greatest Sixers from the team\u2019s history.\u201d<ref name=\"City artist pictured four of team\u2019s greatest stars in latest work\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Ramona |title=City artist pictured four of team's greatest stars in latest work |url=http://www.philly.com/ |accessdate=2 June 2018 |agency=Philadelphia Daily News |publisher=Philadelphia Daily News |date=June 12, 2001}}</ref> Milou continued works in similar fashion throughout the years, another example including four quarterbacks from the [[Eagles football|Eagles]] - Norm VanBrocklin, Ron Jaworski, Randall Cunningham and Donovan McNabb.<ref name=\"Shortly noted\">{{cite news |last1=Klein |first1=Michael |title=Shortly noted |agency=Philadelphia Inquirer |publisher=Philadelphia Inquirer |date=January 7, 2003}}</ref> More recently, Milou created a 48x36in oil portrait of Eagles quarterback [[Carson Wentz]]<ref name=\"Carson Wentz meets Philly artist who painted his portrait\" /> titled ''Faith in Green''. Upon the Eagles 2018 NFL [[Super Bowl LII]] win, Milou conceived ''Next Dog Up'', a 4x5ft canvas depicting [[Vince Lombardi]] trophy topped by a German shepherd wearing an Eagles helmet, [[Rocky Balboa]] and cartoon character [[Underdog (TV series)|Underdog]].<ref name=\"Philly artist, lifelong Eagles fan creates an ode to the underdogs\">{{cite news |title=Philly artist, lifelong Eagles fan creates an ode to the underdogs |url=http://6abc.com/sports/philly-artist-creates-an-ode-to-the-underdogs/3027720/ |accessdate=2 June 2018 |agency=6ABC |publisher=6ABC |date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Commissions ===\nIn 2001 Milou was commissioned by the Philadelphia Museum of Art to create two large oil paintings. The pair of paintings portrayed the two famous facades of the building using Milou's take on Van Gogh style techniques. He was commissioned by the museum again in 2007 to paint a portrait of [[Benjamin Franklin]] in celebration of the founding father's 300th birthday.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />\n\n=== Collaborations ===\nIn 2004 Milou teamed up with artist Charles Cushing to create a collaborative series of 8x5ft canvases depicting different streets of Philadelphia.<ref name=\"Hip To Be Square\" /> Milou and Cushing had been painting outdoors together for years, so they claimed \u201cthe vibrant Philly street scene was a natural choice of subject.\u201d<ref name=\"Taking Art to the Streets\">{{cite news |last1=Gale |first1=D.S. |title=Taking Art to the Streets |agency=Philadelphia City Paper |publisher=Philadelphia City Paper |date=2001}}</ref> \u201cIt\u2019s spontaneous creation, we paint simultaneously \u2013 it\u2019s like dueling brushes.\u201d<ref name=\"Hip To Be Square\" /> They then took the set of paintings, along with 500 signed and numbered lithograph prints, to the streets of Philadelphia to sell directly to customers and to local shops. The first painting in the series of [[Center City, Philadelphia]], titled ''Uptown Philly 2000'', was sold to a couple for $7,500. The second large canvas was a montage of [[Old City, Philadelphia]] where Milou lived at the time.<ref name=\"Taking Art to the Streets\" />\nContinuing in 2004, Milou alongside Thomas Dellapenna and Brett Sauce, created paintings of Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes winner [[Smarty Jones]]. The paintings were displayed together in Milou's gallery.<ref name=\"Horse of another color\">{{cite news |last1=Klein |first1=Michael |title=Horse of another color |agency=The Philadelphia Inquirer |publisher=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=2004}}</ref>\nHe again worked with Dellapenna in 2005 to create their painting ''On The Town'', which is 6x8ft with the hefty price tag of $12,500.<ref name=\"Gallery Philadelphia Art\">{{cite book |last1=Zeleniak |first1=James |title=Gallery Philadelphia Art |date=January 2005 |publisher=Wherer Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Philadelphia }}</ref>\n\n== Galleries ==\nAfter working and promoting himself outdoors for years in [[Rittenhouse Square]], Milou gained enough recognition and finance to open a gallery in the area. He saw initial potential in Philadelphia's market,<ref name=\"Will he stay or will he go now?\u201d\">{{cite book |last1=Midgley |first1=Brook |title=Will he stay or will he go now? |date=Fall 2005 |publisher=Sink Magazine |location=Philadelphia }}</ref> opening his first gallery in 2003. The eponymous ''Perry Milou Gallery'' served as an indoor studio and exhibition for people to visit after watching him paint outdoors for the previous four years.<ref name=\"Hot Tips Art Scene\" /> In 2005 he moved the gallery to a different location down the street.<ref name=\"Gallery Philadelphia Art\" /> Milou opened his third gallery ''Galleria 1903'' in 2007, continuing to showcase his personal work as well as other local artists.<ref name=\"Philly in a Day\">{{cite book |last1=Rosenberg |first1=Meredith |title=Philly in a Day |date=August 2007 |publisher=Where Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Philadelphia }}</ref>\nAfter years as a gallerist in Philadelphia, the businessman in Milou had him looking to other larger markets where more people would be willing to invest in quality artwork at higher price points.<ref name=\"Will he stay or will he go now?\u201d\" />\nAfter closing ''Galleria 1903'' and leaving Philadelphia, Milou moved to Miami where he opened his fourth gallery in May 2008.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> ''Milou Gallery'' was located in Miami's Wynwood Art District,<ref name=\"New Gallery Openings\">{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Irene |title=New Gallery Openings |date=July 2008 |publisher=Where Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Miami }}</ref> where Milou was hoping to capitalize on the art market that was fueled by the annual Art Basel showcase.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" />\n\n== Community/Philanthropy ==\nIn the late 1990s during the very start of his career, Milou opened ''American Milou\u2019s Studio for Children'' in [[Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Hip To Be Square\" /> Through the 2000s\u2019 Milou was involved in philanthropic organizations such as Co-Founder of Philadelphia Art for ALS, the [[Susan G. Komen for the Cure|Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer Foundation]], an annual supporter of CVI, the Cardiovascular Institute of Philadelphia, MOCA Shakers and Gen. Art. In 2009 Milou provided a series of art workshops called \u201c''Palette Kids''\u201d while he was living in Miami, in collaboration with the [[Miami Children's Museum]].<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> Milou has sold several paintings in silent auctions and donated the proceeds to charitable organizations, including his own retrospective show in 2013 featuring 50 of his original paintings with proceeds donated to the Philadelphia Animal Welfare Society and One Fund Boston.<ref name=\"Milou Retrospective\">{{cite book |last1=Lidor |first1=Fryda |title=Milou Retrospective |date=Summer 2013 |publisher=Philadelphia Style Magazine, Niche Media Holdings |location=Philadelphia }}</ref> Another being the Second Annual Bubby's Cook-off in 2014 in which the proceeds went to the Friendship Circle Foundation.<ref name=\"The Second Annual Bubby\u2019s Cook-off\">{{cite book |last1=Dillon |first1=Hughe |title=The Second Annual Bubby's Cook-off |date=February 28, 2014 |publisher=Philadelphia Magazine |location=Philadelphia |url=https://www.phillymag.com/the-scene/2014/02/28/bubbys-cook-off-friendship-circle-lubavitch-bucks-county/#gallery-2-1 |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nMilou regularly worked and displayed his finished paintings in the corner of Rittenhouse Square until the Park Commission got involved in 2002. The Commission claimed receiving several complaints about Milou, and though Milou claimed he never transacted a sale inside the park, the Commission director said that was irrelevant and began to enforce the no-solicitation policy by initiating ranger patrols through the Square. Milou said he planned to continue painting in the park.<ref name=\"Rittenhouse Smackdown\">{{cite book |last1=Fiorillo |first1=Victor |title=Rittenhouse Smackdown |date=August 2002 |publisher=Philadelphia Magazine |location=Philadelphia |url=https://www.phillymag.com/ |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMilou was raised in the [[Cheltenham Township, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Cheltenham]]-[[Mount Airy, Philadelphia|Mount Airy]] and [[Haverford Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Haverford]] suburbs near Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"City artist pictured four of team\u2019s greatest stars in latest work\" /> He graduated from the [[University of Arizona]],<ref name=\"Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia\" /> where he studied graphic design and illustration.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" /> While attending university, he was the first student to convince the Bachelor of Fine Arts program to include \u201copen studio\u201d as a major in 1990.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> After college he moved back to Philadelphia.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" /> Milou now resides in Pennsylvania with his wife, daughter and son.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milou, Perry}}\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:Pop artists]]\n[[Category:Painters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Artists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:American contemporary painters]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Perry Milou\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       =\n| birth_name     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1967|10|4}}\n| birth_place    = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = [[Art]], [[Painting]], [[Pop art]]\n| training      = [[University of Arizona]] [[Tucson, Arizona]]\n| movement      = [[Pop art]], [[Contemporary art]]\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n}}\n\n'''Perry Milou''' (born October 4, 1967) is an American contemporary [[pop artist]] known for his representational works of popular culture subjects including iconic celebrities, notable sports players, political figures and landmarks.\nCollectors and critics have noted his bold and rich palettes throughout his career.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\">{{cite book |last1=Glantz |first1=Joseph |title=Philadelphia Originals |date=2009 |publisher=Schiffer Publishing |location=Atglen, PA |isbn=978-0-7643-3338-5 }}</ref> His list of commission patrons and collectors includes names such as [[Sylvester Stallone]], [[Julius Erving]], the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]], the [[Philadelphia Eagles]]<ref name=\"Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia\">{{cite book |last1=Nickels |first1=Thom |title=Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia |date=2014 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |location=Charleston, SC |isbn=978-1-4671-0141-7 }}</ref> and [[Ed Rendell]].\nHe lives and works in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n\n[[File:VanGohing to Philly, Philadelphia skyline painting by Perry Milou.jpg|thumb|Vangoghing to Philly by Perry Milou]]\n\n== Work ==\nMilou first gained recognition in Philadelphia, with paintings of local sports heroes and landmarks which he created outdoors in a high traffic area of the city where people could see him and his work.<ref name=\"First Look Perry Milou Gallery\">{{cite news |last1=Amorosi |first1=A.D. |title=First Look Perry Milou Gallery |publisher=Philadelphia City Paper |date=June 2\u201312, 2003}}</ref>\nMilou takes an original approach while drawing influence from masters <ref name=\"Hip To Be Square\">{{cite book |last1=Waltzer |first1=James |title=Hip To Be Square |date=March 2004 |publisher=Where Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Philadelphia }}</ref>\u2013 pop stylings of [[Peter Max]] and [[Andy Warhol]], skills of [[Edgar Degas]] and brushstrokes of [[Vincent Van Gogh]].<ref name=\"Patriotic Art Becomes \u2018Melting Pot\u2019\">{{cite journal |last1=Jancsurak |first1=Joe |title=Patriotic Art Becomes 'Melting Pot' |journal=Art Business News |date=July 2005 |volume=32| issue = 7 }}</ref> He's described his art as a \"fine-pop\u201d<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\">{{cite web |last1=Melamed |first1=Samantha |title=The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/pope/20150827_His_papal_paintings_have_become_big__big_business.html |website=philly.com |publisher=Inquirer, Philly news, philly.com |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref> and \u201cin your face with vibrant colors\u201d,<ref name=\"Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia\" /> and said \u201cmy art peters between commercial and [[fine art]].\u201d Others have coined his style as \u201cpop-[[Impressionist art|impressionist]]\u201c.<ref name=\"First Look Perry Milou Gallery\" />\nIn the late 2000s he developed a technique which he called \u201crain,\u201d dripping oil paint vertically down the canvas,<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> creating the sensation of looking through a rain streaked window. An example of this technique is ''The Dreary Dean'', which depicts the tragic moodiness of [[James Dean]] in portrait.<ref name=\"Hot Tips Art Scene\">{{cite book | last1=Zeleniak |first1=James | last2=Brown | first2=Gerard |title=Hot Tips Art Scene |date=July 2003 |publisher=Where Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Philadelphia }}</ref> Other works combined [[Swarovski]] crystals with this painting technique, like his ''Vegas Icons Playing Cards'' series.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />\nHis portfolio's long list of recognizable figures includes names such as [[Liz Taylor]], [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Frida Kahlo]], [[Geronimo]], characters from television's [[The Sopranos]],<ref name=\"Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia\" /> [[Frank Sinatra]], [[George W. Bush]],<ref name=\"Patriotic Art Becomes \u2018Melting Pot\u2019\" /> Rocky Balboa,<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> the [[Dalai Lama]], [[Nelson Mandela]], [[Sophia Loren]], [[Jackie Kennedy]], [[Robin Williams]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Barbra Streisand]], Sylvester Stallone, [[Elvis Presley]], [[Lady Gaga]], [[Chazz Palminteri]], [[Cole Hamels]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], and [[Albert Einstein]].<ref name=\"The Delaware Velley Italian-American Herold\">{{cite news |last1=Zippi |first1=Barbara Ann |title=Italian Culture, Inside the colorful world of the man who painted the pope |volume=2 |issue=9 |publisher=The Delaware Velley Italian-American Herold |date=September 2015}}</ref> In 2007 his Marilyn Monroe series was featured in the ''Marylin in Art'' book published by Cantor Publishing Group.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> In January 2017, Milou presented [[Joe Biden]] his portrait of the former US Vice President upon his return home to Delaware after the [[inauguration]].<ref name=\"Carson Wentz meets Philly artist who painted his portrait\">{{cite news |last1=Koller |first1=Brock |title=Carson Wentz meets Philly artist who painted his portrait |url=http://6abc.com/sports/wentz-meets-philly-artist-who-painted-his-portrait/2090454/ |accessdate=2 June 2018 |agency=6ABC News |publisher=6ABC News |date=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\u201cI am constantly looking at the sky; it is the closest thing to watching God paint in the present moment.\u201d<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />\n\n=== ''Vegas Icons Playing Cards'' Series ===\nIn the 2000s, Milou created a series of 16 \u201cplaying cards\u201d,<ref name=\"The Art Of The Entrepreneur\">{{cite book |last1=Delahauterive |first1=Huey |title=The Art Of The Entrepreneur |date=2008 |publisher=Symposium Magazine, Troy Publishing Inc. }}</ref> multi-media oil paintings embellished with Swarovski Crystals and [[decoupage]].<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />  Each painting featured a pop icon which he paired with a suited insignia and corresponding quote, using different painting techniques to represent the characteristics of each character. This series includes [[Bono]] as the two of clubs, Elvis Presley the king of spades, and Marilyn Monroe queen of diamonds.<ref name=\"The Art Of The Entrepreneur\" />\n\n=== ''Lover Lips'' Series ===\nContinuing to work in series, Milou developed a collection of large scale oil paintings in his \"rain\" style thematically centered on lips. This series includes subjects from classic actresses such as [[Sophia Loren]] and [[Brigitte Bardot]] to modern one's like [[Angelina Jolie]] and [[Jessica Alba]].<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />\n\n=== ''Pucker Up Project'' ===\nIn 2008, after moving to Miami, Milou was one of many artists to open his gallery doors for [[Art Basel Miami|Art Basel]]. During this time he created The ''Pucker Up Project'',<ref name=\"Main Event, Art Basel Preview\">{{cite book |last1=Martin |first1=Richard |title=Main Event, Art Basel Preview |date=November 2008 |publisher=Miami Magazine, Modern Luxury Media |location=Miami }}</ref> a series of three 8x8ft paintings. Each canvas included 1,024 painted square sections that combined created the image on each canvas, an effect like [[pointillism]] Anticipating large crowds, he linked this interactive project to charity and charged $100 to kiss a square.<ref name=\"The Art Of The Entrepreneur\" /> Proceeds went to benefit the Sylvester Comprehensive Cancer Center.<ref name=\"Main Event, Art Basel Preview\" />\n\n[[File:Prayer for Peace, Pope Francis painting by Perry Milou.jpg|thumb|A Prayer for Peace by Perry Milou]]\n\n=== ''A Prayer for Peace'' ===\nIn 2015 Milou's painting ''A Prayer For Peace'' became the official licensed portrait by The [[World Meeting of Families]] for the Papal visit to Philadelphia. Inspired by [[Pope Francis]], Milou created a series of paintings he coined ''The Faces of Francis''.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" /> The first licensed painting ''A Prayer for Peace'' portrayed Francis in profile blowing a kiss<ref name=\"Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis\">{{cite news |first1=Cherri | last1=Gregg | first2=Jan | last2=Carabeo |title=Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis |url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2015/08/19/artist-world-meeting-of-families-portrait-pope-francis/ |accessdate=2 June 2018 |agency=CBS Philly |publisher=CBS Philly |date=August 19, 2015}}</ref> with the earth as the background, painted in Milou's \u201crain\u201d technique.<ref name=\"Brush With Fate\">{{cite book |last1=Amorosi |first1=A.D. |title=Brush With Fate |date=Fall 2015 |publisher=Philadelphia Style Magazine, Niche Media Holdings |location=New York, New York }}</ref> The second ''Holy Day'' depicts Francis outside the Philadelphia Museum of Art. ''A Prayer for Peace'' is priced at $1,000,000 with a majority of the proceeds designated to charity.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis\" />\nThe organization negotiated a percentage-based licensing deal with Milou, which led to a line of official merchandise - posters, mugs, paperweights, tote bags \u2013 developed through retailer [[Aramark]]. This deal led to more partnerships for the event, including 15 more Pope centered products and prints of the paintings with text like \u201cIrish Blessings\u201d, \u201cAmore\u201d and \"Feliz Natal\".<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" />\nMilou believes this honor came from a higher power and [[Miracle|divine intervention]] made everything fall into place, sharing \u201cdivine coincidences\u201d about his life - being born on October 4, St. Francis Day,<ref name=\"Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis\" /> his grandfather's name Francis DeFrancesco, mother Angel, wife Angela, father in law Angelo, nanny Angelica, daughter Francesca and his son due to be born the week Pope Francis arrived in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"The Delaware Velley Italian-American Herold\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/08/28/perry-milou-pope-painting-getty-images/|title=Welcome {{!}} Philadelphia Magazine|website=www.phillymag.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2015/08/19/artist-world-meeting-of-families-portrait-pope-francis/|title=Philadelphia Artist Creates Official World Meeting Of Families Portrait Of Pope Francis|date=2015-08-19|access-date=2018-06-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports icons ===\nMilou began including sports players in paintings in the early 2000s, especially when a local team was on a championship run.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" /> An early example being ''The Franchise'' created in 2001, a 7x4.5&nbsp;ft oil painting featuring [[76ers]] [[Allen Iverson]], [[Wilt Chamberlain]], [[Charles Barkley]], and [[Julius Erving]]. \u201cI attempted to depict the four greatest Sixers from the team\u2019s history.\u201d<ref name=\"City artist pictured four of team\u2019s greatest stars in latest work\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Ramona |title=City artist pictured four of team's greatest stars in latest work |url=http://www.philly.com/ |accessdate=2 June 2018 |agency=Philadelphia Daily News |publisher=Philadelphia Daily News |date=June 12, 2001}}</ref> Milou continued works in similar fashion throughout the years, another example including four quarterbacks from the [[Eagles football|Eagles]] - Norm VanBrocklin, Ron Jaworski, Randall Cunningham and Donovan McNabb.<ref name=\"Shortly noted\">{{cite news |last1=Klein |first1=Michael |title=Shortly noted |agency=Philadelphia Inquirer |publisher=Philadelphia Inquirer |date=January 7, 2003}}</ref> More recently, Milou created a 48x36in oil portrait of Eagles quarterback [[Carson Wentz]]<ref name=\"Carson Wentz meets Philly artist who painted his portrait\" /> titled ''Faith in Green''. Upon the Eagles 2018 NFL [[Super Bowl LII]] win, Milou conceived ''Next Dog Up'', a 4x5ft canvas depicting [[Vince Lombardi]] trophy topped by a German shepherd wearing an Eagles helmet, [[Rocky Balboa]] and cartoon character [[Underdog (TV series)|Underdog]].<ref name=\"Philly artist, lifelong Eagles fan creates an ode to the underdogs\">{{cite news |title=Philly artist, lifelong Eagles fan creates an ode to the underdogs |url=http://6abc.com/sports/philly-artist-creates-an-ode-to-the-underdogs/3027720/ |accessdate=2 June 2018 |agency=6ABC |publisher=6ABC |date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Commissions ===\nIn 2001 Milou was commissioned by the Philadelphia Museum of Art to create two large oil paintings. The pair of paintings portrayed the two famous facades of the building using Milou's take on Van Gogh style techniques. He was commissioned by the museum again in 2007 to paint a portrait of [[Benjamin Franklin]] in celebration of the founding father's 300th birthday.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" />\n\n=== Collaborations ===\nIn 2004 Milou teamed up with artist Charles Cushing to create a collaborative series of 8x5ft canvases depicting different streets of Philadelphia.<ref name=\"Hip To Be Square\" /> Milou and Cushing had been painting outdoors together for years, so they claimed \u201cthe vibrant Philly street scene was a natural choice of subject.\u201d<ref name=\"Taking Art to the Streets\">{{cite news |last1=Gale |first1=D.S. |title=Taking Art to the Streets |agency=Philadelphia City Paper |publisher=Philadelphia City Paper |date=2001}}</ref> \u201cIt\u2019s spontaneous creation, we paint simultaneously \u2013 it\u2019s like dueling brushes.\u201d<ref name=\"Hip To Be Square\" /> They then took the set of paintings, along with 500 signed and numbered lithograph prints, to the streets of Philadelphia to sell directly to customers and to local shops. The first painting in the series of [[Center City, Philadelphia]], titled ''Uptown Philly 2000'', was sold to a couple for $7,500. The second large canvas was a montage of [[Old City, Philadelphia]] where Milou lived at the time.<ref name=\"Taking Art to the Streets\" />\nContinuing in 2004, Milou alongside Thomas Dellapenna and Brett Sauce, created paintings of Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes winner [[Smarty Jones]]. The paintings were displayed together in Milou's gallery.<ref name=\"Horse of another color\">{{cite news |last1=Klein |first1=Michael |title=Horse of another color |agency=The Philadelphia Inquirer |publisher=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=2004}}</ref>\nHe again worked with Dellapenna in 2005 to create their painting ''On The Town'', which is 6x8ft with the hefty price tag of $12,500.<ref name=\"Gallery Philadelphia Art\">{{cite book |last1=Zeleniak |first1=James |title=Gallery Philadelphia Art |date=January 2005 |publisher=Wherer Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Philadelphia }}</ref>\n\n== Galleries ==\nAfter working and promoting himself outdoors for years in [[Rittenhouse Square]], Milou gained enough recognition and finance to open a gallery in the area. He saw initial potential in Philadelphia's market,<ref name=\"Will he stay or will he go now?\u201d\">{{cite book |last1=Midgley |first1=Brook |title=Will he stay or will he go now? |date=Fall 2005 |publisher=Sink Magazine |location=Philadelphia }}</ref> opening his first gallery in 2003. The eponymous ''Perry Milou Gallery'' served as an indoor studio and exhibition for people to visit after watching him paint outdoors for the previous four years.<ref name=\"Hot Tips Art Scene\" /> In 2005 he moved the gallery to a different location down the street.<ref name=\"Gallery Philadelphia Art\" /> Milou opened his third gallery ''Galleria 1903'' in 2007, continuing to showcase his personal work as well as other local artists.<ref name=\"Philly in a Day\">{{cite book |last1=Rosenberg |first1=Meredith |title=Philly in a Day |date=August 2007 |publisher=Where Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Philadelphia }}</ref>\nAfter years as a gallerist in Philadelphia, the businessman in Milou had him looking to other larger markets where more people would be willing to invest in quality artwork at higher price points.<ref name=\"Will he stay or will he go now?\u201d\" />\nAfter closing ''Galleria 1903'' and leaving Philadelphia, Milou moved to Miami where he opened his fourth gallery in May 2008.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> ''Milou Gallery'' was located in Miami's Wynwood Art District,<ref name=\"New Gallery Openings\">{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Irene |title=New Gallery Openings |date=July 2008 |publisher=Where Magazine, Morris Communications Company |location=Miami }}</ref> where Milou was hoping to capitalize on the art market that was fueled by the annual Art Basel showcase.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" />\n\n== Community/Philanthropy ==\nIn the late 90's during the very start of his career, Milou opened ''American Milou\u2019s Studio for Children'' in [[Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Hip To Be Square\" /> Through the 2000s\u2019 Milou was involved in philanthropic organizations such as Co-Founder of Philadelphia Art for ALS, the [[Susan G. Komen for the Cure|Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer Foundation]], an annual supporter of CVI, the Cardiovascular Institute of Philadelphia, MOCA Shakers and Gen. Art. In 2009 Milou provided a series of art workshops called \u201c''Palette Kids''\u201d while he was living in Miami, in collaboration with the [[Miami Children's Museum]].<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> Milou has sold several paintings in silent auctions and donated the proceeds to charitable organizations, including his own retrospective show in 2013 featuring 50 of his original paintings with proceeds donated to the Philadelphia Animal Welfare Society and One Fund Boston.<ref name=\"Milou Retrospective\">{{cite book |last1=Lidor |first1=Fryda |title=Milou Retrospective |date=Summer 2013 |publisher=Philadelphia Style Magazine, Niche Media Holdings |location=Philadelphia }}</ref> Another being the Second Annual Bubby's Cook-off in 2014 in which the proceeds went to the Friendship Circle Foundation.<ref name=\"The Second Annual Bubby\u2019s Cook-off\">{{cite book |last1=Dillon |first1=Hughe |title=The Second Annual Bubby's Cook-off |date=February 28, 2014 |publisher=Philadelphia Magazine |location=Philadelphia |url=https://www.phillymag.com/the-scene/2014/02/28/bubbys-cook-off-friendship-circle-lubavitch-bucks-county/#gallery-2-1 |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nMilou regularly worked and displayed his finished paintings in the corner of Rittenhouse Square until the Park Commission got involved in 2002. The Commission claimed receiving several complaints about Milou, and though Milou claimed he never transacted a sale inside the park, the Commission director said that was irrelevant and began to enforce the no-solicitation policy by initiating ranger patrols through the Square. Milou said he planned to continue painting in the park.<ref name=\"Rittenhouse Smackdown\">{{cite book |last1=Fiorillo |first1=Victor |title=Rittenhouse Smackdown |date=August 2002 |publisher=Philadelphia Magazine |location=Philadelphia |url=https://www.phillymag.com/ |accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMilou was raised in the [[Cheltenham Township, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Cheltenham]]-[[Mount Airy, Philadelphia|Mount Airy]] and [[Haverford Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Haverford]] suburbs near Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"City artist pictured four of team\u2019s greatest stars in latest work\" /> He graduated from the [[University of Arizona]],<ref name=\"Legendary Locals of Center City Philadelphia\" /> where he studied graphic design and illustration.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" /> While attending university, he was the first student to convince the Bachelor of Fine Arts program to include \u201copen studio\u201d as a major in 1990.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Originals\" /> After college he moved back to Philadelphia.<ref name=\"The Pope Visit 2015 Visit to Philadelphia\" /> Milou now resides in Pennsylvania with his wife, daughter and son.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milou, Perry}}\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:Pop artists]]\n[[Category:Painters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Artists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:American contemporary painters]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perry_Milou"}
{"title_page": "Seth Putnam", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Seth Putnam\n| image = Seth Putnam.jpg\n| image_size =\n| landscape  =\n| background = solo_singer \n| caption = Putnam in 2007\n| birth_name = Seth Edward Putnam\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1968|5|15|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Newton, Massachusetts|Newton]], [[Massachusetts]], United States\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2011|06|11|1968|5|15}}\n| origin =\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Grindcore]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n* [[hardcore punk]]\n}}\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n* [[Singing|Vocals]]\n* [[guitar]]\n* [[Bass guitar|bass]]\n* [[Drum kit|drums]]\n}}\n| occupation = Musician\n| years_active = 1986\u20132011\n| associated_acts = [[Anal Cunt]]\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* Wicked Sick\n* Limited Appeal\n* [[Earache Records]]\n}}\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Seth Edward Putnam''' (May 15, 1968 \u2013 June 11, 2011)<ref name=\"BMDead\">{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=159315 |title=Anal C**T Frontman Seth Putnam Dead At 43 |website=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=June 11, 2011 |accessdate=August 11, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614032943/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=159315 |archivedate=June 14, 2011}}</ref> was an American musician who was the founder, vocalist and occasional guitarist of [[grindcore]] band [[Anal Cunt]]. He was known for his high-pitched screamed vocals and lyrics that either shock, offend, or invoke [[black comedy|morbid humor]]. Throughout his career, Putnam was also involved in numerous side projects.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early years===\nPutnam was born on May 15, 1968, in [[Newton, Massachusetts]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/71292842 |title=Seth Edward Putnam |website=[[Find a Grave]] |accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> to father Edward R. Putnam and mother Barbara Ann Donohue. His parents are divorced. Seth was married to his first wife, Alison, from December 1998 through June 2001. He married Julie, his second wife, in 2008. In the mid-1980s, Putnam played bass in the [[thrash metal]] band [[Executioner (band)|Executioner]].\n\n===Personality===\nDespite his shock humor and turbulent lifestyle, Putnam was often described by fans and peers as a warm, intelligent, sensitive man. Putnam saw himself as a [[comedian]] and used music as an outlet.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.decibelmagazine.com/2011/06/28/seth-putnam-remembered/ |title=Seth Putnam Remembered |date=June 28, 2011 |first=Shawn |last=Macomber |magazine=[[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]] |accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn school, classmates who knew Putnam described him as intelligent and stern, but unmotivated, apathetic and often an underwhelming student. Putnam skipped a grade in school and became a very bright student, tutoring his classmates. In his own words, Putnam often blamed brutal fights with Catholic school nuns for helping to shape his cynical personality. When he reached high school after eighth grade, he had lost interest in excelling in education or academics, becoming more of a slacker and underachiever.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thegauntlet.com/article/467/20831/Seth-Putnam-from-Anal-Cunt-discusses-growing-up.html |title=Seth Putnam from Anal Cunt discusses growing up |date=January 5, 2011 |first=Jason |last=Fisher |website=The Gauntlet |accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> By the time he had graduated school, Putnam had left the Catholic religion in which he was raised. After graduation, Putnam showed no interest in attending college or university.\n\nThe 2019 grindcore documentary ''Slave to the Grind'' explores Putnam in detail, with his peers expressing the duality of his nature:<ref name=\"sttg\">{{Citation | title = Slave to the Grind | publisher = Death by Digital| year = 2019 | url = https://reelhouse.org/deathbydigital/slave-to-the-grind/slave-to-the-grind }}</ref> former bandmates Tim Morse and Scott Hull describe Putnam often being personable and relaxed, but Hull also notes that he'd often get arrested causing trouble on the street.<ref name=\"sttg\"/> [[Discordance Axis]] singer Jon Chang notes that he was really close to Putnam for years, but describes him as a \"really disturbed guy\" and a \"backstabbing piece of shit at the end of his life\". Chang also recounted an incident \nafter a show when Putnam introduced his mother to Chang, he remarked that they had met earlier when he pulled Putnam's mother out from the show's [[moshpit]], causing Putnam to become aggressive and threaten Chang, much to the confusion of everyone present.<ref name=\"sttg\"/> \nPutnam was also good friends with [[Pantera]] frontman, [[Phil Anselmo|Philip Anselmo]].\n\n===Drug overdose and coma===\nOn October 12, 2004 Putnam was hospitalized after ingesting a cocktail of [[crack-cocaine]], [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]], [[heroin]], and two months' worth of [[Ambien]] sleeping pills.<ref name=\"coma\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bostonphoenix.com/boston/music/cellars/documents/05023497.asp |title=Coma chameleon - Seth Putnam's near-death experience |first=Carly |last=Carioli |newspaper=[[Boston Phoenix]] |date=October 12, 2004 |accessdate=August 5, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051217193005/http://www.bostonphoenix.com/boston/music/cellars/documents/05023497.asp |archivedate=December 17, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It has been reported that he spent the previous day contemplating suicide,<ref name=\"coma\" /> though exact circumstances surrounding the drug overdose are vague.\n\nAnal Cunt's 1997 album ''I Like It When You Die'' contained the track \"You're in a Coma\". Putnam's reaction to the resulting irony of being in a coma was published in the ''[[Boston Phoenix]]'': \"Actually, it turned out it was just as gay as the song I wrote nine years ago \u2013 being in a coma was just as fuckin' stupid as I wrote it was.\"<ref name=\"coma\" /> Anal Cunt kept performing the song during live shows after the coma, with Putnam sharing anecdotes with the audience before the song.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n\n===Feud with Chris Barnes===\nThere was friction between Putnam and [[Six Feet Under (band)|Six Feet Under]] vocalist [[Chris Barnes (musician)|Chris Barnes]]. According to Putnam's defunct website, Putnam heckled Barnes during a Six Feet Under set, leading to an altercation between the two, ending with Six Feet Under's roadies ganging up on Putnam while Barnes fled to his tour bus and hid there. Putnam released the song \"[[It Just Gets Worse|Chris Barnes Is a Pussy]]\" as retaliation to the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wickedsickrecords.com/SP_FAQs.htm |title=Seth Putnam Frequently Asked ?'s |website=Wicked Sick Records |date=April 16, 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330181724/http://www.wickedsickrecords.com/SP_FAQs.htm |archivedate=March 30, 2009 |accessdate=August 11, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to Putnam in an interview with Capital Chaos TV several years later, Six Feet Under went out of their way to avoid playing in the same city as Anal Cunt several years after the incident. Putnam stated \"I guess he (Chris Barnes) is still afraid of me\". Despite the feud, Putnam stated that \"[[Bringer of Blood|Murdered in the Basement]]\" was his favorite song by Six Feet Under.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/anal-cunt-s-seth-putnam-chris-barnes-is-a-pussy/ |title=Anal Cunt's Seth Putnam: 'Chris Barnes Is A Pussy' |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=November 4, 2003 |accessdate=August 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn June 11, 2011, Putnam died of a suspected [[heart attack]] at the age of 43.<ref name=\"BMDead\" /><ref>{{cite news |first=Rosie |last=Swash |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/jun/13/seth-putnam-dies-aged-43 |title=Seth Putnam, the 'GG Allin of grindcore', dies aged 43  |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London, UK |date=June 13, 2011 |accessdate=August 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPutnam's grave is located within Newton Cemetery in Newton, Massachusetts.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Side projects and former bands==\n{{More citations needed section|date=September 2019}}\n\n====Angry Hate====\nThe idea of the band came up when Seth and Larry Lifeless (Kilslug vocalist) were drunk one night watching [[Jerry Springer]] and Larry said \"That guy looks like he should be in an old punk band called Angry Hate or something\".\nThe first recording was in January ,1999, of Larry hammering a fence against some lady's garage which was put on at the end of the song, \"M.P.\" on the first release. That summer, they recorded 4 songs. all of them were old Sickness songs. \"Blinking Blue Lights\" was actually recorded by Kilslug, but never released. The other songs that were done originally by the Sickness never got released either. They made another E.P. called \"Bad Mood\" that had a certain amount of copies pressed but were never officially released. Seth and Lee Suniga (owner of Menace To Sobriety Records) sold them on eBay. Angry Hate did 2 live shows in March and April of 2002.\n\n====Satan's Warriors====\nSatan's Warriors started in February of 1986 after Seth and his friends made up a fake death metal fanzine with fake band names as a joke, Seth eventually admitted to doing it, in April of that year. There was an opening for a band to play live over the radio so Seth got a lineup together and made a four-song demo with him on drums and vocals and his cousin Drew on guitar. Their final show was on July of 1988. They were supposed to get back together in 2003 and re-record some songs written between 1986 and 1988. The lineup was supposed to be with Seth on guitar & vocals, Paulie Kraynak on second guitar, and John Gillis on drums.\n\n====Impaled Northern Moonforest====\nIn early 1997, Seth and Josh Martin came up with the idea of starting a joke black metal band and decided to record a demo, they didn't use actual drums because someone was sleeping in the room next to them so Josh played his acoustic guitar while Seth did vocals and percussion by slapping his leg and a mattress, they did a few shows and sold copies of their first demo, the titles on the demo are different from the ones on the 7\" vinyl release due to Seth and Josh losing their copies of the demo and forgetting the titles.\n\n====Shit Scum====\nShit Scum formed in 1988 after Seth saw an ad looking for musicians, Seth chose to call after seeing Cryptic Slaughter as the only influence because not many people in Boston were into that band. Seth eventually invited Fred Ordonez to see Satan's Warriors (which was their last show), Anal Cunt was also playing what was supposed to be their last show but Fred and his friends never showed up, so Seth did another show with Anal Cunt so Fred could see them, Shit Scum also did their first show on the same day. Seth was eventually invited to a studio to play bass on their first demo called \"Self Mutilation\", they later did a show in 1990, Seth and Fred (without Wayne who was their drummer) went to a studio that college rock bands mainly performed at. The engineer didn't like them and tried convincing them to quit, the record was eventually finished and they ended up owing the studio money so the studio kept the master reel. Anal Cunt did a tour in Germany and did some Shit Scum covers. Matthias Weigand (head of Ecocentric Records) liked the cover of the song \"Shit Scum\" and wanted to put out a 7\". Seth called the studio and asked about the reel, the guy on the phone said \"it's right here, pick it up whenever you want\", not knowing they owed money to the studio. Seth mixed all the songs and sent them to Ecocentric Records. Fred never had a cover for the record so Matthias made one up. The record was eventually called \"Manson Is Jesus\". Fred wanted the record to be called, \"I Wish this Record Could Punch You in the Face\", and have a fist on the cover. Shit Scum had already broken up by the time the album was released.\n\n====Full Blown A.I.D.S.====\nFull Blown A.I.D.S. started in 1997 while he was jamming with his friend and cousin. In 1998 he wrote some songs and recorded a demo of \"No One Cares\" with Nate Linehan on drums. In 2002 he moved to Texas for a while but eventually moved back to Boston. In 2003 the band went into the studio and recorded some songs and mixed them in a day. They eventually put out two E.P's and put out a compilation CD in 2008<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/2062039-Full-Blown-AIDS|title=Full Blown AIDS|last=|first=|date=|website=Discogs|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> with both E.P's and the song \"Throwing Cars At People On Coke With Thor\".\n\n====Death's Head Quartet====\nThe Death's Head Quartet was a Jazz/Noise improv. band that featured Seth on bass and vocals, Chris Joyce on guitar, Robert Williams on drums, and Jim Hobbs on saxophone<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wickedsickrecords.com/SP_FAQs.htm#What%20are%20ALL%20the%20bands%20that%20Seth%20been%20involved%20with%20(including%20guest%20appearances)|title=SP FAQ's|website=www.wickedsickrecords.com|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>. Their first release was called \"Live on the Joint\" which was a radio broadcast from November 1, 2001. Their second release was recorded on April 9, 2001 and wasn't released until 2003.\n\n====Cuntsaw====\nCuntsaw started in 1989 with Seth on vocals and guitar and Tim Morse on drums. They usually practiced after Anal Cunt shows. They did one demo called \"Concerned\" and did one show at Brandeis University with Fred Ordonez on second guitar. They eventually broke up. The Anal Cunt Song \"Foreplay With A Tree Shredder\" was originally a Cuntsaw song that had a different title.\n\n====You're Fired====\nYou're Fired started in 2002. Within two months they had a nine-song demo recorded which eventually became the Warning E.P and was released in 2002. After Seth passed away, they made an E.P. called \"The End\" with Paulie Kraynak on guitar. Most of the riffs were written by Seth and the album was also recorded with Seth's Gibson SG and Marshall amplifier that were also used on the Warning E.P. \"The End\" was released in 2012 on vinyl and it also can be purchased on BandCamp along with the Warning E.P.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yourefiredboston.bandcamp.com/|title=The End (E.P.), by YOU'RE FIRED|website=YOU'RE FIRED|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n====Pantera====\nIn 1996, Putnam did guest vocals on [[Pantera]]'s [[The Great Southern Trendkill]] for their songs,\"The Great Southern Trendkill\", \"War Nerve\", \"13 Steps to Nowhere\", and \"Suicide Note Pt. II\".\n\n====Adolf Satan====\nAdolf Satan started in 2002 after Upsidedown Cross broke up. Seth played drums for the band for a brief period of time. He eventually quit and Nate Linehan joined. They recorded a demo in 2003 and eventually made a self-titled studio album. They recorded another demo in 2006 before breaking up two years later.\n\n*[[Upsidedown Cross (band)|Upsidedown Cross]] (note: Although Putnam is credited playing guitar on their split with Sloth, the album was actually recorded years before he joined the band)\n*[[Executioner (band)|Executioner]]\n*[[Post Mortem (Boston Band)|Post Mortem]]\n*[[Siege (band)|Siege]]\n\n====P.O.D.D.A. (Pile Of Drunks & Drug Addicts)====\nNot much is known about this band but they had only one recording session in 2007 which eventually surfaced onto YouTube, the band had Seth on vocals, [https://www.discogs.com/artist/2659376-Dejan-Podobnik Dejan Podobnik](Patareni, Millions of Dead Cops...) on drums and Chomi on guitar. Mickey Offender from D.R.I., Offenders,  was supposed to lay a bass track but it never happened.(rip)\n\n====Sirhan Sirhan====\nThis band started in December of 1990 and Seth and Tim Morse were trying to think of a christmas gift for Mike Mahan who recently moved to Indiana, they recorded a demo and got a band picture in a $2 photo booth. They sent it to Mike who eventually lost his copy, the demo was released as a split album with Cuntsaw.\n\n====Insult====\nInsult started in 1992 and decided to record an album in 1997, it was going horribly for them so they got Seth to come in and produce their album, the album was called \"I Wanna Be A Burn Victim\", Seth eventually became their bass player and did a west coast tour with them in 1998 as well as a live show over the radio which was released on a split with Anal Cunt, he quit in 1999.\n\n====Person Killer====\nPerson Killer was a one man project Seth started around 1995, he made a demo and sent it to Earache Records along with a t-shirt, a pin, and a letter that didn't reveal the sender's name. It was planned to be released on a two LP set called \"The Worst Of Seth Putnam\" but it hasn't been released.\n\n===Vaginal Jesus===\nRumors circulated as to whether or not Putnam was a member of Vaginal Jesus, originally stating that he was just \"friends\" with the band. However, he later retracted this claim and publicly admitted to being a member.<ref>Resistance magazine // issue no. 25, Winter 2005/2006</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623033415/http://www.racrecords.com/shop/magazines/resistance-magazine-issue-25-spring-2007/|title=Resistance Magazine Issue #25 Winter 2005 / 2006 \u2013 R.A.C. Records|date=23 June 2018|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.inm.acousticblackmetal.com/ Impaled Northern Moonforest]\n* [http://www.inm.acousticblackmetal.com/impaled_northern_moonforest/index.html previous Impaled Northern Moonforest site]\n* [http://wickedsickrecords.com/SP_FAQs.htm#What%20are%20ALL%20the%20bands%20that%20Seth%20been%20involved%20with%20(including%20guest%20appearances)]\n* [http://www.wickedsickrecords.com/bands.html]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ku7b-YCQW_A]\n{{Anal Cunt}}\n{{Siege}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Putnam, Seth}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:American punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:Grindcore]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Boston]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Seth Putnam\n| image = Seth Putnam.jpg\n| image_size =\n| landscape  =\n| background = solo_singer \n| caption = Putnam in 2007\n| birth_name = Seth Edward Putnam\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1968|5|15|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Newton, Massachusetts|Newton]], [[Massachusetts]], United States\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2011|06|11|1968|5|15}}\n| origin =\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Grindcore]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n* [[hardcore punk]]\n}}\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n* [[Singing|Vocals]]\n* [[guitar]]\n* [[Bass guitar|bass]]\n* [[Drum kit|drums]]\n}}\n| occupation = Musician\n| years_active = 1986\u20132011\n| associated_acts = [[Anal Cunt]]\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* Wicked Sick\n* Limited Appeal\n* [[Earache Records]]\n}}\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Seth Edward Putnam''' (May 15, 1968 \u2013 June 11, 2011)<ref name=\"BMDead\">{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=159315 |title=Anal C**T Frontman Seth Putnam Dead At 43 |website=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=June 11, 2011 |accessdate=August 11, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614032943/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=159315 |archivedate=June 14, 2011}}</ref> was an American musician who was the founder, vocalist and occasional guitarist of [[grindcore]] band [[Anal Cunt]]. He was known for his high-pitched screamed vocals and lyrics that either shock, offend, or invoke [[black comedy|morbid humor]]. Throughout his career, Putnam was also involved in numerous side projects.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early years===\nPutnam was born on May 15, 1968, in [[Newton, Massachusetts]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/71292842 |title=Seth Edward Putnam |website=[[Find a Grave]] |accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> to father Edward R. Putnam and mother Barbara Ann Donohue. His parents are divorced. Seth was married to his first wife, Alison, from December 1998 through June 2001. He married Julie, his second wife, in 2008. In the mid-1980s, Putnam played bass in the [[thrash metal]] band [[Executioner (band)|Executioner]].\n\n===Personality===\nDespite his shock humor and turbulent lifestyle, Putnam was often described by fans and peers as a warm, intelligent, sensitive man. Putnam saw himself as a [[comedian]] and used music as an outlet.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.decibelmagazine.com/2011/06/28/seth-putnam-remembered/ |title=Seth Putnam Remembered |date=June 28, 2011 |first=Shawn |last=Macomber |magazine=[[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]] |accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn school, classmates who knew Putnam described him as intelligent and stern, but unmotivated, apathetic and often an underwhelming student. Putnam skipped a grade in school and became a very bright student, tutoring his classmates. In his own words, Putnam often blamed brutal fights with Catholic school nuns for helping to shape his cynical personality. When he reached high school after eighth grade, he had lost interest in excelling in education or academics, becoming more of a slacker and underachiever.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thegauntlet.com/article/467/20831/Seth-Putnam-from-Anal-Cunt-discusses-growing-up.html |title=Seth Putnam from Anal Cunt discusses growing up |date=January 5, 2011 |first=Jason |last=Fisher |website=The Gauntlet |accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> By the time he had graduated school, Putnam had left the Catholic religion in which he was raised. After graduation, Putnam showed no interest in attending college or university.\n\nThe 2019 grindcore documentary ''Slave to the Grind'' explores Putnam in detail, with his peers expressing the duality of his nature:<ref name=\"sttg\">{{Citation | title = Slave to the Grind | publisher = Death by Digital| year = 2019 | url = https://reelhouse.org/deathbydigital/slave-to-the-grind/slave-to-the-grind }}</ref> former bandmates Tim Morse and Scott Hull describe Putnam often being personable and relaxed, but Hull also notes that he'd often get arrested causing trouble on the street.<ref name=\"sttg\"/> [[Discordance Axis]] singer Jon Chang notes that he was really close to Putnam for years, but describes him as a \"really disturbed guy\" and a \"backstabbing piece of shit at the end of his life\". Chang also recounted an incident \nafter a show when Putnam introduced his mother to Chang, he remarked that they had met earlier when he pulled Putnam's mother out from the show's [[moshpit]], causing Putnam to become aggressive and threaten Chang, much to the confusion of everyone present.<ref name=\"sttg\"/> \nPutnam was also good friends with [[Pantera]] frontman, [[Phil Anselmo|Philip Anselmo]].\n\n===Drug overdose and coma===\nOn October 12, 2004 Putnam was hospitalized after ingesting a cocktail of [[crack-cocaine]], [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]], [[heroin]], and two months' worth of [[Ambien]] sleeping pills.<ref name=\"coma\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bostonphoenix.com/boston/music/cellars/documents/05023497.asp |title=Coma chameleon - Seth Putnam's near-death experience |first=Carly |last=Carioli |newspaper=[[Boston Phoenix]] |date=October 12, 2004 |accessdate=August 5, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051217193005/http://www.bostonphoenix.com/boston/music/cellars/documents/05023497.asp |archivedate=December 17, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It has been reported that he spent the previous day contemplating suicide,<ref name=\"coma\" /> though exact circumstances surrounding the drug overdose are vague.\n\nAnal Cunt's 1997 album ''I Like It When You Die'' contained the track \"You're in a Coma\". Putnam's reaction to the resulting irony of being in a coma was published in the ''[[Boston Phoenix]]'': \"Actually, it turned out it was just as gay as the song I wrote nine years ago \u2013 being in a coma was just as fuckin' stupid as I wrote it was.\"<ref name=\"coma\" /> Anal Cunt kept performing the song during live shows after the coma, with Putnam sharing anecdotes with the audience before the song.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n\n===Feud with Chris Barnes===\nThere was friction between Putnam and [[Six Feet Under (band)|Six Feet Under]] vocalist [[Chris Barnes (musician)|Chris Barnes]]. According to Putnam's defunct website, Putnam heckled Barnes during a Six Feet Under set, leading to an altercation between the two, ending with Six Feet Under's roadies ganging up on Putnam while Barnes fled to his tour bus and hid there. Putnam released the song \"[[It Just Gets Worse|Chris Barnes Is a Pussy]]\" as retaliation to the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wickedsickrecords.com/SP_FAQs.htm |title=Seth Putnam Frequently Asked ?'s |website=Wicked Sick Records |date=April 16, 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330181724/http://www.wickedsickrecords.com/SP_FAQs.htm |archivedate=March 30, 2009 |accessdate=August 11, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to Putnam in an interview with Capital Chaos TV several years later, Six Feet Under went out of their way to avoid playing in the same city as Anal Cunt several years after the incident. Putnam stated \"I guess he (Chris Barnes) is still afraid of me\". Despite the feud, Putnam stated that \"[[Bringer of Blood|Murdered in the Basement]]\" was his favorite song by Six Feet Under.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/anal-cunt-s-seth-putnam-chris-barnes-is-a-pussy/ |title=Anal Cunt's Seth Putnam: 'Chris Barnes Is A Pussy' |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=November 4, 2003 |accessdate=August 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn June 11, 2011, Putnam died of a suspected [[heart attack]] at the age of 43.<ref name=\"BMDead\" /><ref>{{cite news |first=Rosie |last=Swash |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/jun/13/seth-putnam-dies-aged-43 |title=Seth Putnam, the 'GG Allin of grindcore', dies aged 43  |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London, UK |date=June 13, 2011 |accessdate=August 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPutnam's grave is located within Newton Cemetery in Newton, Massachusetts.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Side projects and former bands==\n{{More citations needed section|date=September 2019}}\n\n====Angry Hate====\nThe idea of the band came up when Seth and Larry Lifeless (Kilslug vocalist) were drunk one night watching [[Jerry Springer]] and Larry said \"That guy looks like he should be in an old punk band called Angry Hate or something\".\nThe first recording was in January ,1999, of Larry hammering a fence against some lady's garage which was put on at the end of the song, \"M.P.\" on the first release. That summer, they recorded 4 songs. all of them were old Sickness songs. \"Blinking Blue Lights\" was actually recorded by Kilslug, but never released. The other songs that were done originally by the Sickness never got released either. They made another E.P. called \"Bad Mood\" that had a certain amount of copies pressed but were never officially released. Seth and Lee Suniga (owner of Menace To Sobriety Records) sold them on eBay. Angry Hate did 2 live shows in March and April of 2002.\n\n====Satan's Warriors====\nSatan's Warriors started in February of 1986 after Seth and his friends made up a fake death metal fanzine with fake band names as a joke, Seth eventually admitted to doing it, in April of that year. There was an opening for a band\nto play live over the radio so Seth got a lineup together and made a 4 song demo with him on drums and vocals and his cousin Drew on guitar. Their final show was on July of 1988. They were supposed to get back together in 2003 and re-record some songs written between 1986 and 1988. The lineup was supposed to be with Seth on guitar & vocals, Paulie Kraynak on second guitar, and John Gillis on drums.\n\n====Impaled Northern Moonforest====\nIn early 1997, Seth and Josh Martin came up with the idea of starting a joke black metal band and decided to record a demo, they didn't use actual drums because someone was sleeping in the room next to them so Josh played his acoustic guitar while Seth did vocals and percussion by slapping his leg and a mattress, they did a few shows and sold copies of their first demo, the titles on the demo are different from the ones on the 7\" vinyl release due to Seth and Josh losing their copies of the demo and forgetting the titles.\n\n====Shit Scum====\nShit Scum formed in 1988 after Seth saw an ad looking for musicians, Seth chose to call after seeing Cryptic Slaughter as the only influence because not many people in Boston were into that band. Seth eventually invited Fred Ordonez to see Satan's Warriors (which was their last show), Anal Cunt was also playing what was supposed to be their last show but Fred and his friends never showed up, so Seth did another show with Anal Cunt so Fred could see them, Shit Scum also did their first show on the same day. Seth was eventually invited to a studio to play bass on their first demo called \"Self Mutilation\", they later did a show in 1990, Seth and Fred (without Wayne who was their drummer) went to a studio that college rock bands mainly performed at. The engineer didn't like them and tried convincing them to quit, the record was eventually finished and they ended up owing the studio money so the studio kept the master reel. Anal Cunt did a tour in Germany and did some Shit Scum covers. Matthias Weigand (head of Ecocentric Records) liked the cover of the song \"Shit Scum\" and wanted to put out a 7\". Seth called the studio and asked about the reel, the guy on the phone said \"it's right here, pick it up whenever you want\", not knowing they owed money to the studio. Seth mixed all the songs and sent them to Ecocentric Records. Fred never had a cover for the record so Matthias made one up. The record was eventually called \"Manson Is Jesus\". Fred wanted the record to be called, \"I Wish this Record Could Punch You in the Face\", and have a fist on the cover. Shit Scum had already broken up by the time the album was released.\n\n====Full Blown A.I.D.S.====\nFull Blown A.I.D.S. started in 1997 while he was jamming with his friend and cousin. In 1998 he wrote some songs and recorded a demo of \"No One Cares\" with Nate Linehan on drums. In 2002 he moved to Texas for a while but eventually moved back to Boston. In 2003 the band went into the studio and recorded some songs and mixed them in a day. They eventually put out two E.P's and put out a compilation CD in 2008<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/2062039-Full-Blown-AIDS|title=Full Blown AIDS|last=|first=|date=|website=Discogs|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> with both E.P's and the song \"Throwing Cars At People On Coke With Thor\".\n\n====Death's Head Quartet====\nThe Death's Head Quartet was a Jazz/Noise improv. band that featured Seth on bass and vocals, Chris Joyce on guitar, Robert Williams on drums, and Jim Hobbs on saxophone<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wickedsickrecords.com/SP_FAQs.htm#What%20are%20ALL%20the%20bands%20that%20Seth%20been%20involved%20with%20(including%20guest%20appearances)|title=SP FAQ's|website=www.wickedsickrecords.com|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>. Their first release was called \"Live on the Joint\" which was a radio broadcast from November 1, 2001. Their second release was recorded on April 9, 2001 and wasn't released until 2003.\n\n====Cuntsaw====\nCuntsaw started in 1989 with Seth on vocals and guitar and Tim Morse on drums. They usually practiced after Anal Cunt shows. They did one demo called \"Concerned\" and did one show at Brandeis University with Fred Ordonez on second guitar. They eventually broke up. The Anal Cunt Song \"Foreplay With A Tree Shredder\" was originally a Cuntsaw song that had a different title.\n\n====You're Fired====\nYou're Fired started in 2002. Within two months they had a nine-song demo recorded which eventually became the Warning E.P and was released in 2002. After Seth passed away, they made an E.P. called \"The End\" with Paulie Kraynak on guitar. Most of the riffs were written by Seth and the album was also recorded with Seth's Gibson SG and Marshall amplifier that were also used on the Warning E.P. \"The End\" was released in 2012 on vinyl and it also can be purchased on BandCamp along with the Warning E.P.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yourefiredboston.bandcamp.com/|title=The End (E.P.), by YOU'RE FIRED|website=YOU'RE FIRED|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n====Pantera====\nIn 1996, Putnam did guest vocals on [[Pantera]]'s [[The Great Southern Trendkill]] for their songs,\"The Great Southern Trendkill\", \"War Nerve\", \"13 Steps to Nowhere\", and \"Suicide Note Pt. II\".\n\n====Adolf Satan====\nAdolf Satan started in 2002 after Upsidedown Cross broke up. Seth played drums for the band for a brief period of time. He eventually quit and Nate Linehan joined. They recorded a demo in 2003 and eventually made a self-titled studio album. They recorded another demo in 2006 before breaking up two years later.\n\n*[[Upsidedown Cross (band)|Upsidedown Cross]] (note: Although Putnam is credited playing guitar on their split with Sloth, the album was actually recorded years before he joined the band)\n*[[Executioner (band)|Executioner]]\n*[[Post Mortem (Boston Band)|Post Mortem]]\n*[[Siege (band)|Siege]]\n\n====P.O.D.D.A. (Pile Of Drunks & Drug Addicts)====\nNot much is known about this band but they had only one recording session in 2007 which eventually surfaced onto YouTube, the band had Seth on vocals, [https://www.discogs.com/artist/2659376-Dejan-Podobnik Dejan Podobnik](Patareni, Millions of Dead Cops...) on drums and Chomi on guitar. Mickey Offender from D.R.I., Offenders,  was supposed to lay a bass track but it never happened.(rip)\n\n====Sirhan Sirhan====\nThis band started in December of 1990 and Seth and Tim Morse were trying to think of a christmas gift for Mike Mahan who recently moved to Indiana, they recorded a demo and got a band picture in a $2 photo booth. They sent it to Mike who eventually lost his copy, the demo was released as a split album with Cuntsaw.\n\n====Insult====\nInsult started in 1992 and decided to record an album in 1997, it was going horribly for them so they got Seth to come in and produce their album, the album was called \"I Wanna Be A Burn Victim\", Seth eventually became their bass player and did a west coast tour with them in 1998 as well as a live show over the radio which was released on a split with Anal Cunt, he quit in 1999.\n\n====Person Killer====\nPerson Killer was a one man project Seth started around 1995, he made a demo and sent it to Earache Records along with a t-shirt, a pin, and a letter that didn't reveal the sender's name. It was planned to be released on a two LP set called \"The Worst Of Seth Putnam\" but it hasn't been released.\n\n===Vaginal Jesus===\nRumors circulated as to whether or not Putnam was a member of Vaginal Jesus, originally stating that he was just \"friends\" with the band. However, he later retracted this claim and publicly admitted to being a member.<ref>Resistance magazine // issue no. 25, Winter 2005/2006</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623033415/http://www.racrecords.com/shop/magazines/resistance-magazine-issue-25-spring-2007/|title=Resistance Magazine Issue #25 Winter 2005 / 2006 \u2013 R.A.C. Records|date=23 June 2018|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.inm.acousticblackmetal.com/ Impaled Northern Moonforest]\n* [http://www.inm.acousticblackmetal.com/impaled_northern_moonforest/index.html previous Impaled Northern Moonforest site]\n* [http://wickedsickrecords.com/SP_FAQs.htm#What%20are%20ALL%20the%20bands%20that%20Seth%20been%20involved%20with%20(including%20guest%20appearances)]\n* [http://www.wickedsickrecords.com/bands.html]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ku7b-YCQW_A]\n{{Anal Cunt}}\n{{Siege}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Putnam, Seth}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:American punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:Grindcore]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Boston]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "NJZombie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSatan's Warriors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seth_Putnam"}
{"title_page": "David Pastorius", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=April 2015}}\n{{orphan|date=April 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n|  Name        = David Pastorius\n|  background  = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|  birth_place = [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], USA\n|  instrument  = Bass Guitar\n|  genre       = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[jazz fusion]], [[funk]], [[funk rock]]\n|  associated_acts = FHM, David Pastorius and Local 518, Elephant Gun, [[Tech N9ne]]\n|  website     = {{url|davidpastorius.com/}}.\n |}}\n\n'''David Pastorius''' is a bass guitarist born in [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], residing in [[Melbourne, Florida]], USA.<ref name=fbpo>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius Exclusive Interview|url=http://forbassplayersonly.com/interview-david-pastorius/|publisher=For Bass Players Only|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=14 July 2014}}</ref>  David is the nephew of world-renowned American jazz bassist [[Jaco Pastorius]].<ref name=fbpo/><ref name=ntreb1>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius: It's Not What You Think Interview|url=http://www.notreble.com/buzz/2009/12/10/david-pastorius-its-not-what-you-think/|publisher=NoTreble.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=10 December 2009|first1=Corey|last1=Brown}}</ref>\n\nDavid has played in numerous bands in the Florida region, has toured across the United States with various artists such as [[Tech N9ne]] and [[Pat Travers]], appeared in a number of bass guitar related magazines and has released and appeared on several studio albums.\n\nDavid spent the summer of 2019 playing with Carl Palmer's ELP Legacy on the Royal Affair Tour along with Yes, Asia and John Lodge of the Moody Blues. <ref>http://yesworld.com/2019/04/yes-announces-the-royal-affair-tour-launching-june-12-in-bethlehem-pa/</ref>\n\n==History==\nDavid started playing bass guitar at the age of 15<ref name=fbpo/> after being inspired by his high school friend, who had played the [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] cover version of [[Stevie Wonder]] song [[Higher Ground (Stevie Wonder song)|Higher Ground]] for him.<ref name=fbpo/><ref name=ntreb1/> At the age of 17, David joined his first band FHM (THE FLESHY HEADED MUTANTS) and began to play with local musicians performing Heavy Metal originals and cover songs.<ref name=fbpo/>\n\nDavid had performed on the album Jaco Pastorius Big Band Word of Mouth Revisited, a tribute to [[Jaco Pastorius]], released on August 23, 2003 by Ohio record label [[Heads Up International]].<ref name=cmg>{{cite web|title=Word Of Mouth Revisited Jaco Pastorius Big Band|url=http://www.concordmusicgroup.com/albums/Word-Of-Mouth-Revisited/|publisher=ConcordMusicGroup.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=26 August 2003}}</ref>  The album featured performances by David along with popular bassists [[Victor Bailey (musician)|Victor Bailey]], [[Richard Bona]], Jeff Carswell, [[Jimmy Haslip]], [[Christian McBride]], [[Marcus Miller]], [[Gerald Veasley]] and [[Victor Wooten]].<ref name=sost>{{cite web|title=Jaco Pastorius Big Band - Word Of Mouth Revisited|url=http://www.soundstage.com/music/reviews/rev545.htm|publisher=SoundStage.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=November 2003}}</ref><ref name=jazztimes>{{cite web|title=Jaco Pastorius Big Band Word Of Mouth Revisited|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/14339-word-of-mouth-revisited-jaco-pastorius-big-band|publisher=JazzTimes.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=December 2003}}</ref><ref name=cjazz>{{cite web|title=Review: Jaco Pastorius Big Band - Word of Mouth Revisited|url=http://www.contemporaryjazz.com/review-of-jaco-pastorius-big-band/|publisher=ContemporaryJazz.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=2003}}</ref><ref name=abjazz>{{cite web|title=Review: Jaco Pastorius Big Band: Word of Mouth Revisited (2003)|url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/jaco-pastorius-big-band-word-of-mouth-revisited-jaco-pastorius-heads-up-international-review-by-franz-a-matzner.php|publisher=AllAboutJazz.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=3 October 2003}}</ref>\n\nDavid formed the band, David Pastorius and Local 518, and released their debut self-titled album in the spring of 2007 on Japanese record label [[P-Vine Records]].<ref name=fbpo/><ref name=p-vine>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius & Local 518|url=http://p-vine.jp/artists/david-pastorius-local-518|publisher=P-Vine Records|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=ntreb2>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius & Local 518 Release Debut Album|url=http://www.notreble.com/buzz/2007/05/18/david-pastorius-local-518-release-debut-album/|publisher=NoTreble.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=18 May 2007|first1=Corey|last1=Brown}}</ref> In 2009, the band released their follow up album entitled Sense of Urgency.<ref name=ntreb1/><ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius & Local 518 Sense of Urgency|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/sense-of-urgency-mw0001963631|publisher=AllMusic.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=2009}}</ref><ref name=bassmumag>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius' New Album \"Sense of Urgency\"|url=http://bassmusicianmagazine.com/2009/12/david-pastorius%E2%80%99-new-album-%E2%80%9Csense-of-urgency%E2%80%9D/|publisher=BassMusicianMagazine.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=1 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, David joined the Southern punk/funk band Elephant Gun with Trevor Prince on guitar and vocals, and Tom Van Dyke on drums. The members had stemmed from local Florida bands Local 518, Goliath and Big Orange Nitty Gritty.  Elephant Gun hosted Wednesday night open mic events at Hustler Bar and Pool Room in the town of [[Indialantic, Florida]].<ref name=thebeachsideresident>{{cite web|title=Elephant Gun|url=http://thebeachsideresident.com/2009/12/elephant-gun/|publisher=thebeachsideresident.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=1 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225025551/http://thebeachsideresident.com/2009/12/elephant-gun/|archive-date=25 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=indablog>{{cite web|title=Indaba Members Compete to Play at NAMM|url=http://blog-archive.indabamusic.com/2011/06/elephantgun/|publisher=indabamusic.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=24 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225010518/http://blog-archive.indabamusic.com/2011/06/elephantgun/|archive-date=25 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On December 17, 2011 while playing a set at Off The Traxx Sports Bar in [[Melbourne, Florida]] with Elephant Gun, David had a heart attack.<ref name=romag>{{cite web|title=Rolling With a \"Band Of Psychos\"|url=http://www.rockeramagazine.com/mag/index.php/interviews/item/868-rolling-with-a-band-of-psychos|publisher=RockeraMagazine.com|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>  He had gone to the hospital after the show and had two stents placed in his arteries. On January 21, 2012, Baroos Beachside Bar in the town of [[Indialantic, Florida]], held a benefit concert to assist David and his family with his health issues. Six bands had played the event<ref name=321mag>{{cite web|title=Benefit For David Pastorius|url=http://321magazineonline.com/dpastorious-baroos-012112/|publisher=321magazineonline.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=21 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225013545/http://321magazineonline.com/dpastorious-baroos-012112/|archive-date=25 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2011 David performed live alongside drummer [[Keith LeBlanc]] and guitarist [[Eric Gales]] for the concert event Eric Gales + Voodoo Chile - A Tribute To Jimi Hendrix at the B.B. King Blues Club & Grill in New York City.<ref name=citygny>{{cite web|title=Eric Gales + Voodoo Chile - A Tribute To Jimi Hendrix|url=http://www.cityguideny.com/wireless/eventinfo.cfm?id=88466|publisher=CityGuideNY.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=31 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 and throughout 2014, David had started to record and film a series of video \"bass remixes\" of songs by one of his musical idols, American rapper, [[Tech N9ne]], and posted them on YouTube.<ref name=flto>{{cite web|title=Melbourne's Pastorius is all about that bass|url=http://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/local/2014/10/31/melbournes-pastorius-bass/18271015/|publisher=FloridaToday.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=31 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=ntreb3>{{cite web|title=Bass Remix: An Interview with David Pastorius|url=http://www.notreble.com/buzz/2014/07/03/bass-remix-an-interview-with-david-pastorius/|publisher=NoTreble.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=3 July 2014|first1=Kevin|last1=Johnson}}</ref>  Davids renditions caught the attention of Tech N9ne and his record label [[Strange Music]], in turn they requested David to perform a version of the Tech N9ne classic song \"This Ring\".<ref name=\"flto\"/><ref name=ntreb3/> Shortly afterward in the autumn of 2014, David joined Tech N9ne's \"Band Of Psychos\" for a brief tour including 13 shows on the west coast of the U.S.A.<ref name=\"romag\"/><ref name=\"flto\"/><ref name=fbpo2>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius on Tech N9ne and Marleaux basses|url=http://forbassplayersonly.com/news-features-david-pastorius-on-tech-n9ne-and-marleaux-basses/|publisher=ForBassPlayersOnly.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=26 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=stmuinc>{{cite web|title=Meet The Psychos - Bassist David Pastorius|url=http://www.strangemusicinc.com/2014/10/tech-n9ne/david-pastorius-band-of-psychos-interview/|publisher=StrangeMusicInc.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=22 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 David was asked to contribute to the documentary film, ''[[Jaco (film)|JACO: A Documentary Film]]'', produced and co-written by [[Metallica]] bassist [[Robert Trujillo]].<ref name=usatoday>{{cite web|title=Metallica's Robert Trujillo eager to spread 'Jaco' love|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/09/18/metallica-robert-trujillo-jaco-pastorius-documentary/15678819/|publisher=USAToday.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=22 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=jacothefilm>{{cite web|title=Jaco A Documentary Film|url=http://jacothefilm.com/filmmakers/|publisher=jacothefilm.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014215428/http://jacothefilm.com/filmmakers/|archive-date=14 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=imdb>{{cite web|title=Jaco|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2385115/|publisher=imdb.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=6 October 2014}}</ref>  David along with music artists Rodrigo y Gabriela, [[Chino Moreno]], and [[Tech N9ne]] are featured in a song during the credits at the films end.<ref name=\"romag\"/>  To assist in raising funds to complete the film, a campaign was started on crowd funding website [[PledgeMusic|Pledge Music]]; David offered 60 minute one on one video Skype lessons to help raise funds for the project.<ref name=pledgemusicjaco>{{cite web|title=Robert Trujillo Presents Jaco: A Documentary Film|url=http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/jacothefilm|publisher=PledgeMusic.com|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>  On October 6, 2014 David made an appearance at the Sweetwater Music Hall, in Mill Valley, California for a work-in-progress screening of the film and a special live performance with a variety of music artists.<ref name=sweetwatermusichall>{{cite web|title=A Musical Celebration honoring Jaco Pastorius|url=http://www.sweetwatermusichall.com/event/675603-musical-celebration-honoring-mill-valley/|publisher=sweetwatermusichall.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=mvff>{{cite web|title=A Musical Celebration of Jaco |url=http://www.mvff.com/musical-celebration-jaco/ |publisher=Mill Valley Film Festival |accessdate=24 February 2015 |date=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010002409/http://www.mvff.com/musical-celebration-jaco/ |archivedate=October 10, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=metallica>{{cite web|title=Artists In Residence|url=http://www.metallica.com/page.asp?ps_key=7967E279D0FE422B9CCB97C05F603B05|publisher=Metallica.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=13 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225035746/http://www.metallica.com/page.asp?ps_key=7967E279D0FE422B9CCB97C05F603B05|archive-date=25 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nPastorius is a fan of many genres but listens to a lot of hip hop, 1980s, and heavy metal. His influences include bass players Sam Griffith, [[Robert Trujillo]] (of [[Metallica]]), [[Flea (musician)|Flea]] (of [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]), [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] (of [[Iron Maiden]]), [[Les Claypool]] (of [[Primus (band)|Primus]]), and [[Mark King (musician)|Mark King]] (of [[Level 42]]). His musical hero is [[Mike Patton]] of [[Mr. Bungle]] and [[Faith No More]].<ref name=\"flto\"/>\n\n==Instruments==\nDavid plays Marleaux bass guitars,<ref name=fbpo2/><ref name=marleaux>{{cite web|title=Marleaux BassGuitars Artists|url=http://www.marleaux-bass.com/marleaux_artists.html|publisher=Marleaux-Bass.com|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref> a Classic Series Max-tone bass made by Artisan Bass Works<ref name=artisanbassworks>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius and his Classic Series Max-tone|url=http://www.artisanbassworks.com/products/classic-series-max-tone?variant=386980102|publisher=ArtisanBassworks.com|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref> and Hartke amps.<ref name=fbpo/>\n\n==Discography==\nLate 1990s - The Nature Kids\n\n===with David Pastorius and Local 518===\n:2007 - David Pastorius and Local 518 (P-Vine Records)\n:2009 - Sense of Urgency\n\n===Compilation albums===\n:2003 - Jaco Pastorius Big Band Word of Mouth Revisited (Heads Up International)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pastorius, David}}\n[[Category:Jazz fusion bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Melbourne, Florida]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Florida]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:American jazz bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=April 2015}}\n{{orphan|date=April 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n|  Name        = David Pastorius\n|  background  = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|  birth_place = [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], USA\n|  instrument  = Bass Guitar\n|  genre       = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[jazz fusion]], [[funk]], [[funk rock]]\n|  associated_acts = FHM, David Pastorius and Local 518, Elephant Gun, [[Tech N9ne]]\n|  website     = {{url|davidpastorius.com/}}.\n |}}\n\n'''David Pastorius''' is a bass guitarist born in [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], residing in [[Melbourne, Florida]], USA.<ref name=fbpo>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius Exclusive Interview|url=http://forbassplayersonly.com/interview-david-pastorius/|publisher=For Bass Players Only|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=14 July 2014}}</ref>  David is the nephew of world-renowned American jazz bassist [[Jaco Pastorius]].<ref name=fbpo/><ref name=ntreb1>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius: It's Not What You Think Interview|url=http://www.notreble.com/buzz/2009/12/10/david-pastorius-its-not-what-you-think/|publisher=NoTreble.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=10 December 2009|first1=Corey|last1=Brown}}</ref>\n\nDavid has played in numerous bands in the Florida region, has toured across the United States with various artists such as [[Tech N9ne]] and [[Pat Travers]], appeared in a number of bass guitar related magazines and has released and appeared on several studio albums.\n\nDavid spent the summer of 2019 playing with Carl Palmer's ELP Legacy on the Royal Affair Tour along with Yes, Asia and John Lodge of the Moody Blues. <ref>http://yesworld.com/2019/04/yes-announces-the-royal-affair-tour-launching-june-12-in-bethlehem-pa/</ref>\n\n==History==\nDavid started playing bass guitar at the age of 15<ref name=fbpo/> after being inspired by his high school friend, who had played the [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] cover version of [[Stevie Wonder]] song [[Higher Ground (Stevie Wonder song)|Higher Ground]] for him.<ref name=fbpo/><ref name=ntreb1/> At the age of 17, David joined his first band FHM (THE FLESHY HEADED MUTANTS) and began to play with local musicians performing Heavy Metal originals and cover songs.<ref name=fbpo/>\n\nDavid had performed on the album Jaco Pastorius Big Band Word of Mouth Revisited, a tribute to [[Jaco Pastorius]], released on August 23, 2003 by Ohio record label [[Heads Up International]].<ref name=cmg>{{cite web|title=Word Of Mouth Revisited Jaco Pastorius Big Band|url=http://www.concordmusicgroup.com/albums/Word-Of-Mouth-Revisited/|publisher=ConcordMusicGroup.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=26 August 2003}}</ref>  The album featured performances by David along with popular bassists [[Victor Bailey (musician)|Victor Bailey]], [[Richard Bona]], Jeff Carswell, [[Jimmy Haslip]], [[Christian McBride]], [[Marcus Miller]], [[Gerald Veasley]] and [[Victor Wooten]].<ref name=sost>{{cite web|title=Jaco Pastorius Big Band - Word Of Mouth Revisited|url=http://www.soundstage.com/music/reviews/rev545.htm|publisher=SoundStage.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=November 2003}}</ref><ref name=jazztimes>{{cite web|title=Jaco Pastorius Big Band Word Of Mouth Revisited|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/14339-word-of-mouth-revisited-jaco-pastorius-big-band|publisher=JazzTimes.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=December 2003}}</ref><ref name=cjazz>{{cite web|title=Review: Jaco Pastorius Big Band - Word of Mouth Revisited|url=http://www.contemporaryjazz.com/review-of-jaco-pastorius-big-band/|publisher=ContemporaryJazz.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=2003}}</ref><ref name=abjazz>{{cite web|title=Review: Jaco Pastorius Big Band: Word of Mouth Revisited (2003)|url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/jaco-pastorius-big-band-word-of-mouth-revisited-jaco-pastorius-heads-up-international-review-by-franz-a-matzner.php|publisher=AllAboutJazz.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=3 October 2003}}</ref>\n\nDavid formed the band, David Pastorius and Local 518, and released their debut self-titled album in the spring of 2007 on Japanese record label [[P-Vine Records]].<ref name=fbpo/><ref name=p-vine>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius & Local 518|url=http://p-vine.jp/artists/david-pastorius-local-518|publisher=P-Vine Records|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=ntreb2>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius & Local 518 Release Debut Album|url=http://www.notreble.com/buzz/2007/05/18/david-pastorius-local-518-release-debut-album/|publisher=NoTreble.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=18 May 2007|first1=Corey|last1=Brown}}</ref> In 2009, the band released their follow up album entitled Sense of Urgency.<ref name=ntreb1/><ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius & Local 518 Sense of Urgency|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/sense-of-urgency-mw0001963631|publisher=AllMusic.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=2009}}</ref><ref name=bassmumag>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius' New Album \"Sense of Urgency\"|url=http://bassmusicianmagazine.com/2009/12/david-pastorius%E2%80%99-new-album-%E2%80%9Csense-of-urgency%E2%80%9D/|publisher=BassMusicianMagazine.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=1 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, David joined the Southern punk/funk band Elephant Gun with Trevor Prince on guitar and vocals, and Tom Van Dyke on drums. The members had stemmed from local Florida bands Local 518, Goliath and Big Orange Nitty Gritty.  Elephant Gun hosted Wednesday night open mic events at Hustler Bar and Pool Room in the town of [[Indialantic, Florida]].<ref name=thebeachsideresident>{{cite web|title=Elephant Gun|url=http://thebeachsideresident.com/2009/12/elephant-gun/|publisher=thebeachsideresident.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=1 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225025551/http://thebeachsideresident.com/2009/12/elephant-gun/|archive-date=25 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=indablog>{{cite web|title=Indaba Members Compete to Play at NAMM|url=http://blog-archive.indabamusic.com/2011/06/elephantgun/|publisher=indabamusic.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=24 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225010518/http://blog-archive.indabamusic.com/2011/06/elephantgun/|archive-date=25 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On December 17, 2011 while playing a set at Off The Traxx Sports Bar in [[Melbourne, Florida]] with Elephant Gun, David had a heart attack.<ref name=romag>{{cite web|title=Rolling With a \"Band Of Psychos\"|url=http://www.rockeramagazine.com/mag/index.php/interviews/item/868-rolling-with-a-band-of-psychos|publisher=RockeraMagazine.com|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>  He had gone to the hospital after the show and had two stents placed in his arteries. On January 21, 2012, Baroos Beachside Bar in the town of [[Indialantic, Florida]], held a benefit concert to assist David and his family with his health issues. Six bands had played the event<ref name=321mag>{{cite web|title=Benefit For David Pastorius|url=http://321magazineonline.com/dpastorious-baroos-012112/|publisher=321magazineonline.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=21 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225013545/http://321magazineonline.com/dpastorious-baroos-012112/|archive-date=25 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2011 David performed live alongside drummer [[Keith LeBlanc]] and guitarist [[Eric Gales]] for the concert event Eric Gales + Voodoo Chile - A Tribute To Jimi Hendrix at the B.B. King Blues Club & Grill in New York City.<ref name=citygny>{{cite web|title=Eric Gales + Voodoo Chile - A Tribute To Jimi Hendrix|url=http://www.cityguideny.com/wireless/eventinfo.cfm?id=88466|publisher=CityGuideNY.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=31 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 and throughout 2014, David had started to record and film a series of video \"bass remixes\" of songs by one of his musical idols, American rapper, [[Tech N9ne]], and posted them on YouTube.<ref name=flto>{{cite web|title=Melbourne's Pastorius is all about that bass|url=http://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/local/2014/10/31/melbournes-pastorius-bass/18271015/|publisher=FloridaToday.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=31 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=ntreb3>{{cite web|title=Bass Remix: An Interview with David Pastorius|url=http://www.notreble.com/buzz/2014/07/03/bass-remix-an-interview-with-david-pastorius/|publisher=NoTreble.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=3 July 2014|first1=Kevin|last1=Johnson}}</ref>  Davids renditions caught the attention of Tech N9ne and his record label [[Strange Music]], in turn they requested David to perform a version of the Tech N9ne classic song \"This Ring\".<ref name=\"flto\"/><ref name=ntreb3/> Shortly afterward in the autumn of 2014, David joined Tech N9ne's \"Band Of Psychos\" for a brief tour including 13 shows on the west coast of the U.S.A.<ref name=\"romag\"/><ref name=\"flto\"/><ref name=fbpo2>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius on Tech N9ne and Marleaux basses|url=http://forbassplayersonly.com/news-features-david-pastorius-on-tech-n9ne-and-marleaux-basses/|publisher=ForBassPlayersOnly.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=26 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=stmuinc>{{cite web|title=Meet The Psychos - Bassist David Pastorius|url=http://www.strangemusicinc.com/2014/10/tech-n9ne/david-pastorius-band-of-psychos-interview/|publisher=StrangeMusicInc.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=22 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 David was asked to contribute to the documentary film, ''[[Jaco (film)|JACO: A Documentary Film]]'', produced and co-written by [[Metallica]] bassist [[Robert Trujillo]].<ref name=usatoday>{{cite web|title=Metallica's Robert Trujillo eager to spread 'Jaco' love|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/09/18/metallica-robert-trujillo-jaco-pastorius-documentary/15678819/|publisher=USAToday.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=22 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=jacothefilm>{{cite web|title=Jaco A Documentary Film|url=http://jacothefilm.com/filmmakers/|publisher=jacothefilm.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014215428/http://jacothefilm.com/filmmakers/|archive-date=14 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=imdb>{{cite web|title=Jaco|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2385115/|publisher=imdb.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=6 October 2014}}</ref>  David along with music artists Rodrigo y Gabriela, [[Chino Moreno]], and [[Tech N9ne]] are featured in a song during the credits at the films end.<ref name=\"romag\"/>  To assist in raising funds to complete the film, a campaign was started on crowd funding website [[PledgeMusic|Pledge Music]]; David offered 60 minute one on one video Skype lessons to help raise funds for the project.<ref name=pledgemusicjaco>{{cite web|title=Robert Trujillo Presents Jaco: A Documentary Film|url=http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/jacothefilm|publisher=PledgeMusic.com|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>  On October 6, 2014 David made an appearance at the Sweetwater Music Hall, in Mill Valley, California for a work-in-progress screening of the film and a special live performance with a variety of music artists.<ref name=sweetwatermusichall>{{cite web|title=A Musical Celebration honoring Jaco Pastorius|url=http://www.sweetwatermusichall.com/event/675603-musical-celebration-honoring-mill-valley/|publisher=sweetwatermusichall.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=mvff>{{cite web|title=A Musical Celebration of Jaco |url=http://www.mvff.com/musical-celebration-jaco/ |publisher=Mill Valley Film Festival |accessdate=24 February 2015 |date=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010002409/http://www.mvff.com/musical-celebration-jaco/ |archivedate=October 10, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=metallica>{{cite web|title=Artists In Residence|url=http://www.metallica.com/page.asp?ps_key=7967E279D0FE422B9CCB97C05F603B05|publisher=Metallica.com|accessdate=24 February 2015|date=13 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225035746/http://www.metallica.com/page.asp?ps_key=7967E279D0FE422B9CCB97C05F603B05|archive-date=25 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nPastorius is a fan of many genres but listens to a lot of hip hop, 80's, and heavy metal. His influences include bass players Sam Griffith, [[Robert Trujillo]] (of [[Metallica]]), [[Flea (musician)|Flea]] (of [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]), [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] (of [[Iron Maiden]]), [[Les Claypool]] (of [[Primus (band)|Primus]]), and [[Mark King (musician)|Mark King]] (of [[Level 42]]). His musical hero is [[Mike Patton]] of [[Mr. Bungle]] and [[Faith No More]].<ref name=\"flto\"/>\n\n==Instruments==\nDavid plays Marleaux bass guitars,<ref name=fbpo2/><ref name=marleaux>{{cite web|title=Marleaux BassGuitars Artists|url=http://www.marleaux-bass.com/marleaux_artists.html|publisher=Marleaux-Bass.com|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref> a Classic Series Max-tone bass made by Artisan Bass Works<ref name=artisanbassworks>{{cite web|title=David Pastorius and his Classic Series Max-tone|url=http://www.artisanbassworks.com/products/classic-series-max-tone?variant=386980102|publisher=ArtisanBassworks.com|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref> and Hartke amps.<ref name=fbpo/>\n\n==Discography==\nLate 90's - The Nature Kids\n\n===with David Pastorius and Local 518===\n:2007 - David Pastorius and Local 518 (P-Vine Records)\n:2009 - Sense of Urgency\n\n===Compilation albums===\n:2003 - Jaco Pastorius Big Band Word of Mouth Revisited (Heads Up International)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pastorius, David}}\n[[Category:Jazz fusion bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Melbourne, Florida]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Florida]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:American jazz bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Pastorius"}
{"title_page": "Billy Foster", "text_new": "{{for|American television director|Bill Foster (director)}}\n{{Infobox NASCAR driver\n| name               = William \"Billy\" Foster\n| image              =\n| caption            =\n| birth_name         = William A. Foster\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1937|09|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1967|01|20|1937|09|18}}\n| death_place        = [[Riverside, California]], U. S.\n| death_cause        = Race accident\n| height             =  <!-- \"X ft Y in\" or \"X cm\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| weight             =  <!-- \"X lb\", \"X kg\" or \"X st Y lb\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| achievements       =\n| awards             =\n| Total_Cup_Races    = 1 <!-- Strictly Stock Series, Grand National Series, Winston Cup Series, Nextel Cup Series, Sprint Cup Series, Monster Energy Cup Series -->\n| Years_In_Cup       = 1\n| Cup_Car_Team       = No. 22 (Rudy Hoerr)\n| Prev_Cup_Pos       =\n| Prev_Cup_Year      =\n| Best_Cup_Pos       =\n| First_Cup_Race     = [[1966 NASCAR Grand National Series|1966]] [[Winston Western 500|Motor Trend 500]] ([[Riverside International Raceway|Riverside]])\n| Last_Cup_Race      =\n| First_Cup_Win      =\n| Last_Cup_Win       =\n| Cup_Wins           = 0\n| Cup_Top_Tens       = 1\n| Cup_Poles          = 0\n| module        =\n{{Infobox Champ Car driver|embed=yes\n| Total_Champ_Races  = 27\n| Years_In_Champ     = 3\n| Years              = [[1964 USAC Championship Car season|1964]]-[[1966 USAC Championship Car season|1966]]\n| Champ_Car_Team     = Jim Robbins\n| Champ_Wins         = 0\n| Champ_Podiums      = ?\n| Champ_Poles        = 0\n}}\n}}\n'''William A. Foster''' (September 18, 1937 &ndash; January 20, 1967) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[Auto racing|racecar driver]].\n\nBorn in [[Victoria, British Columbia]], Foster died in a crash during practice for a [[NASCAR]] [[Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series|Grand National]] stock car race at [[Riverside International Raceway]] in [[Riverside, California]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Crash is fatal to Foster|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ve1RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=aXQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5217%2C291419|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|date=January 21, 1967|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\nFoster won the 1963 CAMRA (Canadian American Modified Racing Association) in 1963 in the first year of the series. He also won the Utah Copper Cup race in 1963 and 1964.\n\nFoster also drove in the [[United States Auto Club|USAC]] [[Championship Car]] series, racing in the 1964-1966 seasons, with 28 career starts, including the 1965 and 1966 [[Indianapolis 500]] races.  He finished in the top ten 10 times, with his best finish in 2nd position in 1966 at [[Lakewood Speedway|Atlanta]].\n\nFoster and [[Mario Andretti]] became best of friends, building a close relationship which Andretti claimed he would never do again with a fellow racer because Foster's death so significantly affected him.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nFoster ran a [[NASCAR Cup Series]] race at [[Riverside International Raceway]] in [[1966 NASCAR Grand National Series|1966]] and finished 7th. He died in a practice for NASCAR race at Riverside in the following year. He also competed in 2 [[NASCAR West Series]] races in 1965.\n\nFoster was cousins with musician, producer, composer, arranger [[David Foster]] and with Canadian stock car driver Jim Steen.\n\nHe was inducted into the [[Canadian Motorsport Hall of Fame]] in 1993.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Canadians in NASCAR]]\n*[[List of Canadians in Champ Car]]\n*[[Canadian Motorsport Hall of Fame]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Racing-Reference driver|Billy_Foster}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080517170519/http://www.victoriaautoracinghalloffame.com/billyfoster/billyfoster.html Victoria Auto Racing Hall of Fame entry]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081010125318/http://www.indy500.com/stats/driver/Billy_Foster Indianapolis 500 Career Stats]\n* [http://www.motorsportmemorial.org/focus.php?db=ct&n=464 Motor Sport Memorial entry]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110209123027/http://cmhf.ca/member_BILLY_FOSTER.html Canadian Motor Sports Hall of Fame]\n* [https://speedsport.com/racing-history/camra-played-key-role-in-open-wheel-racing-history/]\n* [https://www.newspapers.com/image/30007807/?terms=billy%2Bfoster%2Bwins%2Bcopper%2Bcup]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foster, Billy}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Victoria, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis 500 drivers]]\n[[Category:NASCAR drivers]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers killed while racing]]\n[[Category:Sports deaths in California]]\n\n{{Canada-autoracing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|American television director|Bill Foster (director)}}\n{{Infobox NASCAR driver\n| name               = William \"Billy\" Foster\n| image              =\n| caption            =\n| birth_name         = William A. Foster\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1937|09|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1967|01|20|1937|09|18}}\n| death_place        = [[Riverside, California]], U. S.\n| death_cause        = Race accident\n| height             =  <!-- \"X ft Y in\" or \"X cm\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| weight             =  <!-- \"X lb\", \"X kg\" or \"X st Y lb\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| achievements       =\n| awards             =\n| Total_Cup_Races    = <!-- Strictly Stock Series, Grand National Series, Winston Cup Series, Nextel Cup Series, Sprint Cup Series, Monster Energy Cup Series -->\n| Years_In_Cup       =\n| Cup_Car_Team       =\n| Prev_Cup_Pos       =\n| Prev_Cup_Year      =\n| Best_Cup_Pos     